<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BARTStrike 3rdLd-Writethru a0796 09-26 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BART Strike, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0796,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Reached With San Francisco Commuter Rail
Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with ratification vote set for Wednesday,
quotes from union officials; Waalkens cq in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union officials and Bay Area Rapid
Transit authorities reached a tentative contract settlement Sunday
on the eve of a threatened strike that would affect about 100,000
commuters on the 71-mile train line.
   ``Both sides compromised and compromised, and then we met _ sort
of happily _ in the middle,'' said Suzanne Angeli, vice president
of Public Employees Union Local 790.
   Union negotiators and BART officials held face-to-face talks
throughout the weekend with a state mediator before a settlement
was reached late Sunday afternoon. The agreement was announced at a
joint news conference Sunday evening.
   A ratification vote is set for Wednesday, and Local 790
President Milt Waalkens predicted approval.
   ``I think they will be as happy as they can be with what we've
gotten,'' he said.
   Details of the tentative settlement were not released.
   A strike had been called for Monday morning after 1,200
janitors, maintenance workers and clerks rejected a contract offer
last week. As negotiations took place Sunday, agency managers were
being trained in operations of the train system, BART spokesman Sy
Mouber said.
   A wildcat strike threatened for Sunday by union representatives
angry about the training did not materialize, Mouber said. BART
hoped the training would enable it to operate about half its normal
service Monday with the use of 42 management employees.
   Another union, which represents 500 station agents and train
operators had agreed to a contract with BART but promised to honor
Local 790's picket lines. Those lines had been scheduled to form at
6 a.m. Monday at 34 stations.
   The disputed contract proposals involved profits from retirement
fund investments, union activity during work hours, sick leave
restrictions and overtime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
