<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-UnitedNations Bjt   09-26 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-United Nations, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's U.N. Speech Focuses on World View</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top expected before 9:15 a.m. EDT based on text of speech</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan promised to outline his view
of what lies ahead for the world as he went before the United
Nations today for his seventh appearance and his last before
leaving office.
   Asked as he returned from a weekend at Camp David, Md., on
Sunday whether he was looking forward to his annual visit for the
opening of the General Assembly in New York, the president answered
with a single word: ``Yes.''
   An official who spoke on the condition of anonymity said over
the weekend that Reagan would deal in his speech with the thorny
issue of chemical weapons, which the United States and many other
Western nations manufacture.
   The president's national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin L.
Powell, predicted last week that the president also would press
efforts to stem the proliferation of such weapons in individual
talks with world leaders.
   Reagan has addressed the opening session of the General Assembly
each year since 1983. He also spoke at a special U.N. session on
disarmament in 1982.
   In his weekly radio speech Saturday, the president said he would
talk today about his administration's record of ``successes for our
philosophy of peace through strength.''
   ``The great question now is, what next?'' he added. ``Where does
the world go in the next eight years and the next 80 years? What
are the steps we might take toward a safer, better, freer world?
And I'll have some thoughts of my own on Monday.''
   ``One thing is certain,'' he said. `If we're to continue to
advance world peace and human freedom, America must remain strong.
We must turn a deaf ear to those born-again patriots who talk about
strength while serving up the same old menu of weakness.''
   The president didn't say whom he was talking about, but the
words were similar to those he has used to describe the campaign of
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   After his speech, the president planned to meet with U.N.
Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar; with senior advisers at
the U.S. mission to the United Nations; with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres; with President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe; with Sheik Sabah
Al-Ahmed, foreign minister of Kuwait; and with members of the
Persian Gulf Cooperation Council.
   Powell told reporters the United States is ``committed to a
comprehensive, worldwide ban on chemical weapons'' and he expected
Reagan to ``press the issue'' in his talks.
   Both Iran and Iraq used chemical weapons in their eight-year
Persian Gulf war. In addition, the United States has accused Iraq
of using poison gas against its Kurdish minority.
   It will be Reagan's first meeting with Perez de Cuellar since
the White House's announcement on Sept. 13 that the president was
releasing $188 million the United States had withheld from the
organization to show displeasure with U.N. budgetary and hiring
practices.
   Powell said the United Nations had responded to U.S. suggestions
by making changes in its budget procedures and the size of its
staff and that the president wanted to recognize this as well as
the fact that the organization ``has started to play a more
important role around the world in helping to deal with regional
conflicts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
