<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SiberianMigration     09-26 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Siberian Migration,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Exhibit Showcases Rare Alaskan Artifacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Spencer Fullerton Baird sent a team of
scientists to Russian Alaska in 1865, he expected them to return to
the Smithsonian Institution with samples of birds, animals and
Eskimo artifacts.
   They brought back all that, as well as evidence of mineral
wealth that helped persuade a reluctant Congress two years later to
spend $7.2 million to buy Alaska from the Russian czar. ``Seward's
Folly'' it was called, after William Henry Seward, who was then
secretary of state.
   Many of the samples collected in those and later expeditions,
including some native American hunting cloaks of astounding beauty,
have gone on display at a joint U.S.-Soviet exhibit that also
features samples collected by 18th century Russian pioneers but
never before shown. The exhibit is at the Smithsonian's Museum of
Natural History.
   ``This is a story that no one country can tell,'' said William
Fitzhugh, curator of the show, which is the fruit of a decade of
planning and cooperation between American and Soviet
anthropologists.
   The exhibit, ``Crossroads of Continents: Cultures of Siberia and
Alaska,'' also highlights recent scientific findings about the
migration of people across the Bering Strait 11,000 years to 12,000
years ago and the development of native American culture in the far
Northwest.
   And now, 121 years after Alaska was sold for a song, Russian
scholars flocked to the Smithsonian last week for a series of
seminars on the links between ethnic groups in Far Eastern Siberia
and the Eskimo, Aleut, Athapaskan, Eyak and Tlingit peoples of
Alaska and northwestern Canada.
   ``So we learn that the Smithsonian played a leading role in
convincing Congress in the 19th century to buy Alaska,'' said
Aleksandr Potemkin, cultural attache at the Soviet Embassy in
Washington.
   ``It is the same Smithsonian Institution that is playing a
leading role in bringing the neighbors together again,'' he said.
   The exhibition, part of increased cultural cooperation between
the superpowers, breaks new ground in several respects.
   It provides Western scholars with their first look at examples
of Eskimo and Tlingit art collected for the czars by explorers like
Vitus Bering, and by scientists and Russian traders who settled as
far south as San Francisco. Many of the objects have been stored
out of public sight in the Museum of Anthropology and Ethnography,
the oldest museum in the Soviet Union, founded in what is now
Leningrad by Peter the Great in 1714.
   In another first, after the exhibition tours the United States,
with stops in Seattle, New York, Indianapolis and Anchorage, it
will go to Ottawa, Canada, and then to Moscow, Leningrad and two
Soviet cities yet to be chosen.
   The rich collection of clothes, hunting devices and other
utensils on display testify to the links between the native
cultures of Siberia and Alaska, and also the differences.
   Many of the Siberian peoples, said Fitzhugh, learned to raise
herds of reindeer. That form of life involves a more complex social
structure than that of the Alaska peoples, who remained largely
hunter-gatherers.
   ``The hunters had a spiritual relation with the animals that
were their prey,'' said Fitzhugh. And when they hunted, they wore
their best clothes, including one elaborate cloak sewn of gut and
decorated with cormorant feathers, Fitzhugh's favorite object in
the exhibit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MetOpening     09-26 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Met Opening,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opera Season Opens With War Horse; Real Excitement Lies Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Opera's 105th season may be
opening with something of a musical whimper, but it promises to end
with a bang.
   The gold curtain will rise tonight on a production of Verdi's
``Il Trovatore'' that, when it premiered last season, provoked some
of the most scathing critical catcalls in recent memory.
   When the season ends in May, it will be with a musical event of
historic proportions _ three performances of Wagner's four-opera
Ring Cycle, not seen in its entirety at the Met for a generation.
   In between are a number of promising evenings _ starting with
the second night of the season when Handel's ``Giulio Cesare'' will
be presented at the Met for the first time. Kathleen Battle and
Tatyana Troyanos will star, along with Jeffrey Gall, the first
countertenor ever to sing at the Met.
   The Handel masterpiece will be conducted by Trevor Pinnock, the
British early music specialist who not only has never conducted at
the Met before but has never conducted any opera before. He will be
leading an orchestra of about 30 players, unusually small for the
Met pit.
   By contrast, there is little new or unusual about ``Il
Trovatore.'' Met artistic director James Levine will conduct an
all-star cast that includes Luciano Pavarotti, Eva Marton and
Sherrill Milnes, but whether they can overcome the dreary staging
remains to be seen.
   ``Normally it takes a new opera production years to decline to
the point of terminal weariness and ineptitude, but the
Metropolitan Opera's `Trovatore' reached that sad state in one
evening,'' New York Times chief music critic Donal Henahan wrote
after the premiere last fall.
   Of Fabrizio Melano's production, Henahan said, ``The idea that
anyone actually directed the solo singers or the chorus strained
belief.'' Ezio Frigerio's sets, he wrote, ``consisted mostly of six
groups of marbleized pillars that moved about for reasons known
perhaps only to the designer.''
   Despite this and other pans, most upcoming performances of
``Trovatore'' have been sold out for weeks. That includes opening
night, when tickets cost up to $1,000, a price that entitles the
holder to attend a post-opera party. Total gross revenues from the
evening will come to $629,000.
   ``Gradually, we're making opening night into the gala social
event it was 25 years ago,'' explained Met spokeswoman Johanna
Fiedler. ``If you approach it that way, then it makes sense to do
something like Verdi that is popular with the kind of audience that
goes to galas.''
   A key ingredient of success for such a gala seems to be the
presence of either Pavarotti or the world's other leading operatic
tenor, Placido Domingo. One or the other has starred in five out of
the last six opening nights, and Domingo will be on hand when the
Met puts on another gala in December _ a new production of Verdi's
``Aida.''
   The three Ring Cycles that will climax the season represent the
fulfillment of a longtime dream for Levine, restoring to the
repertory for the first time since the early 1970s one of the
crowning works of opera. The production by Otto Schenk has sets and
projections by Guenther Schneider-Siemssen that combine an
old-fashioned literalism with modern technology. The cast, led by
Hildegarde Behrens as Bruennhilde, is about the best available in
today's impoverished world of Wagnerian singing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrailleGreetings     09-26 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Braille Greetings,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greeting Card Designer Wants To Bridge Gap Between Blind And
Sighted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With something as simple as a greeting
card, Truesillia Ruth Shank hopes to help bridge the gap between
the worlds of the sighted and the blind.
   ``It seems so unfair that a blind person should miss out on the
simple, little pleasures of life,'' said Mrs. Shank, sitting in the
living room of her modest home that doubles as the office for her
7-month-old card company, Sucurre Greetings. Sucurre is an Old
French word meaning ``to assist.''
   ``Can you imagine being 30, 40 or 50 years old and having to
wait for someone to read a stack of Christmas cards to you? Or not
being able to go into a store and pick out an anniversary card for
your wife or a birthday card for your child?'' she asked.
   The inspiration for Sucurre Greetings, which Mrs. Shank owns
with her husband, came while she was working on an advertising
project with a blind businessman.
   ``He was doing things I couldn't do even with my sight,'' she
said. ``It just didn't seem right that he needed someone to go to a
store with him just to pick out a card.''
   Because of the limited market, Braille greeting cards have not
been manufactured by established card companies, said Adam Ash,
publisher of the Gift Reporter, a trade publication for the gift
industry. Some rehabilitation agencies have been known to sell some
Braille cards at Christmas, and others translate greeting cards to
Braille when requested.
   ``At best, what you've been able to get up until now is a card
for a sighted person that's been Brailled. These cards are designed
specifically for a visually impaired person, but are still
appealing to a sighted person as well,'' said Paul Ponchillia, a
professor in the Department of Blind Rehabilitation at Western
Michigan University.
   Ponchillia, who is blind, helped the Shanks design the cards.
   The Shanks, also co-owners of a year-old advertising and
printing company, hope the pastel colors and simple but elegant
designs embossed on the front of the cards will appeal to a wide
audience. Underneath the design is a description of the object in
Braille. Inside, Braille appears under the message, typically a
short phrase with slightly raised letters.
   One lavender card has an embossed bird in flight on the cover.
Inside, the message is ``My heart's all a-flutter.''
   In addition to her basic line of 25 cards, Mrs. Shank said she
also has a line of Christmas cards.
   ``We want the person to get the full impact of the card _ a card
that everyone can enjoy,'' said Mrs. Shank, a bubbly, 32-year-old
mother of three.
   She does the embossing by hand. Her husband, Michael, art
director at a television station, does much of the designing and
printing. Most of the Brailling is done by blind volunteers.
   Distribution of the cards is mostly limited to local card shops,
but Mrs. Shank says she fills mail orders and is trying to line up
distributors for the cards in other parts of the country. The cards
sell for $2 and $2.50 locally.
   If the cards catch on, the Shanks would like to provide jobs for
blind rehabilitation and training groups.
   And it looks as if the cards may be catching on. Marshall Field
has expressed interest in buying the line for their chain of
department stores, as well as an alphabet book Mrs. Shank designed
for use by both sighted and blind children.
   ``Before getting involved in this, I never really knew a blind
person and I don't think I ever remember seeing a book that's shown
me what Braille's like,'' she said.
   ``We planned the book to get rid of the gap between sighted and
blind children. We want a sighted child to know what Braille feels
like and a blind child to be able to feel the letters that we're
seeing. Maybe that way we can get rid of some of the prejudice.''
   Prejudice is a subject Mrs. Shank knows well.
   ``Because I'm black, some people might ask why I'm not doing
something for a black cause. Well, blindness knows no color. When
people stop being prejudiced against blind people or handicapped
people, maybe they'll stop being prejudiced about black people,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito-News     09-26 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito-News,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frustration Over Lack of Information, Conflicting Reports On
Emperor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Emperor Hirohito lies in his sickbed, a lack of
information and conflicting reports on his health are provoking
frustration and concern.
   The Imperial Household Agency's stubborn reluctance to release
detailed information about the monarch is drawing increasingly
strong criticism.
   ``I am getting the strong impression that the emperor's real
condition may be much worse than what's been reported,'' said Naoki
Inose, author of several books on the imperial family. ``Only a
handful of doctors, nurses and servants actually get to see the
emperor other than those in the imperial family.''
   The Imperial Household Agency, which handles all matters
concerning the monarchy, has been releasing only the emperor's
temperature, blood pressure and pulse three to four times a day
along with a brief comment about his condition.
   ``What we are interested in is how the emperor is really doing,
not those medical numbers,'' said a middle-aged man who came to the
palace Sunday to sign his name in a registry of well-wishers. ``His
condition is everyone's interest.''
   A reporter for a nationally circulated newspaper said the
Imperial Household Agency had its ``own standards about the news,
which apparently differ considerably from today's ordinary
standard.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's second largest circulation newspaper,
said Saturday that the emperor apparently has cancer. It quoted
pathologists who examined tissue taken from the emperor's pancreas
when he underwent intestinal bypass surgery last September as
saying ``cancer cells were found in the tissue.''
   The article said pathologists at Tokyo University believe the
emperor has either pancreatic or duodenum cancer and that palace
officials decided he should not be told about it. Instead, the
article said, they announced the illness as merely an inflammation
of the pancreas.
   Shouichi Fujimori, director general of the Imperial Household
Agency, telephoned the publisher of the Asahi Shimbun, expressed
regret and asked the newspaper to exercise self-restraint.
   ``At this point where the emperor's consciousness is still clear
and he is struggling with his illness, publishing the article was
deemed totally inappropriate,'' said Kenji Maeda, an Imperial
Household Agency spokesman. ``Taking into account the emperor's
feeling, the decision to publish such an article apparently lacks
consideration.''
   But he refused to confirm or deny the report, saying only:
``Matters regarding the fact of the article and publishing such an
article are on different dimensions.''
   Deputy Managing Editor Hisao Kuwashima said the paper printed
the article after its editors decided the emperor would not be able
to read a newspaper again.
   ``Everyone is frustrated about the lack of information about his
condition,'' said Kuwashima. ``His conditions have been clearly
showing signs of pancreatic cancer since a long time ago. After he
was listed in critical condition, we decided we must run this
article.'' He said the decision also was based on the fact that
Hirohito is a public figure.
   In Japan, the decision whether to tell patients they have cancer
is left to doctors and relatives.
   When Hirohito's temperature soared Saturday afternoon, some news
services and television stations quoted unidentified government
sources as saying the emperor was in critical condition, was hooked
to a respirator and was receiving heart massages.
   Maeda hastily denied those reports and angrily said: ``Which can
you trust, speculation by unknown soruces or us?''
   The emperor has no political power but serves as a symbol of
Japan.
   ``Secrecy is an important part of the imperial family,'' said
Inose. ``If an imperial family gave away all secrets and everything
became open, they would not be able to maintain the implicit
authority they have now.
   ``For the people surrounding the imperial family, what's good
for the emperor always comes before what's good for people, and
that's been taken for granted for centuries,'' Inose said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
