<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Graves     09-26 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Graves,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graves For Sale For Chinese Living Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese who live abroad and wish to be buried in
the motherland can now buy a plot under a grave-marketing venture
by Canton and Hong Kong companies, the official Xinhua News Agency
reported today.
   The joint venture is offering 2,000 ``tombs'' on a hillside 12
miles from Canton, with a 50-square-foot site costing $2,050, the
agency said.
   People wishing a more prominent post-life return to the mainland
will be able to put up personal statues, and the plots come in a
variety of styles to meet the needs of people of different
religions, the report said.
   The project is a joint venture between the Guangzhou (Canton)
Funeral and Interment Service Co. and a Hong Kong interment service
company.
   Xinhua did not specify whether those buying the sites would
follow Chinese custom and be cremated before being put to rest.
   The Beijing government has tried to make cremation a universal
practice in China because of the country's severe land shortage,
but has met some resistance in rural areas where people are
traditionally buried.
</TEXT>
