<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic     09-26 0918</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic,0946</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Tension Mounts In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the tense capital of Yugoslavia's
backward region of Kosovo, the majority Albanians and minority
Slavs are divided from the cradle to the grave.
   It starts in kindergarten, where parents say Albanian and Slav
children trade racial slurs.
   It ends with the death notices on trees lining main streets _
black borders for Slavs, green for Albanians.
   In good times, there was some fraternization, even
intermarriage, among the Albanians, who make up 90 percent of
Kosovo's 2 million people, and the 200,000 Slavs. But the closeness
is increasingly rare since ethnic riots in 1981 left at least nine
dead and 200 injured.
   In the past months, the tension has increased in this region the
Slavs see as their historic homeland.
   The Albanians, most of whom are Moslems, want to win a greater
voice in governing Kosovo, now administered by the republic of
Serbia. The Slavs are pushing to absorb the autonomous province
into Serbia.
   For the mostly Christian Slavs, made up of Serbs and
Montenegrins, the Albanian demand is impossible. They argue that a
separate republic would oust them from Kosovo.
   Kosovo was settled by Serbs in the 7th century and was the heart
of Serbia's medieval empire. The Turks conquered it in 1389 and
ruled until the Balkan War of 1913, when it was partitioned between
Serbia and what is now the republic of Montenegro in Yugoslavia.
Albanians, believed to be descended from the ancient Illyrians,
have been in the region since ancient times.
   Slavs say the Albanians would precipitate the breakup of this
communist Balkan country by seceding and uniting with Albania, the
neighboring communist country.
   Thousands of Serbs and Montenegrins have left Kosovo because of
arson and other attacks they blame on the Albanians, who are rarely
given a chance to publicly respond to what appear to be grossly
distorted accounts.
   The animosity, exacerbated by emotional Slav rallies protesting
alleged Albanian attacks, is now so high that many residents
believe a military crackdown will come within months, or even
weeks. Police equipped with armored personnel carriers have been
sent to the province by the federal government in Belgrade.
   The Slavs say Kosovo's Albanians, who have the highest birthrate
in Europe, are making a conscious effort to outbreed them. They
claim the Albanians are chasing them out of Kosovo by attacking
their women and children and offering irresistibly high amounts of
money for their properties.
   ``You could buy in New York for what they pay here,'' said a
Western resident of Pristina, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
He cited prices of $222,000 for a house in the hilly city.
   The Slavs have found a champion for their cause in Slobodan
Milosevic, the leader of Serbia's Communist Party, who advocates
more direct Serbian control over Kosovo and the autonomous province
of Vojvodina, near the Hungarian border. Both areas control their
own judiciary, police and other insitutions.
   The position of the Serbian Communist Party has thrown
Yugoslavia into its most explosive political crisis of the postwar
era.
   Milosevic's views have drawn hundreds of emotional crowds to
rallies where they vent their frustrations with Yugoslavia's
economic crisis by chanting for arms and vowing to keep Kosovo
Slavic.
   ``We are shaking the country,'' said Miroslav Solevic, a
Pristina Serb who heads a committee to organize the rallies.
   But leaders of Yugoslavia's other republics say Milosevic's
emotional tactics could lead to civil war.
   The rallies ``have a negative effect on the situation in
Kosovo,'' said Albanian Hashim Rexhepi, a member of Kosovo's
Communist leadership.
   ``It's very bad for us now,'' said student Nazim Rexhepi, an
ethnic Albanian with no known family ties to the politician.
``Nobody asks us anything. If we even organized a similar rally (to
those held by the Serbs), we would all be proclaimed Albanian
separatists and sentenced.''
   The ethnic crisis has been worsened by Kosovo's economic
backwardness.
   Seventy percent of the population is under 30, and 135,000
people are jobless. Listless, bored young men gather by the
hundreds on Pristina's refuse-strewn streets.
   Those with jobs earn as little as $75 a month, less than half
the national average. A middle-class family of four is lucky to
live in a one-bedroom apartment in a building with broken light
bulbs and windows and an entrance that reeks of garbage.
   Money from the richer republics has produced some incongruously
luxurious buildings, such as the university library.
   ``We're the only country in the world that has borrowed money to
finance its own destruction,'' said a Serbian journalist in Kosovo
who spoke on condition of anonymity. He was referring to
Yugoslavia's $21 billion debt and child support paid to Albanians
for each of their many children.
   In the village of Prekale, armed Serbian vigilantes protect
children from harassment by Albanian villagers and police patrol
the area every six hours.
   ``The ordinary people _ it's not their fault. It's all the big
heads that do this,'' says Serb villager Slobodan Maksimovic.
   The villagers are ready to flee if ethnic violence erupts, but
Serbian nationalists anxious to stem emigration from Kosovo have
persuaded many people to stay.
   ``I had to come back from (working in) Switzerland to protect my
family,'' said Maksimovic. ``I have to go with my kids every day to
school, wait until they finish and then come back with them. We
feel as if we are in a zoo, encircled by Albanians and guarded by
police.''
</TEXT>
