<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PrisonDisturbance     09-26 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Disturbance,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Found Dead After Disturbance Over Jail Liquor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By QUANE KENYON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners briefly seized control of a
high-security section of the Idaho State Penitentiary on Sunday,
and guards later found an inmate dead in his cell, authorities said.
   The 3{-hour rampage began when two unarmed guards ran into
resistance trying to confiscate homemade liquor from inmates, said
Tim McNeese, executive assistant to state Department of Corrections
director Al Murphy.
   The prisoners broke glass and burned mattresses and papers
before surrendering.
   The death was being investigated as an apparent homicide, said
McNeese. He said the victim's name was being withheld pending
notification of relatives. He refused to release details of how the
man was killed.
   After SWAT teams entered the building and inmates ended their
disturbance without force, officers found the body during an
inspection, McNeese said at a news conference.
   ``It appears there was significant damage,'' said McNeese. It
was mainly glass damage. ``There isn't that much in there to
burn,'' he said.
   Someone broke through a cinderblock cell wall to get at the
inmate, he said. He said there was no immediate information whether
the disturbance was staged to aid the slaying.
   The cellblock involved normally has a population of 120. McNeese
said he had no immediate indication how many inmates took part in
the disturbance and destruction, but many remained in their cells.
</TEXT>
