<1ST_LINE>r a PM-High-TechHigh     09-26 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-High-Tech High,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virginia High-Tech High School Makes Its Mark in Just Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNANDALE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Jefferson High School for Science
and Technology has yet to graduate its first class but already more
than a sixth of its 340 seniors have been named National Merit
Scholarship semifinalists.
   And a 16-year-old junior led a four-student team to victory over
1,500 schools in a rigorous nationwide competition for a $1 million
supercomputer last month.
   In other respects, the kids in the school in Annandale, a suburb
of Washington, D.C., are normal teen-agers. They go out for
football, plaster their classroom walls with posters and art,
produce a school newspaper, audition for the drama club play.
   But their academic record is something else. The seniors'
performance in the Merit Scholarship competition placed the high
school fifth among the 19,000 schools that participated.
   ``Isn't it fabulous?'' says Fairfax County School Superintendent
Robert Spillane. ``This is the first full year of a four-year
school, and it has already made its mark.''
   A passion for learning among the student body and unusual
cooperation make Thomas Jefferson a trend-setter among high schools
in this era of burgeoning technology.
   ``What characterizes the environment in this building is
extraordinary intellectual stimulation _ a sense of enjoyment of
learning and a commitment to excellence,'' said Mary Harley Kruter,
admissions and staff development director. ``It's really
phenomenal.''
   The school won the supercomputer thanks to a project by Manish
Tuteja, 16, called ``Complex Plane Analysis of the Newton Raphson
Method on High Order Polynomials.'' The project focused on a method
for deriving formulas in calculus, involving work being done in
relatively new study of chaos, according to principal Geoffrey
Jones.
   ``The work he did was quite significant and likely will lead to
publication,'' Jones said.
   Jefferson opened in fall 1985 in an area that's growing faster
than any in the country in the high-tech field. Sixteen-hundred
teen-agers are bused in daily from all over northern Virginia.
   Only one in three eighth-grade students who hope to attend
Jefferson meet its rigorous standards for admission. Aspirants must
take a standardized test and write an essay. School officials also
take into account their previous school experiences, including
grades, activities, and ability and interest in science and
mathematics.
   Students pursue parallel programs in science and technology. The
science curriculum follows the standard college preparatory course,
with classes in earth science, biology, calculus and the other
usual requirements.
   The technology portion focuses on learning by doing in the real
world.
   ``We have a strong tie with business and industry that leads us
to a different model of education, focusing on the technology as
it's being used and developed in the field,'' Jones said. ``The
ideal program for us is to have student and faculty who are
actually working with people in the industry on the same
technologies and learning the science and math as part of the
experience.''
   Corporations have donated computer labs and other equipment to
the young school, and professionals visit regularly to teach and
work with students.
   ``We actually send students out to work in the field,'' said
Jones, pointing out the example of Honeywell, where students work
part-time and during the summer.
   Other companies that support Jefferson include Atlantic
Research, Virginia Power, AT&T, Sony, Hazelton Laboratories, BDM,
Martin Marietta, Hewlitt Packard, Computer Sciences Corp., IBM,
Dynalectron and TRW.
   The high-tech focus at the school is balanced by a strong
humanities program and a sports program.
   Jones plays down the Merit Scholarship aspect of his school's
success, saying the standardized tests are ``not a good measure of
school success.'' His challenge is finding innovative ways to
measure how well Jefferson fulfills its mandate as one of the first
schools in the nation to focus intensively on science and
technology.
   ``One of our real challenges or goals is to develop a model for
scientific and technological education, and to see if that model is
different from what has traditionally happened in the schools,''
said Jones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
