<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LamaEnthronement     09-26 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lama Enthronement,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Mother Enthroned As First Western Buddhist Lama
Reincarnate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POOLESVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher Burroughs was 14 when he was
told his mother was a Tibetan saint who lived 300 years ago. But it
wasn't much of a surprise to him.
   ``She was always giving advice and teaching people,'' he says of
his mother, Catharine, who was enthroned Saturday as the Western
world's first adult reincarnate lama. Now 16, Christopher
eventually plans to continue the path of Buddha, known as dharma,
and become a monk.
   ``There is certainly an adjustment when you find out that Mom is
not just Mom,'' says her husband, Michael Burroughs, director of
the Buddhist prayer center in Poolesville, a suburb of Washington,
D.C. ``But there was no question that she always was
extraordinary.''
   Catharine Burroughs, a 38-year-old mother of three, had been a
meditation teacher in Maryland when Penor Rinpoche, a ``living
Buddha'' who runs a Buddhist monastery in India, visited her
classes in 1985 and told her that her instinctive knowledge was
Tibetan Buddhism, and that her wisdom was that of a Tibetan saint,
Ahkon Lhamo, who helped found a monastery the mid-1600s.
   He returned to the center Saturday, which he named the seat of
his teachings in America, to perform the ceremony.
   ``I was teaching Buddhism before I ever read a book on it,''
Mrs. Burroughs said while sipping tea after the ceremony.
   The reincarnate lamas, teachers with an obligation to help rid
the world of suffering, are venerated by Tibetan Buddhists because
they are believed to return to this world voluntarily to enlighten
others.
   Usually such lamas are recognized as children to be the
reincarnation of their predecessor who recently died.
   ``In India there are (reincarnate lamas) who have walked up to
their parents and said `I am not Joe-Bob, I am so-and-so. Take me
to my monastery,''' Mrs. Burroughs said.
   She was born in Brooklyn to a Roman Catholic Italian father and
Jewish mother. She attended high school and community college in
Miami, and moved to Maryland in 1982 to establish a place for
meditation.
   The Buddhist center, formally established in 1983 as Kunsang
Odsal Palyul Changchub Cheoling, is a temple of Buddhist teaching
and prayer devoted to the cessation of suffering.
   Its members are some 70 professionals in the
Baltimore-Washington area who take shifts maintaining a 24-hour
prayer vigil, and fund the center through private donations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
