<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Bostonians     09-26 0115</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Bostonians,90</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audience Interprets Bush Remark as Slur on Boston Region</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Vice President George Bush drew a
deep groan from the presidential debate audience in questioning
Michael Dukakis' use of ``phony or some one of these marvelous
Boston adjectives'' to describe the Reagan administration's foreign
policy.
   With a long ``o-o-o-h,'' the audience appeared to have
interpreted Bush's remark during the presidential debate Sunday
night as a regional slur, appealing to a belief among many voters
that Dukakis' home town is a cradle for liberal politicians and
ideas.
   ``Several Bostonians don't like it,'' Bush said in response to
the utterances from the audience, ``But the rest of the country
will understand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0031 </DOCNO>
