<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Christmas     09-26 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Christmas,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Uses Slip To Poke Fun at His Penchant for Verbal Mistakes</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Republican nominee George Bush used
some momentary confusion over weapons systems in the presidential
debate to poke fun at his tendency to utter bloopers on the
campaign trail.
   ``It's Christmas,'' the vice president said during the debate
with Democrat Michael Dukakis after confusing the Midgetman and
Minuteman with the MX missile but correcting himself immediately.
   Laughter erupted from the audience, remembering Bush's reference
earlier this month to the Japanese bombing of Pearl Harbor as
occurring on Sept. 7, 1941, instead of Dec. 7.
   ``Wouldn't it be nice to be perfect?'' Bush quipped in response
to the laughter. He then played to a Republican theme that Dukakis
is cold and aloof. ``Wouldn't it be nice to be the ice man, so you
never make a mistake?''
   Dukakis got the last laugh by picking up on the same quip when
Bush later objected to moderator Jim Lehrer cutting off his
response to a question on the Iran-Contra arms and money scandal.
   ``It's only on yellow here, wait a minute,'' Bush said,
referring to a light at the front of the stage warning that his
response time for the question was about to expire, but had not yet.
   Lehrer admitted he was wrong, apologized _ saying ``You said
nobody's perfect'' _ and told Bush to go ahead with his answer.
   ``I said I wasn't perfect, I thought you were,'' Bush told
Lehrer, drawing more giggles from the audience. ``Where was I?''
   ``The 25th of December, Mr. Vice President,'' Dukakis answered.
   ``I agree,'' Bush said. ``I've finished.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0033 </DOCNO>
