<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SpinControl 1stLd-Writethru a0451 09-26 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spin Control, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In The Cafeteria, All the Choices Were Self-Serving</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 18th graf, `George Bush,' to CORRECT spelling of Kerry.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ The debate was over and gridlock
reigned in the press room. It wasn't reporters trying to reach
George Bush and Michael Dukakis, it was the stampede of political
heavyweights shamelessly promoting their candidate's performance
while making the other guy's seem abysmal.
   Senators and governors competed for reporters' attention and
television's cameras to claim that Dukakis came across as
presidential, humane and compassionate and Bush as plastic and
fuzzy _ or vice versa.
   In political parlance, it is known as the spin patrol and a glut
of spin was spun by politicians brought in for just that purpose.
The Democrats had the likes of Sens. Ted Kennedy and Bill Bradley
and the Republicans had Sen. Alan Simpson, former Sen. John Tower
and New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu.
   The Wake Forest University cafeteria, turned into a press room,
was packed with post-debate spinners, who needed no prompting to
stand amenably, surrounded by cameras and tape recorders and
reporters with notebooks. Other spinners made the rounds of the
television shows.
   Kennedy volunteered that his home state governor, Dukakis, had
scored a clear win. ``He was presidential, he was compelling, he
was convincing,'' said Kennedy.
   The Democratic line on Bush was typified by Dukakis adviser Tom
Donilon, who coordinated the Democrat's debate preparation: ``I
don't think he was very presidential tonight. He wasn't in command
and control. He was wandering.''
   Simpson of Wyoming said Bush showed he was ``a real human
being'' while Dukakis ``looked absolutely programmed'' as well as
``plastic.''
   And Sununu came up with this instant analysis: ``I thought the
vice president looked very relaxed. I think Michael Dukakis looked
very clerkish.''
   While each side claimed their candidate had won, many were
willing to say that the winning and losing was not pronounced and
some even ventured to acknowledge that the other candidate scored a
point or two.
   ``I don't think either candidate made any mistakes,'' owned up
Sununu.
   Several Democrats seized on Bush's stumbles such as when he
referred to the Midgetman missile, ``Or the Minuteman _ whatever it
is.''
   No, rebutted the Bush spinners, little mistatements showed Bush
was human, not a ``man who looks like a machine,'' in Simpson's
description of Dukakis.
   Appearances were important to the spinners because each side had
wanted to project their man as a caring, humane candidate as well
as one who grasped the issues.
   Predictably, each side expressed satisfaction on that score.
   Media consultant Frank Greer who had coached Dukakis on being
more personable, said his candidate ``did everything that he needed
to do and more.''
   Richard Darman, who played the part of Dukakis in Bush's debate
practice sessions, on the other hand said Bush scored ``a perfect
10'' while Dukakis came across as ``dour, stern, didactic.''
   ``Dukakis was boring,'' said Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater.
   ``George Bush was on the defensive,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass.
   Several Republicans, including GOP party chairman Frank
Fahrenkopf stressed that more than winning or losing, the debate
helped crystallize the differences between the two candidates and
in the mind of the Bush ssupporters cement Dukakis as a liberal.
   ``They both did fine. They both reinforced their positions,''
said Atwater, who then could not resist adding the spin: ``All the
swing voters that watched this, would come down on the side of the
vice president.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
