<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Issues Bjt   09-26 0971</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Issues, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Debate Achievement: The Candidates' Differences Stand Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Stands for Winston-Salem, N.C.-dateline story listed on
digest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 90 minutes, George Bush and Michael Dukakis
gave the American people a clear-cut choice on issues likely to
land on the desk of the next occupant of the Oval Office: from
housing the homeless to dealing with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Their debate Sunday night brought out in sharp relief their
differences on the Strategic Defense Initiative, on taxes, on
universal health insurance, the death penalty, abortion and other
issues.
   Between the jibes and jabs, both Bush and Dukakis managed to
spell out many of the stands they have built their campaigns around.
   They fudged on some big questions, like how they would deal with
the federal deficit, or fulfill campaign promises without adding to
the red ink.
   When confronted with what one reporter called the nation's No. 1
domestic problem, drug abuse, Bush suggested the answer is ``to
instill values in these young people,'' while Dukakis implied all
would be well if the White House just hadn't dealt with a
drug-running Panamanian dictator.
   Here is a look at how other key issues played out in the debate:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STAR WARS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis accused Bush of wanting to spend ``billions and
trillions on Star Wars.'' He said he knew of no reputable scientist
who believes this ``kind of an Astrodome over ourselves'' could
work. But Dukakis said he would continue basic Star Wars research
at its 1983 level of $1 billion a year _ about a quarter of the
current budget.
   Bush demanded to know why he would ``spend a dime on something
that you consider a fantasy, and a fraud.'' Bush vowed, ``I will
fully research it, go forward as fast as we can. We've sent up the
levels of funding, and when it is deployable, I will deploy it.
That's my position on SDI, and it's never waivered a bit.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEFICIT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush said his ``flexible freeze'' would help bring the deficit
down. He also called for line-item veto authority and a balanced
budget amendment to the Constitution.
   Dukakis suggested he'd find savings in agriculture subsidies,
scrap certain weapons, find ways to bring interest rates down and
bring in ``billions and billions'' by cracking down on tax cheats.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAPITAL GAINS TAX</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis charged Bush's promise to lower the tax on capital gains
(from 28 to 15 percent) would cost $40 billion and provide a tax
break of $30,000 (``more than the average teacher makes'') for
people earning $200,000 a year.
   Bush said that when the capital gains tax was cut in the past,
it produced more revenue and investment, not less.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HEALTH INSURANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis defended his plan to seek legislation requiring most
businesses to offer workers health insurance; that would reach 22
million of the 37 million Americans who now have no health
insurance. ``I think it's time that when you get a job in this
country it came with health insurance,'' the Democrat said.
   But Bush said that would cost businesses $35 billion. ``One
thing I will not do, is sock every business in the country, and
thus, throw some people out of work,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOMELESS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Asked about the nation's up to 3 million homeless, Bush said he
would fully fund the McKinney Act and seek to galvanize voluntary
efforts.
   Dukakis charged the Reagan administration created the problem by
cutting back ``by 90 percent on our commitment to affordable
housing for families of low and moderate income. And when you do
that, you have homeless families.''
   Bush countered that interest rates were 21{ percent the last
time ``your party controlled the White House.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ABORTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis said, ``I don't favor abortion. I don't think it's a
good thing. I don't think most people do. The question is, who
makes the decision? And I think it has to be the woman, in the
exercise of her own conscience and religious beliefs, that makes
that decision.''
   Bush, who favors outlawing all abortions except to save the
mother's life or in cases of rape or incest, ducked a question on
whether he favors jailing women and doctors who defied such a law.
``I haven't sorted out the penalties,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>POVERTY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush said he supports Head Start; the Womens, Infant and
Children nutrition program and expansion of Medicaid to help
alleviate urban poverty, as well as cracking down on crime.
   Dukakis charged the Reagan-Bush administration has ``cut and
slashed and butchered'' education and nutrition programs for poor
children, and aid for college. He accused the administration of
resisting welfare reforms.
   Bush said federal spending on education actually has risen in
the Reagan years.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOREIGN AFFAIRS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis defended his lack of experience in the foreign arena,
saying that didn't hamper other governors who became president such
as Woodrow Wilson and Franklin D. Roosevelt. And he charged that
Bush's ``long resume ... didn't stop him from endorsing the sale of
arms to the Ayatollah'' and being involved with Panama's Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Bush offered a ``deal'' to Dukakis: ``I will take all the blame
for those two incidents if you give me half the credit for all of
the good things that have happened in world peace since Ronald
Reagan and I took over from the Carter administration.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NUCLEAR WEAPONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis denied he favors ``unilateral disarmament,'' but
acknowledged he would cut ``certain weapon system we don't need and
can't afford.'' Bush criticized his rival's opposition to the
mobile MX and Midgetman missiles, saying the Soviets are tough
negotiators, and ``I'm not going to give away a couple of aces in
that very tough card game.''
   Dukakis said, ``I thought the administration was opposed to the
Midgetman.'' He said the administration has suggested at the Geneva
arms talks ``that we ban mobile missile systems entirely.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
