<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   09-26 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0814,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Stocks Rally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Nikkei, dollar closings.
Pick up 4th pvs, Dealers said.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese currency
in Tokyo today while stock prices eased over widespread concerns
about the health of ailing Emperor Hirohito.
   The dollar closed at 134.73 yen, up 0.26 yen from its close on
Thursday, the last day of trading. It opened at 134.80 yen and
moved in a narrow range of 134.66-134.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the main index
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, shed 59.17 points or 0.22 percent to
end Monday's trading at 27,330.95.
   Dealers said the dollar's strength followed a reaffirmation
among monetary authorities from seven major industrialized
countries, meeting in West Berlin over the weekend, that they would
continue to coordinate economic policies targeting stable exchange
rates and containment of inflation.
   But they said the market needed fresh incentives to determine
the direction of the currency. ``They (the G-7) did not say whether
the dollar should or shouldn't be traded higher or lower,''
complained one dealer at a major commercial bank, who spoke
anonymously.
   Seiichi Kita of Daiwa Securities said steel issues turned out to
be ``a driving force to gear up the index in late morning trading''
as investors began to buy prospective shares ahead of a new
financial year beginning Tuesday.
   The Nikkei index lost 159.63 points, or 0.58 percent, in early
trading, following a 38.19-point loss during Saturday's half-day
session, after morning papers reported the emperor was continuing
to receive blood transfusions. But palace officials later denied
the reports and said Hirohito was in stable condition.
   Kita said, however, investors were still concerned about the
87-year-old monarch.
   Both the currency and stock markets in Tokyo were closed Friday
because of a national holiday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Color     09-26 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Color,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even The Undecided Had a Cry: `Throw They Both Back!'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Demonstrators who wanted to deliver a
message to the candidates were sealed off on the soccer field, but
that didn't stop Wake Forest University students from expressing
themselves. Some undecideds hung a banner: ``Throw 'em both back.
Let's go fishing again.''
   It could have been homecoming weekend _ with the Big Debate
taking the place of the Big Game.
   There were banners, partisan crowds, a huge press contingent and
a festive yet tense atmosphere Sunday as George Bush and Michael
Dukakis matched wits for 90 minutes in the chapel with millions of
Americans looking on through television.
   Placards dotted the windows of buildings ringing the grassy
quadrangle at the center of the tree-lined campus. Banners hung
from windowsills with catchy slogans: ``I hate pork rinds. Vote for
Dukakis,'' and ``Deacons don't dig the Duke.''
   Wake Forest's athletic teams use the nickname ``Demon Deacons.''
   Other banners had less partisan messages: ``Don't hide in a Bush
or run for the Mike. Come see for yourself who you like.''
   Demonstrators representing a variety of causes hoped for a
moment in the spotlight, but the university soccer field where they
were shuttled off to was hundreds of yards away from the debate
site.
   ``We'd like to be closer but that's something we can't do
anything about,'' said Marian Franklin of the Winston-Salem chapter
of the National Organization for Women, who held a sign touting the
Equal Rights Amendment.
   As the debate time neared, a throng of star-struck students
packed sidewalks near Wait Chapel, watching for the arrival of
VIPs. Network anchors appeared to excite the crowd more than anyone
if the flashbulb pops and gasps of recognition were any indication.
   Only two public entrances to the chapel were provided, creating
huge traffic jams as people struggled through security checks.
   Inside, the crowd chatter grew and tension built in anticipation
of candidates' grand entrance.
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of the Massachusetts governor, entered the
auditorium while Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk and his GOP
counterpart Frank Fahrenkopf were welcoming the crowd. Mrs.
Dukakis, wearing a dark blue dress, took her seat in the front row.
   After Kirk and Fahrenkopf stopped talking, Bush's wife, Barbara,
entered through another door. She wore a black-and-white print
dress and a pearl necklace.
   Bush partisans gave her a standing ovation; Dukakis supporters
remained seated and did not clap.
   The vice president and the Massachusetts governor walked onstage
simultaneously from opposite sides, meeting at the center and
cordially shaking hands. But they wasted no time attacking each
other.
   Moderator Jim Lehrer had urged the feisty crowd not to applaud,
cheer or otherwise disrupt the debate _ a plea that was ignored as
the spectators vented their pleasure or disdain.
   Bush's claim that he was not attacking Dukakis's patriotism on
the Pledge of Allegiance issue drew scornful laughter from the
Democratic side of the aisle. When Dukakis said he had been tough
on criminals, it was the Bush side's turn to guffaw.
   The applause and signs of displeasure became more frequent as
the debate went on _ despite a second admonition from Lehrer _ and
the candidates' exchanges got more heated. The temperatures inside
the chapel seemed to rise; Bush and Dukakis frequently sipped water
and Bush mopped his brow with a handkerchief as his rival delivered
a closing statement.
   The combatants again shook hands and smiled after the debate's
conclusion. Members of the candidates' families hurried forward;
Bush leaned forward to kiss his wife while Dukakis and his wife
embraced.
   They lingered onstage for several moments; Bush even autographed
a couple of debate programs. Then both rushed away to post-debate
rallies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
