<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DebateReax     09-26 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate Reax,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Heap Praise But Independents Say No Clear Debate
Winner Emerged</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Political partisans heaped on the hyperbole in the aftermath of
the presidential candidates' debate, but independent observers said
neither nominee delivered the zinger that could change the face of
their race.
   Who won? ``Who knows. This is a media event. This is
entertainment,'' said Jerry Calvert, political science chairman at
Montana State University. ``Both of the men scored well with the
people who are already supporting them.''
   Politicians promptly backed Calvert up: Republicans declared
George Bush the clear victor of Sunday's 90-minute confrontation at
Wake Forest University, while Democrats unabashedly designated
Michael Dukakis the champion.
   ``I believe Dukakis not only won the debate but the election
tonight,'' said Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
   ``Bush really laid him out,'' said Sen. Orrin G. Hatch,
Republican of Utah.
   Professional analysts were more reluctant to pick a winner, and
even some elected officials were equivocal. ``Neither guy won,''
said Republican Gov. James Thompson of Illinois, ``and neither guy
lost.''
   ``There was no knockout here,'' said political commentator David
Gergen, former communications director for President Reagan. ``I
thought Bush picked up points on policy issues. I thought Dukakis
was smoother on presentation and reached out effectively to the
middle class.''
   On balance, Gergen said, Bush appeared to succeed in further
delineating his ideological differences with Dukakis, while the
Democrat scored with economically struggling voters. ``I don't
think this will swing it,'' he said. ``I do think this will make it
a more competitive race.''
   Many Republicans put greater emphasis on the ideological issue,
saying Bush succeeded in portraying Dukakis as too liberal for most
voters.
   ``George Bush had a mission and he can say mission
accomplished,'' said Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., who lost the GOP
nomination to Bush. ``He documented again and again that Mike
Dukakis is a Ted Kennedy Massachusetts liberal _ and that means
someone who's out of step with mainstream America.''
   Democrats, however, took the position that their nominee had
widened his appeal. ``Dukakis won decisively in terms of picking up
political support. He came across as assured, confident and clear
on the facts,'' said Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who lost
his party's nomination to Dukakis.
   Bush, Gephardt said, ``seemed befuddled and confused.''
   But Culpepper Clark, a University of Alabama professor who
studies speeches, scored five topics for Bush, four for Dukakis and
three a tie. ``If you believe that Dukakis had to score some kind
of knockout or create some kind of major error on the part of the
vice president, it did not occur,'' he said.
   Some viewers considered style rather than issues. Psychologist
Joyce Brothers rated the candidates on everything from using their
hands for emphasis _ advantage Dukakis _ to appearing relaxed, a
score for Bush.
   ``Dukakis did much better when the camera caught him
accidentally. He is the master of the ironic smile,'' she said.
``Bush was caught making notes, like a professor. That's a minus.
But Bush is the better master of the pause.''
   Lillian Glass, a speech consultant who is author of ``Talk to
Win,'' said Dukakis ``came across a lot weaker than Bush.''
   ``Bush looks presidential, but he needs to hold his head up
straighter,'' she said. ``He made impressive recovery when he made
an error. It made a big difference for him to drop his voice. The
wimp factor is finally gone.''
   There were complaints from some quarters about the coaching
undergone by both participants. ``Both candidates were pretty well
programmed,'' said Sen. J. Bennett Johnston Jr., D-La. ``We saw a
little window into the candidates tonight, but not enough.''
   ``Both gave somewhat canned responses,'' agreed a Republican
Louisianan, Rep. Jim McCrery.
   As a result, not all observers were thrilled by the
performances. Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., called the debate
``pretty mundane,'' and to Democrat Willie Brown, speaker of the
California Assembly, ``It was rather boring.''
   Others drew more dramatic evaluations:
   _Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, the Democratic leader in the
Senate: ``Tonight we saw a leader emerge and it was Michael
Dukakis.''
   _Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas: ``I believe George Bush
did what he had to do to win the election. He came across as being
more of a leader and more of a real person.''
   _Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.: ``Dukakis had to do well, and I
think this will clearly be the opportunity Michael Dukakis lost.
The vice president has fended him off.''
   _Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York: ``Governor Dukakis clearly
advanced his campaign dramatically. He appeared knowledgeable,
decisive, cool, presidential. He won.''
   _Pat Robertson, the television evangelist who ran against Bush
for the Republican nomination for president: ``On the important
issues of taxation, strong defense and law and order, George Bush
was a clear winner.''
   _Ira Glasser, president of the American Civil Liberties Union,
of which Dukakis is a member: Bush's criticism of the ACLU during
the debate was ``a descent into mudslinging of a kind we have not
seen in my lifetime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
