<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0459EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Peoria     09-26 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Peoria,380</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>But Did It Play in Peoria?
^By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's how Bush vs. Dukakis played in Peoria:
   George Bush scored big for his position on drugs, his vice
presidential experience and desire to return to ``fundamental
values.''
   Michael Dukakis won points for his criticism of U.S. dealings
with ``drug-running Panamanian dictators,'' international
terrorists and advocacy of programs for America's homeless.
   One hundred voters _ selected at random _ took part in an
instantaneous electronic survey of their reactions as they watched
Dukakis and Bush debate on television Sunday night.
   ``It's clear from the audience here that neither candidate hit a
home run with their remarks,'' said Bill Adams, a professor at
George Washington University who coordinated the opinion survey
experiment for a Washington, D.C., research firm.
   The group was assembled at a Peoria hotel and hooked to
computers through an electronic monitoring system that allowed
minute-by-minute monitoring of their opinions.
   Adams said the Peoria area was chosen for the audience survey
because Illinois is a pivotal state in the election.
   Before the debate, the group included 33 people leaning toward
Bush, 41 leaning toward Dukakis and 26 undecided.
   After the debate, 36 said they were leaning toward Bush, 45 were
leaning toward Dukakis and 19 were undecided.
   The debate reaffirmed Mary Herman's impressions of Bush.
   ``He's more personable and I think he has a better sense of
values,'' said Ms. Herman, 69, of East Peoria. ``I don't care for
Mr. Dukakis' ideas. He's too liberal.''
   ``To me, quite honestly, he seems to be more for the average
person,'' said Patty Impinto, 43, of Peoria, referring to Dukakis.
She said the debate changed her preference from Bush to Dukakis.
   ``Both candidates made gains,'' said Christopher Wheeler, who
developed the electronic system used to gauge the audience
response. ``Each man pulled a segment of the undecided voters into
their corners. Nobody lost any ground.''
   Women generally responded more strongly to Dukakis.
   ``It demonstrated vividly the gender gap,'' Adams said. ``The
men in our audience were resonating to Bush. More dramatically, the
women were responding much more positively to Dukakis. It was
highly significant, statistically.''
   ``I was also struck by the phenomenal lack of response to the
Dan Quayle issue,'' Adams said. ``I interpreted that to mean a lot
of them are withholding judgment until the vice presidential
debate.''
</TEXT>
