<DOCNO> AP880926-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Africa-Hunger     09-26 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Africa-Hunger,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 100 Million Africans Reported Undernourished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 million Africans, or one in four, do
not get enough food to fuel an active working life, and the
situation is getting worse, a new World Bank report says.
   ``In the 1980s ... both the proportion and the total number of
Africans with deficient diets have climbed _ and will continue to
rise unless special action is taken,'' the study says.
   Edward V. K. Jaycox, the bank's vice president for Africa,
released the report Sunday. He told a news conference that
production of food grains on the continent has been declining for
two decades.
   The study says 103.7 million Africans are among the ``food
insecure'' _ those who do not get the minimum of 2,200 calories a
day that people need to be able to work.
   It lists communist Ethiopia, buffeted by wars and drought, as
having the largest number: 14.7 million, or nearly half its
population. Ethiopia is followed by Nigeria with 13.7 million and
Zaire with 12 million. Both countries have close ties to the United
States.
   Chad, Somalia, Zambia and Mozambique have higher percentages of
food insecure, but their population is smaller. Egypt is the best
off among the 36 countries listed, with only 4 percent of its
population, about 1.7 million, in the category.
   In some places food may be scarce, but more often people just do
not have the money to buy it, said Jaycox.
   Ethiopia is the poorest country on the World Bank's list, with
average income estimated at $120 a year, less than 35 cents a day.
   The report calls for action so that within five years, half to
two-thirds of the countries south of the Sahara will have carried
out programs to cover a majority of the region's most needy.
   But Jaycox said it would be futile to propose anything so
specific as abolishing hunger ``by the year X.''
   He said billions of dollars have been spent on aid for Africa,
but the programs have not worked well. He said many solutions do
not need new aid money.
   One of those is for African governments to pay higher prices to
African farmers, he said. He said the bank had completed
negotiations with Ethiopia that will give farmers more incentives
and reduce state confiscation of crops, which he said started
before the present government took power.
   But food security does not mean that every African country
should grow all its own food, he said.
   ``If a farmer in the Ivory Coast makes $8 a day growing cotton,
which nobody can eat, there's no point in his growing maize at $2 a
day,'' he said.
   Jaycox said some African governments pay their own farmers too
little, which discourages them from producing. The governments then
buy food from abroad and subsidize its sale in the towns.
   He said these policies are worse than the policies of wealthier
countries in America and Europe where governments sell their
surplus food cheap to benefit their own farmers at the expense of
the taxpayer.
   Jaycox said the African policies encourage people to shift to
rice and wheat, which are uneconomical to grow in Africa, away from
the sorghum and maize that their farmers traditionally have raised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--ChronicleEditor     09-26 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chronicle Editor,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Matthew F. Wilson Named Managing Editor Of The Chronicle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matthew F. Wilson has been named managing
editor of the San Francisco Chronicle, the newspaper said in
today's editions.
   Wilson's promotion from his position as special assistant to the
executive editor was effective today.
   As special assistant, he played a major role in the expansion
and redesign of the newspaper's news and feature sections last year.
   Wilson, a 32-year-old native of San Francisco and graduate of
the University of California-Berkeley, began his career at the
Chronicle in 1975 as a copy boy. He became a copy editor in June
1978.
   Wilson helped direct installation of the newspaper's
computerized editing system in 1982 and 1983. He has since been
involved in seminars on technology issues for the American Society
of Newspaper Editors and The Associated Press Managing Editors
Association.
   Wilson's father, Kenneth E. Wilson, was managing editor of the
Santa Rosa Press Democrat and is the Chronicle's assistant to the
publisher for systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0532EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-FourthDistrict     09-26 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fourth District,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skeletons Out of the Closet in Swindall-Jones Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political skeletons were out of the closet
long before Halloween here in the congressional race between
Republican Rep. Pat Swindall and Democratic nominee Ben Jones.
   The congressman, with hidden tape recorders running, discussed
financing his million-dollar home with laundered drug money.
   And Jones, who appeared on the television series ``The Dukes of
Hazzard,'' admits to ``wild'' drunken behavior and a conviction for
assaulting his wife.
   Swindall asked for forgiveness, Jones for understanding. Neither
has much for the other.
   ``He beat his wife,'' Swindall, 47, said at one point,
elaborating at a debate that it was ``your second of four wives.''
   ``Being called dishonest by you is like being called ugly by a
possum,'' said Jones, 46, of Swindall's charge that he changed his
story about his criminal record.
   ``I'll have to say it's the most bitter personal attacks I've
seen in Georgia politics in 35 or 40 years,'' said the secretary of
the Georgia Senate, Hamilton McWhorter.
   Atlanta pollster Claibourne Darden called it ``a contest between
two dirty candidates.''
   Jones blundered by failing to let Swindall simply be haunted by
the house issue, Darden said. Instead, Jones reacted angrily when
Swindall grabbed headlines the night Jones won the Democratic
primary by demanding to see Jones' arrest record. Jones suggested
both take a drug test.
   There have been no drug tests, but the ensuing argument gave
Swindall a chance to swear he had never used drugs and forced Jones
to admit he smoked marijuana in the 1970s.
   McWhorter said he thinks Jones still holds the edge, although
Swindall should benefit from being on the ballot with Vice
President George Bush in the Republican-leaning district, made up
mostly of east Atlanta suburbs.
   Swindall and Jones first squared off in 1986, with Swindall
winning election to his second two-year term. But Jones' 47 percent
showing was a surprise for a candidate who began the race with less
name recognition than Cooter, the character he played on television.
   Jones said at the outset that he was an alcoholic who was
frequently in trouble until he kicked the bottle in 1977.
   In the current race, he said the trouble included an incident in
which he shoved his wife in a bar. Jones said he was convicted of a
misdemeanor assault charge, but originally forgot the outcome.
   He made Swindall's house an issue in the first race, suggesting
Swindall was getting a sweetheart deal from a politically
conservative contractor.
   But the price of the house grew to $1.2 million, and Swindall
last year turned to Charles LeChasney for help in financing it.
   When LeChasney was indicted for money laundering, Swindall
acknowledged he once accepted a $150,000 check from LeChasney. He
said he returned it uncashed because he became suspicious.
   The matter became the campaign's commanding issue when
recordings of Swindall's conversations with LeChasney and a shady
financier _ who turned out to be an undercover Internal Revenue
Service agent _ were leaked in June.
   ``I can only draw the conclusion that certainly there are drugs
involved and I can understand if you want to walk away,'' the agent
told Swindall in a tape-recorded meeting Sept. 13, 1987.
   ``I'd say this: first and foremost it becomes Charles'
problem,'' Swindall answered. ``What I have to say is I borrowed
money from (LeChasney's company),'' he added.
   ``And frankly I don't think it's incumbent upon me to go out and
find out where XYZ Corp. gets their money,'' he said in the
recording.
   Swindall said he had made an error in judgment and asked for
forgiveness.
   Jones said the tapes proved Swindall's dishonesty. But he now
says he wants to quit talking about personal issues, saying he
``overreacted'' by suggesting the drug tests and now wants to focus
on national issues.
   ``I have sinned, Pat, and so have you,'' he said at a debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
