<2ND_LINE>PM-Methodist Bishop,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina's First Black United Methodist Bishop Formally
Installed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Female Bishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina's first black United
Methodist bishop says his installation in the post tells blacks in
the state ``they are part of the church.''
   The Rev. Joseph Bethea, 56, was installed Sunday as leader of
the state's 244,000 United Methodists in 1,080 churches at a packed
service at Washington Street United Methodist Church. Many of the
worshipers came from black congregations.
   At a news conference, Bethea said his new position ``speaks a
very relevant and needed word to ... the black United Methodists in
South Carolina. It says ... they are part of the church; they have
ownership of the church.
   ``I would hope all United Methodists in South Carolina will have
a new sense of healing and wholeness as a result of my assignment
as episcopal leader I hope I have some skills and graces that can
serve all the people.''
   Before his election as bishop Sept. 1, Bethea was superintendent
of the Raleigh (N.C.) District. Bethea is a graduate of Claflin
College in Orangeburg.
