<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Locusts     09-26 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Locusts,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Millions of Locusts Darken Sky Over Khartoum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of red and grey locusts darkened
the sky over Khartoum for 90 minutes this morning, some landing on
cultivated fields along the Nile River to devour the crops.
   Huge swarms of the insects began arriving about 7:30 a.m. and
left at about 9 a.m. The sun was completely covered for almost half
an hour of the 1{-hour period.
   Officials had no immediate estimate of the size of the swarm,
which came in from the east and moved in a westerly direction, or
the amount of damage it left behind.
   Torrential rains caused disastrous flooding in Khartoum last
month, and experts said the greening of normally barren desert
areas created perfect breeding grounds for locusts.
   Earlier this month, Agriculture Minister el-Fatih el-Tigani said
Sudan's locust threat had entered ''a critical stage.''
   He said that the government had destroyed half of about 60
potential swarms in the country but that Sudan lacked sufficient
insecticides or equipment to spray all agriclutural lands facing an
invasion.
   Swarms are known to be mainly in eastern and western Sudan.
Khartoum lies at the center of the country.
   Officials fear that locusts could leave behind more devastation
than last month's flooding, which caused damage estimated at $330
million or more.
</TEXT>
