<DOCNO> AP880926-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Serra-Protest     09-26 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Serra-Protest,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vandals Deface Museum, Memorials Honoring Father Serra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pope Beatification</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals defaced a museum honoring the Rev.
Junipero Serra with such spray-painted slogans as ``Genocidal
Maniac'' for his alleged mistreatment of Indians as others
protested at the 18th century monk's grave.
   The graffiti marred ceremonies Sunday at Presidio Park honoring
Serra, the Spanish priest revered as the founder of California's
missions, on the day he was beatified by Pope John Paul II in the
Vatican City.
   Vandals spray-painted slogans including ``Murderous Lying Scum''
and ``Serra was a Baby Killer'' on the doors and sides of the Serra
Museum and other walls and memorials in the 40-acre park.
   In the northern California town of Carmel, about 20 Indians held
a protest prayer vigil at Serra's grave Sunday.
   ``We want to show we're against this because of the brutality
that occurred when Father Serra had control of the missions,'' said
Anthony Miranda, chairman of the Costanoan band of local Indians.
   Carrying an abalone shell filled with burning sage, a variety of
feathers and shell ornaments and a dried gourd that was beat to
mark cadence, the Indians entered the Carmel Mission between
morning Masses.
   One of about 200 parishioners inside yelled, ``Take your pagan
rites out of the church.''
   When the prayer was finished, the protesters left the church and
resumed a demonstration at the gates of the mission. Several were
weeping.
   Museum officials here said the graffiti, which colored a bronze
likeness of Serra, a bronze statue of an Indian and a 50-foot stone
cross, will cost hundreds of dollars to repair.
   ``It's a shame that they chose this method of protesting. That
sort of thing doesn't help anything and certainly is not going to
change the church's position,'' said Dan Pitre, spokesman for the
San Diego Roman Catholic Diocese.
   About 30 protestors who attended a rally later denied
involvement in the vandalism. Police said they had no suspects.
   The graffiti, including obscenities, attacked Serra for greed,
racism and anti-Semitism, as well as cruelty to Indians.
   Serra's critics say he whipped and enslaved the Indians he
worked to convert, stole their lands, and exposed them to European
diseases to which they had no resistance.
   ``He shouldn't be honored,'' said protestor Kip King, an Indian
descendant. ``Serra had the arrogance of any missionary effort of
coming to a people that already had a religion and trying to impose
their European religion.''
   In ceremonies moving Serra toward sainthood, John Paul called
the Franciscan monk, ``a shining example of Christian virtue and
the missionary spirit.''
   Built in 1769, the San Diego mission was the first in a series
of missions along the California coast whose construction was
organized by Serra.
   ``It saddens and angers me,'' Eleanor Neely, education
coordinator for the Serra museum, said of the graffiti. ``There's
no proof whatsoever that Serra mistreated anyone.''
   A group of nine historians that investigated the issue for the
Catholic Church last year reported that Indians were abused in the
missions but found no evidence to support charges against Serra
himself.
</TEXT>
