<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0489,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Still Bleeding Internally, But Said To Be Stable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with emperor briefly watching
television, stock market closing. Picks up 15th graf pvs, `Seiichi
Kita ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito continued to bleed internally and
his temperature rose today, a week after his condition suddenly
deteriorated, but officials said the 87-year-old monarch's health
was stable.
   Kenji Maeda, spokesman for the Imperial Household Agency, said
doctors gave the world's longest-reigning monarch .43 pints of
blood in a transfusion to compensate for that lost from his
intestinal hemorrhage.
   He said the frail emperor was fully conscious today and had
discharged ``slight traces of blood'' through his bowels during the
night.
   Since he vomited blood one week ago, the emperor has through
transfusions received a total of 5.96 pints.
   Maeda said Hirohito briefly watched television today, and
conversed with Crown Prince Akihito and Crown Princess Michiko when
they visited. On Thursday, all the emperor's imperial duties were
transferred to Akihito, 54, who is heir to the throne.
   ``I have not seen him (today) myself, but my impression is that
his condition is consistent and stable,'' Maeda said. ``But we have
to remain alert.''
   But he said Hirohito's temperature had risen to 100 at
midafternoon, up from 98.1 in the morning and well above his normal
reading of about 95.9.
   The nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun today quoted medical
experts as saying cancer was the likely cause of Hirohito's
continuous discharge of blood.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny press reports
that the emperor has cancer and instead have urged the Japanese
media to refrain from speculation. Cancer is rarely acknowledged
publicly in Japan.
   Government spokesman Keizo Obuchi said Hirohito was well enough
Sunday to watch on television as sumo wrestling champion
Chiyonofuji won his 25th title in the Autumn Grand Sumo Tournament.
   ``A perfect victory, isn't it,'' the emperor was quoted as
saying.
   Chiyonofuji, along with other top wrestlers, called on the
palace today to sign his name to a register wishing the emperor
speedy recovery.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index gyrated today with varied
reports of the emperor's condition. After early reports the emperor
had received transfusions during the night, the index fell almost
160 points. It regained its losses after the palace said Hirohito
was in stable condition, but ended the day down 56 points or 0.22
percent.
   Seiichi Kita of Daiwa Securities said the market fluctuations
indicated investors were still concerned about Hirohito's health.
   A crowd of almost 800 people began gathering at the Imperial
Palace after dawn under threatening skies as the nation's vigil
entered a second week.
   As of Sunday, more than 300,000 had signed registries at the
palace and at 11 other locations around the country wishing for the
emperor's recovery, according to palace reports.
   The emperor, who ascended the throne in December 1926, has been
under 24-hour medical supervision since vomiting blood a week ago.
   His condition took a turn for the worse Saturday when his fever
soared to 102.6. By Sunday night, however, Shoichi Fujimori, grand
steward of the Imperial Household Agency, told reporters the crisis
was over.
   Last year on Sept. 22, Hirohito underwent a bypass operation
after an inflamed pancreas put pressure on the duodenum.
   On Saturday, the Asahi Shimbun reported the emperor was
suffering from pancreatic cancer and the respected Kyodo news
agency, quoting a biopsy report, said pathologists found evidence
of cancer in tissue taken from the region between the pancreas and
duodenum in last year's operation.
   Under the constitution, the emperor has no real power but signs
documents and government appointments already approved by the
government.
</TEXT>
