<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--WorkersKilled     09-26 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Workers Killed,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Workers Killed At Naval Yard When Steam Fills Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two civilian workers at the Philadelphia
Naval Shipyard were killed when 350-degree steam filled the small
tunnel where they were working, a spokesman said.
   The boiler technicians were trying to open a valve to return
steam to a part of the shipyard Sunday morning when the utility
tunnel filled with low-pressure steam that had leaked from a pipe,
said Al Peterson, shipyard spokesman.
   ``The steam filled the area almost instantly and there was no
chance of escape,'' he said.
   Charles Carlson, 42, and Ted Shaw, 28, both of Philadelphia,
entered the tunnel through a manhole at about 6:20 a.m., he said.
   About 40 minutes later, when co-workers realized the men were
overdue, they tried to reach them by radio, Peterson said. Without
knowing what had happened, workers shut off steam to the area as a
precaution, he said.
   Firefighters vented the steam out of the tunnel and pulled the
bodies out, Peterson said. The men were pronounced dead on arrival
at the Naval Hospital.
</TEXT>
