<2ND_LINE>PM-Decapitation Sentence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Sentenced To Die For Shooting, Decapitation of Church
Handyman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to restore dropped first reference to minister.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who shot and killed a church
handyman before beheading him and leaving the man's body in a
burning church has been sentenced to death by electrocution.
   The Rev. John David Terry, 44, was convicted Thursday of
first-degree murder and arson in the slaying of James C. Matheny,
32, whose headless body was found in Terry's burning church on June
16, 1987.
   The jury returned the death sentence against Terry on Sunday
after 13 hours of debate and a brief church service.
   Defense attorney Lionel Barrett said, ``I normally don't put
that much stock in appeals, but I think we've got some genuine
legal issues in this case.''
   Terry's strongest ground for appeal is challenging whether the
murder was committed in conjunction with a larceny, which the jury
listed as one of two aggravating circumstances justifing the
imposition of the death penalty, Barrett said.
   Terry admitted misappropriating more than $30,000 in church
funds, but Barrett argued that it did not amount to larceny under
the terms of Tennessee's felony murder statute.
   Terry also admitted he killed Matheny, dressed the body in his
own clothes and set the Emmanuel Church of Christ Oneness
Pentecostal on fire in a scheme to fake his own death. Prosecutors
said Terry wanted to start a new life and leave insurance proceeds
to his family.
   Terry cut off Matheny's head, part of an arm and patches of skin
marked with tattoos and threw the body parts into Lake Barkley near
Dover, Tenn.
   Prosecutors said Terry bought an additional $150,000 in life
insurance in April 1987 and gathered false identification papers in
the name of a boy who drowned in 1951.
   Circuit Judge Walter Kurtz set Terry's execution for April 3,
1989. Appeals begin immediately and can take more than a decade.
Tennessee has not executed a death row inmate since Nov. 7, 1960.
</TEXT>
