<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonDisturbance     09-26 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Disturbance,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Identified as Informant Slain During Cellblock Rampage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By QUANE KENYON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate who was identified in court papers
as a police informant was killed in his cell while other prisoners
went on a rampage, authorities said.
   The 3{-hour uprising Sunday began when inmates refused to let
two unarmed guards confiscate their homemade liquor. Twenty minutes
after authorities quelled the rampage, they discovered the body of
Richard Holmes.
   The lawyer for Holmes, who faced a charge of aiding and abetting
the murder of a drug informant, said authorities are to blame for
Holmes' death because they made public his cooperation, and one
prosecutor involved in the case said his identity was made public
by mistake.
   ``I'm absolutely convinced he was killed because the
prosecutors, contrary to the promise they made, went public with
the fact that Richard Holmes helped them,'' said attorney Rolf
Kehne.
   Idaho State Penitentiary officials declined to speculate whether
the rampage was staged as a diversion to cover up the killing.
   Guards left the area of the uprising about 3:15 p.m. for
reinforcements. Inmates broke glass and burned mattresses and
papers.
   When SWAT teams from several law enforcement agencies re-entered
the building about 6:45 p.m., inmates left voluntarily and no force
was needed, officials said.
   Tim McNeese, executive assistant to state Department of
Corrections director Al Murphy, refused to release details on how
Holmes died. But he said Holmes' killer got into the cell through a
hole knocked in the cinder-block wall.
   In August, Holmes, 35, led police to the partially buried
remains of a drug informant, Denise Williams, 28, of Nampa. But his
hopes of a plea-bargain fizzled when he failed a polygraph test. He
was convicted of unrelated felony charges and also awaited trial on
a charge of aiding and abetting murder.
   Holmes became an instant target when word spread that he had
cooperated with authorities, Kehne said.
   Just Friday, Kehne said, Holmes told him that he considered
himself to be in danger. Holmes had said a handful of newspaper
clippings detailing how he led police to Ms. Williams' body, in
hopes of making a deal, had been shoved into his cell, the lawyer
said.
   Canyon County Prosecutor Richard Harris said he was shocked to
discover that the sensitive information had been placed in the
court file, accessible to reporters and other members of the public.
   He blamed the action on Owyhee County Prosecutor Lawrence
Wasden. Both prosecutors were involved in the case.
   ``I was upset when I found out about it,'' Harris added, ``but
that's one of the problems you get when you have different agencies
involved.''
   Wasden, reached at his home Sunday night, declined to comment.
   Holmes refused to request protective custody because he did not
want to spend several months before his trial in maximum-security,
his lawyer said.
   Holmes was accused of ordering two friends to kill Ms. Williams.
Maxwell Hoffman, 32, has been charged with first-degree murder, and
Ronald Wages, 36, has pleaded guilty to the same charge.
</TEXT>
