<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-TribunePoll     09-26 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Tribune Poll,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Bush Ahead in Three of Five Key States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll conducted in five key states shows Vice
President George Bush with an edge over Democrat Michael Dukakis,
but the lead was within the margin of error and the results could
be regarded as a dead heat.
   The poll of 1,521 voters, published in weekend editions of the
Chicago Tribune, put the vice president ahead in Florida and Texas,
with Dukakis leading in Illinois and New York. California, the
state with the most electoral votes, was a virtual tie.
   No presidential candidate in the 20th century has won without
taking three of the five states polled, and many voters in those
states were looking to Sunday's nationally televised debate to help
them choose between the candidates.
   Overall, Bush led Dukakis 46 percent to 43 percent in the
mid-September survey by pollster Peter Hart of Washington, but the
poll had a 3.5 percent margin of error.
   Bush led in Florida by a comfortable 54 to 37 percent margin,
and in Texas by 50 to 40 percent. In California, the vice president
was ahead 46 to 43 percent, making the state a virtual tie because
of the poll's 6 percent sampling error for the individual state
statistics.
   Dukakis led in New York, 48 to 40 percent, and in Illinois, 47
to 40 percent.
   Nearly three-quarters of those surveyed said they were likely to
watch the debate, and 42 percent said they would ``definitely''
tune in, the newspaper reported.
   One-fourth said the 90-minute debate would be ``very important''
in helping them decide which candidate to vote for, and 18 percent
said the joint appearance would be ``fairly important.''
</TEXT>
