<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EyeTransplant     09-26 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eye Transplant,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Use Eye-Cell Transplants in Rats to Cure Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have taken a major step toward curing
a disease that causes blindness, saving the eyesight of
experimental rats by transplanting retinal cells in their eyes,
according to a published report.
   Two groups of scientists have succeeded in performing the
transplants and preventing a type of blindness in the rats, The New
York Times reported Sunday. The researchers said the procedure
would have to be repeated on monkeys and other animals before it
could be tried on human beings, the Times reported.
   According to the Retinitis Pigmentosa Foundation in Baltimore,
degenerative diseases of the retina occur in 400,000 living
Americans. Macular degeneration, one of these diseases, is the
leading cause of blindness in this country in people over the age
of 60.
   Sometimes doctors can slow the loss of vision in patients with
these diseases but they have no way of preventing it.
   Before the scientists' findings could be applied to humans, the
problem of tissue rejection will have to be overcome, the newspaper
reported. The rats came from a special, inbred strain whose immune
system accepts other tissue without attacking it.
   The experiments involved rats with an inherited defect in
pigmented epithelial cells, which darken the pupil and allow light
to pass through. These cells cover and nourish photoreceptor cells,
which convert light to electrical signals that are interpreted by
the brain. The pigmented epithelial cells also ingest excess
photoreceptor cells.
   In the diseased rats, the pigmented epithelial cells die, which
eventually leads to the death of the photoreceptor cells.
   To cure the disease before the photoreceptor cells died, the
scientists cut slits in the back of the animals' eyes and injected
tiny drops of fluid containing healthy cells into the area where
the pigmented cells normally grow.
   The research was conducted by two groups working independently:
James E. Turner and Linxi Li of Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, N.C.; and Peter Gouras and his colleagues at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York.
   Turner has operated on more than 200 rats, the Times said. In
every case, the transplanted cells survived and prevented the
photoreceptor cells from dying.
   Gouras said he and his colleagues hoped to try the retinal cell
transplants on monkeys next. Turner said he would try them on
rabbits and monkeys and would try implanting greater numbers of
cells in rats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0075 </DOCNO>
