<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Debate-Veep 1stLd-Writethru a0459 09-26 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Veep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Over Veep Choices: Bush Defends Quayle, Dukakis Questions
Abilities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs pvs 6th graf bgng, ``Did I sense,'' with
Quayle comments.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Michael Dukakis and George Bush had
one of their more feisty debate exchanges when discussing running
mates, with Bush declaring he had ``full confidence'' in Dan Quayle
while Dukakis scoffed at the prospect of ``President Quayle.''
   The debate over running mates came late in the 90-minute clash
Sunday night between Democrat Dukakis and Republican Bush. Bush had
not mentioned Quayle at all before he was asked to explain his
choice; Dukakis twice before briefly had mentioned Bentsen when
discussing his views on foreign policy.
   Bush, in defending Quayle, praised the Indiana senator's defense
credentials and noted his leadership role in winning passage of a
job training measure. ``I believe he will be outstanding,'' said
Bush, who then said the media had subjected Quayle to
``outrageous'' and ``brutal'' scrutiny of his academic and military
records.
   ``He has my full confidence,'' Bush said.
   But the vice president also created an opening for Dukakis when,
in an effort to paint the Massachusetts governor as naive on
foreign policy and defense, said there were three people on the
Republican ticket who were well-versed in those areas. Bush
obviously meant to say three people among the four candidates, but
Dukakis seized the opportunity.
   ``Did I sense a desire that maybe Lloyd Bentsen ought to be your
running mate whe you said that the three people on your ticket?''
Dukakis said to laughter from the audience at Wake Forest
University.
   Quayle, interviewed outside his suburban McLean, Va., home
Sunday night, said he was undisturbed by the questions that Dukakis
raised about his qualifications.
   ``When the American people come to know Dan Quayle ... they will
feel more comfortable,'' Quayle said. ``They've been told a lot of
inaccuracies, a lot of rumors that proved to be groundless.''
   Quayle said Bush had telephoned him after the debate and was
``very upbeat, for a very good reason.'' He said Bush was clearly
victorious ``because he was able to depict Michael Dukakis as out
of the mainstream.''
   Dukakis, who includes the Quayle selection in his attack on
Bush's judgment, used most of his rebuttal time after Bush defended
Quayle on that track and to praise the experience and maturity of
Bentsen.
   But he also delivered a biting criticism of Quayle, a second
term senator who was little known nationally before Bush tapped him
for the vice presidential spot in August.
   ``I doubt very much that Dan Quayle was the best qualified
person for that job,'' Dukakis said. ``And as a matter of fact, I
think for most people the notion of `President Quayle' is a very,
very troubling notion.''
   Bush did not criticize Bentsen but did attack Dukakis for making
fun, in his campaign appearances, of Quayle's given name, J.
Danforth Quayle.
   ``Do you know who J. Danforth was?'' Bush asked of his rival.
``He was a man that gave his life in World War II. So ridiculing a
person's name is a little beneath this process.''
</TEXT>
