<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Turkey-Referendum     09-26 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Referendum,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ozal To Remain Premier After Referendum Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal said today he would
remain in office and continue to serve ``with vigor and
enthusiasm'' even though Turkish voters rejected a referendum
sponsored by his government.
   Opposition parties turned Sunday's proposed constitutional
amendment _ which called for moving municipal elections from March
1989 to November of this year _ into a vote of confidence on Ozal
and his free-market economic policies. The premier said earlier he
would resign ``depending upon the outcome.''
   With 86 percent of the votes counted, the state television
reported early today that 65 percent of the 26.5 million eligible
voters opposed the amendment and 35 percent were in favor of it.
   But Ozal said in a televised statement today that he would
remain premier until the next general elections in 1992.
   He said he was satisfied with the result of the vote, since the
number of ``yes'' votes were about the same as the 36 percent his
Motherland Party won in general elections 10 months ago. The result
gave the party a 290-seat majority in the 450-member Parliament.
   But opposition leaders Erdal Inonu of the Social Democrat
Populist Party and former premier Suleyman Demirel, who heads the
centrist True Path Party, said today's result was a defeat for the
61-year-old premier.
   ``He has not received the support he was seeking,'' said Inonu.
   ``This government has been rejected by the people _ tomorrow
there will be new political conditions in Turkey,'' said Demirel.
   During the pre-referendum campaign, the opposition emphasized
the country's 78 percent inflation, the rising foreign debt _ which
doubled in the past five years to $42 billion _ and low wages.
   Ozal responded that under his tenure, Turkey has enjoyed high
economic growth, which has averaged an annual 7.5 percent in the
past two years and is projected at 7.2 percent for 1988. He said
the economic boom has brought Turkey new housing, roads, dams, and
communications systems.
   The premier called on voters to avoid returning to the turbulent
decade that ended in a 1980 military takeover, which was
accompanied by an economic crisis and political violence.
   Ozal, who launched Turkey's economic recovery program as deputy
premier under the military government, became premier when his
party won in the 1983 elections that restored civilian rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
