<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Housing     09-26 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Housing,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Designates Neighborhoods To Be Integrated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today for the
first time publicly identified ``whites only'' neighborhoods that
could be opened legally to people of all races.
   Tens of thousands of non-whites already live illegally in
districts of Johannesburg, Cape Town, Durban and Port Elizabeth,
which Constitutional Planning Minister Chris Heunis cited as areas
likely to be integrated.
   In a session of Parliament today, Heunis reintroduced three
bills under the Group Areas Act, which segregates all neighborhoods
by race and sharply increases the penalties for violations of the
act.
   The bills, viewed as an attempt to appease conservative white
voters before the nationwide municipal elections on Oct. 26, were
first introduced last month, but were withdrawn after
anti-apartheid groups and black leaders condemned it.
   The new legislation, however, also proposes to legalize a
limited number of multiracial neighborhoods that have developed in
recent years as whites moved out of urban neighborhoods. The
measure has been denounced by the Conservative Party, which is
expected to makes gains in the elections at the expense of
President P.W. Botha's National Party.
   The Group Areas bills created a political furor in Parliament
last month, when the white chamber approved them, but the
mixed-race and Asian chambers boycotted parliamentary discussions
in protest. The government withdrew the bills, but decided to
reintroduce them after the two chambers agreed to end their boycott.
   ``When the colored (mixed-race) and Indian communities tell me
that the Group Areas Act has hurt them, I say in all earnestness:
`I hear you,''' Heunis said today at a joint session of the three
chambers.
   But Heunis said the government remained committed to protecting
``group rights'' _ a phrase for policies which allow whites-only
schools, hospitals and residential areas.
   The mixed-race and Asian chambers are expected to reject all
three bills, including the proposal to allow multiracial
neighborhoods. Leaders of the chambers say the Group Areas Act
should be repealed, rather than amended.
   However, the National Party _ which controls Parliament's white
chamber _ has the power to enact the legislation even if the
proposed bills are rejected by the other two chambers.
   Under South Africa's policy of apartheid, the nation's 26
million blacks are not represented in Parliament and has not vote
in national affairs, which are controlled by the 5 million whites.
   Among the areas mentioned by Heunis as candidates for
multiracial status were Johannesburg's Hillbrow and Joubert Park
neighborhoods and Cape Town's District Six, from which tens of
thousands of mixed-race people were evicted in 1966 after it was
designated for whites only.
   A surplus of housing in white urban neighborhoods is accompanied
by a severe shortage of housing in non-white areas, and thousands
of Asians, blacks and people of mixed race have been moving into
districts vacated by whites.
   The Group Areas Act has been the most hotly contested issue in
the municipal elections.
   The anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party is the only major
white party that opposes the Group Areas Act, the most hotly
contested issue in the municipal elections. Last week, a National
Party member of Johannesburg's city council said he would lobby for
multiracial areas in wards that vote for the Progressive Federal
Party, but would seek to keep other white neighborhoods segregated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
