<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Mafia     09-26 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Mafia,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magistrate And Son Murdered In Mafia Vendetta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALTANISETTA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sicilian magistrate who sentenced
two Mafia bosses to life imprisonment was ambushed and killed along
with this 35-year-old son, police said today.
   Antonio Saetta, 66, and his son Stefano were killed by gunmen
who stopped their car on a road outside Caltanisetta as they drove
home Sunday night, police said.
   Investigators said the ambush appeared to be a Mafia vendetta
for the 1985 sentencing of brothers Michele and Salvatore Greco.
   Saetta was the presiding judge at the trial of the Grecos,
described as the bosses of a powerful Mafia ring. Saetta sentenced
the brothers to life in prison after they were convicted of
masterminding the killing of Judge Rocco Chinnici, who had been
investigating their activities.
   An Interior Ministry spokesman in Rome called Saetta's killing
``a clear challenge to the state'' that recently named a special
investigator, Judge Domenico Sica, to crack down on the Mafia and
its financial links in Sicily.
   Saetta, who had been transferred from the court in Azzizes to
one in Palermo following the trial of the Grecos and their
associates, became the eighth magistrate killed by the Mafia in
Sicily since 1968.
   Police said the killers shadowed Saetta and his son as they left
the nearby resort of Canicatti, where they had spent the weekend
with relatives.
   In a deserted part of the Agrigento-Caltanisetta road in central
Sicily, the killers rammed and stopped the judge's car and fired at
least 20 shots through the windows.
   Police said the judge was hit by three bullets in the head and
two in the chest and died instantly. His son was also hit by
several bullets.
   An anonymous caller tipped police about two hours after the
killings, sources reported.
</TEXT>
