<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence     09-26 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weekend Spate of Gang Violence: Four Dead, Seven Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a weekend when residents marched to
reclaim streets from violent gangs, four people died and seven
others were wounded including a pregnant woman shot as part of an
apparent gang initiation rite, police said.
   Residents of south-central Los Angeles on Saturday marched to
protest gang violence in their neighborhoods.
   ``The walk that we made was simply to say to those people who
want to intimidate us that we won't be intimidated,'' said Claudia
Ghess of the South Central Organizing Committee. ``They think they
have possession of those streets. We want them to know we plan to
take charge of those streets.''
   But that day in the area, one man was killed and three others
were wounded in separate drive-by shootings, authorities said.
   A teen-age gang member on Saturday night walked into the
apartment complex of Marlene Garcia, 19 and three months pregnant,
and opened fire, police Sgt. Ralph Freeze said Sunday.
   Ms. Garcia, sitting on the front steps of the complex, was shot
in the lower back and was in stable condition Sunday at County-USC
Medical Center, Freeze said. Three 16-year-olds were arrested and
booked for investigation of attempted murder.
   The attack was believed to be part of a gang initiation, police
said. The boy who fired the shots was believed to be trying to
impress other gang members.
   A second pregnant woman and two men were wounded Saturday by
pellets from shotgun blasts fired from a passing car, authorities
said.
   The expectant mother, who wasn't identified, and the two men
were treated for minor pellet wounds resulting from the incident on
a Westlake street, Sgt. Richard Roach said.
   In other shootings, one man was killed in a possible
gang-related confrontation, a teen-ager was killed in an argument
among fellow gang members and a pedestrian was fatally shot in a
suspected gang-related incident.
   The highest weekend death toll from gang violence in Los Angeles
this year occurred during the weekend before Labor Day, when 11
died.
</TEXT>
