<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Indians-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0553 09-26 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indians-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0553,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Pair Accused In Newspaper Hostage-Taking Head to Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with request for delay in trial
turned down. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The defendants...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Indian activists went to court today
for their trial on charges of taking hostages at a newspaper in
what they say was an effort to spotlight local corruption, but one
was without his regular lawyer.
   Defense lawyers have said they will argue that Eddie Hatcher and
Timothy Jacobs acted out of necessity when up to 20 people were
taken hostage at The Robesonian on Feb. 1.
   U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle today denied a request for a
continuance in the trial, even though Hatcher's attorney, William
Kunstler, was not present because he is involved in another trial
in New York. Hatcher had said repeatedly he would not participate
in the trial without Kunstler.
   ``I will not be there,'' Kunstler, famed for his defense of
leftist causes, said last week. ``Eddie will not have a lawyer. He
will, I think ... stand up and tell that jury at every opportunity
that he is there without a lawyer.''
   When he granted a third delay in the case Aug. 1, Boyle warned
Hatcher that he did not intend to continue the case again and said
another lawyer should be prepared to begin the trial if Kunstler
was not present.
   But lawyer Barry Nakell asked the judge today to delay the trial
until Oct. 18, when Kunstler should be through with the other case.
Hatcher has said he does not want Nakell as his attorney at the
trial, though Nakell has represented him in some other hearings.
   The judge turned down Nakell's request.
   The defendants are charged with hostage-taking and manufacturing
illegal weapons.
   Hatcher, 31, and Jacobs, 20, have never denied that they took
over the offices of The Robesonian in Lumberton, but say they did
so to draw attention to their allegations of discrimination against
minorities and drug trafficking by local law enforcement agencies.
   They say they were driven to commit ``an act of desperation''
because their knowledge of the drug trafficking had put their lives
in danger.
   ``We have a necessity defense in this case ... (which) involves
showing that neither Timothy or Eddie had any legal alternatives to
what they did and that they were in fear of their lives on Feb.
1,'' Bob Warren, Jacobs' attorney, said last week.
   The 10-hour siege at the newspaper ended after Gov. Jim Martin
agreed to form a state task force to investigate their charges.
   But Hatcher and Jacobs, who say they are Tuscarora Indians, met
only once with the task force, which issued a preliminary report
saying it had found little evidence to back up their charges.
   Hatcher, Jacobs and their supporters said the task force did not
do a thorough investigation and that potential witnesses would not
testify without federal and state immunity.
   The defendants' lawyers have conducted their own investigation
and say they have potential witnesses who could back up the charges
of official wrongdoing.
   Hatcher disappeared Aug. 31 after a federal appeals court
revoked his bond. Jacobs surrendered to marshals the same day.
Hatcher was arrested at Raleigh-Durham Airport one week ago when he
stepped off a plane with a Kunstler associate.
</TEXT>
