<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0537 09-26 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0537,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede: WINSTON-SALEM, N.C.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aides Declare Victory, See Campaign Boost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Dukakis comments, picks up 7th graf pvs,
As for x x x</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said today the first
presidential debate provided the ``the best moments of the whole
campaign,'' and his aides declared him the decisive winner over
Republican rival George Bush.
   ``The American people finally had the chance to look beyond the
slogans and labels, the photo opportunities and the flag-waving,
and get down to the real issues,'' Dukakis said in remarks prepared
for a rally here, his first stop after leaving the debate site,
Winston-Salem, N.C.
   ``We heard a lot of talk last night from Mr. Bush about the
mainstream. But it's clear that he's willing to leave American
families high and dry,'' Dukakis said.
   ``What happened last night was long overdue. Those 90 minutes
were the best moments of this whole campaign,'' he said.
   Susan Estrich, Dukakis' campaign manager, said the Dukakis
campaign's polls ``showed us winning the debate decisively.''
   Estrich, at a briefing in North Carolina before Dukakis departed
on a campaign swing to Ohio and New Jersey, said Dukakis succeeded
in ``dominating the debate virtually from beginning to end,
speaking to the issues of concern to voters sitting around their
kitchen tables.''
   As for Bush, she said, the vice president ``failed to dominate
the debate at all.''
   Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaign chairman, said the Democratic
nominee ``kept George Bush on defense all night long. He took the
issues, he discussed the issues, he was putting in the innovative
proposals that the working Americans are worried about, their
concerns and anxieties. And I thought that Bush was shaky all night
long.''
   With the first debate behind him, Dukakis was heading out to
campaign in key industrial states that are likely to determine the
outcome of the election.
   On his schedule today were stops in Cleveland and Jersey City,
N.J.
   By the end of the week, the Democratic nominee also will
campaign in Illinois, Pennsylvania, New York, Texas and California.
   On Sunday night, Dukakis went from the debate on the campus of
Wake Forest University to a rally a few miles away in the
Winston-Salem Convention Center where he told supporters, ``The
message tonight that we were able to convey .. was that the
Democratic Party and the Democratic ticket are prepared to provide
leadership on the real challenges that face this country and the
real concerns of Americans all over this country.''
   ``This is going to be a tough, competitive stretch drive,'' he
said of the final six weeks of the presidential campaign.
   Dukakis and Bush will debate again in Los Angeles on Oct. 13 or
Oct. 14, the exact date hinging on the baseball playoff schedule.
   Their running mates _ Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and Republican Dan
Quayle _ will debate in Omaha, Neb., on Oct. 5.
   The Massachusetts governor delivered his strongest response to
date when Bush raised what has become known as the Pledge of
Allegiance issue. Bush has scored heavily by attacking Dukakis for
vetoing legislation that would have required recitation of the
pledge in Massachusetts public schools.
   Bush raised it again during the debate and said he was not
questioning his opponent's patriotism.
   ``Of course, the vice president is questioning my patriotism,''
Dukakis responded. ``I don't think there's any question about that.
And I resent it, I resent it.''
   Bush delivered an impassioned defense of his choice of Quayle
for the Republican ticket.
   ``I'm putting my faith in a whole generation of young people who
are in their thirties and in their forties,'' the vice president
said.
   ``Judge the man on his record, not on a lot of rumors and
innuendo,'' he said, chiding Dukakis for referring to the Indiana
senator as ``J. Danforth Quayle.''
   ``Do you know who J. Danforth was?'' Bush said. ``He was a man
that gave his life in World War II. So ridiculing a person's name
is a little beneath this process.''
   Dukakis didn't give an inch. He said that ``for most people the
notion of `President Quayle' is a very, very troubling notion
tonight.''
   Dukakis also was asked to respond to the perception that he is
``passionless, technocratic _ the smartest clerk in the world.''
   ``I care deeply about people,'' he responded. ``All people,
working people, working families, people all over this country who
in some cases are living from paycheck to paycheck.''
   He recalled his 1978 defeat in the Democratic gubernatorial
primary when he was running for a second term.
   ``Defeat is sometimes an important lesson,'' he said. ``I think
I'm a much better governor today. I think I'm a much better person,
a much better listener. I think I'll be a much better president for
having gone through that experience.''
</TEXT>
