<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreeSurgeries     09-26 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Free Surgeries,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Staff Gives To Mexican Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON L. JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deformed and disfigured people came from around
Mexico to a San Diego hospital, lured by promises of better
function and self-esteem, and returned across the border with new
faces, ears or improved hands.
   And it didn't cost them a cent, thanks to churches, a hospital,
a San Diego charity and dozens of medical workers who donated a
20-hour day to conduct back-to-back operations.
   Only those who have seen the medical needs of the poor south of
the border could understand, said nurse Pat Robinson, who
participated in the reconstructive surgical marathon Saturday at
Mercy Hospital.
   ``I have never seen so many children with so many deformities
that haven't been taken care of,'' said Ms. Robinson, who's been in
the field for 30 years.
   Her patients included a 6-year-old girl with a club hand, a
17-year-old girl with a peg of tissue instead of an ear and a
10-month-old baby with a cleft lip dividing her face up to her
eyes. Other patients had club feet and one needed a hip replacement.
   She recalled an operation in which doctors repaired a
40-year-old woman's cleft lip under local anesthesic.
   ``After we finished with her surgery, we helped her hold a
mirror up. She started crying,'' said Ms. Robinson, 50. ``The
change was so noticeable. She felt so good about how she looked.
   ``The doctor gave her his card and she clutched it to her heart.
We all started crying, she was so overcome by gratitude.''
   For the girl without an ear, doctors took a piece of rib and
shaped it to form the external part of the hearing organ. ``That
one took about 2{ hours,'' Ms. Robinson said.
   About 20 surgeons, 12 anesthesiologists and more than 100
nurses, support staff and volunteers participated in the lengthy
session, said Laura Avallone, the hospital's spokeswoman.
   About 30 patients came from as far south as the Mexican state of
Oaxaca, south of Mexico City, for Saturday's operations, Ms.
Robinson said.
   Local churches provided housing the night before the surgeries,
which would have cost upwards of $500,000, officials said. Drug
companies donated all required pharmaceutical materials. The
hospital donated rooms and equipment.
   All but four were returned to Mexico on Sunday with whatever
medical instructions and drugs they needed, Ms. Avallone said. Some
were taken to a Tijuana hospital for observation but most went
home. Those who remained hospitalized at Mercy were in good
condition, she said.
   It was the second such surgical marathon for Mexican patients at
Mercy Hospital, organized with Coad, a San Diego-based
international charitable organization. In February, about 35
patients underwent reconstructive operations.
   Coad, ``helper'' in Spanish, was founded 15 years ago by John M.
Martin of San Diego, a former San Jose construction mogul who
discovered the need for such medical help during a fishing trip in
Mexico.
   He says he has since taken surgical teams to Mexico and Central
America to operate on thousands of people.
   For surgery in San Diego, Martin travels around Mexico to locate
patients with scars or birth defects, takes care of paperwork
including visas, and provides bus transportation.
   ``You could say I have a Christian commitment, but that is not
the real reason _ I do it because I like to do it,'' Martin told
The Tribune of San Diego last week.
   Though weary from Saturday's long hours, Ms. Robinson said she
looked forward to the next Coad event for Mexican patients,
tentatively scheduled for February 1989.
   ``I feel I have something to give and they need it so badly,''
she said. ``It changes their lives. They can be more like a normal
person and feel better about themselves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
