<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Europe,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush-Dukakis Debate Heard Live In Some Parts of Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate-Who Won, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate between U.S. presidential candidates
George Bush and Michael Dukakis was broadcast live in some West
European countries for those sufficiently addicted to U.S. politics
to stay up long after midnight.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. televised the entire debate live
as did Austrian Television and Italy's state-run RAI network. The
Austrians aired it in English, while RAI provided simultaneous
translation into Italian.
   In West Germany, the U.S. Armed Forces Network broadcast it live
on radio and television.
   The debate was held too late for Europe's morning newspapers to
comment, but two afternoon dailies were lukewarm.
   ``Overall, Mr. Bush came out better than many people had
expected; but the debate will not have altered the growing
impression, abroad as well as among many Americans, that for the
most powerful job in the world the choice is between two
mediocrities,'' said London's conservative Evening Standard.
   ``This may be a harsh judgment, but if there are impressive
personalities behind the public faces of the two candidates, then
it is high time they escaped from the suffocating embrace of their
marketing men and revealed the humanity behind the hype,'' it said.
   In Paris, the left-leaning Le Monde said there was ``no evident
winner, no revelation on the character of the candidates, and
absolutely nothing new as to their intentions.''
   In his broadcast, Italian TV correspondent Antonello Marescalchi
said: ``The result of the Bush-Dukakis match is still uncertain.
Dukakis was probably better than Bush, but there was no knockout.''
   He added: ``The vice president and the governor said nothing
new. Every issue had already been discussed during the conventions
in Atlanta and New Orleans, and during the electoral campaign.''
</TEXT>
