<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Party     09-26 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Party,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Meeting Expected To Slow Down Open-Market Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders convened a meeting Monday
that was expected to call for a slowdown in market-oriented reforms
that are fueling inflation and economic turmoil in China.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said 162 members of the
175-member Central Committee and several hundred other leading
party members gathered at the Great Hall of the People for the
five-day meeting.
   The agency said General Secretary Zhao Ziyang delivered a speech
outlining China's troubled economic reforms over the next two years.
   Zhao, it said, dealt with ``improving the economic environment
and rectifying the economic order,'' catchwords for a more cautious
stance emphasizing stability rather than new initiatives in the
country's drive to reduce central planning and tie production to
free-market forces.
   Zhao discussed ways to promote reform in a ``planned way and
under unified leadership'' _ an apparent reference to reported
differences within the party on how to cope with current economic
problems.
   The 20 percent inflation _ spurred by rising consumer demand,
profiteering and government moves to end some price subsidies _ has
become a major source of complaint among urban residents.
   Corruption is rampant, industrial output is increasing at double
the rate the economy can sustain, and local governments have
ignored orders from Beijing to cut back on unauthorized spending.
   Fears of further price increases have led to panic buying and
runs on banks in August, with retail sales almost 40 percent higher
than in the same month in 1987.
   Chinese leaders insist they will not turn their backs on reforms
that have significantly improved the lives of millions of Chinese
over the past decade. But they have admitted the reforms have hit a
shoal of doubt and confusion.
   The government has tried to calm consumers and cool off the
economy by promising there will be no more price increases this
year, and by tightening money supplies and linking interest rates
to the inflation rate.
   Vice Premier Yao Yilin, who oversees economic policy, told
visiting Soviet officials on Friday that China will not lift
controls on the prices of grain and other staples. But the policy
of freezing low prices has discouraged farmers from growing grain
crops.
   At the party meeting, Zhao also discussed ``strengthening party
leadership in order to bring the party's political advantage into
full play,'' the Xinhua report said. The 47 million-member party is
trying to improve an image tarnished by corruption within its ranks
and to restore its prestige among a population disenchanted with
ideology and political infighting.
   The Central Committee session may give some indication if Zhao,
the most ambitious of China's top reformers, has been politically
damaged as a result of the nation's economic problems.
   There has been widespread speculation that Premier Li Peng, the
more cautious head of China's government, has eclipsed Zhao as the
nation's top economic planner amid government concerns that a fast
pace of reform could cause economic and social chaos.
   Western diplomats, however, say there is no indication that
Zhao, although he may have lost some prestige, is in serious
political trouble.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-USMIAs     09-26 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US MIAs,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teams Search For U.S. MIAs In Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials began
searching northern Vietnamese villages Monday for people who may
have seen plane crashes in which American soldiers were lost more
than 15 years ago, an official said.
   Two joint teams including U.S. military experts drove to the
areas near the capital of Hanoi to try to resolve the fates of
seven airmen downed during the Vietnam War, said Maj. Thomas J.
Boyd, spokesman for the U.S. Pacific Command.
   He said the teams headed out in jeeps the Americans flew in from
Honolulu the previous day, along with metal detectors and other
equipment including forensic instruments in case human remains were
found during the 10-day search.
   ``This is the first joint activity that involves tracking down
of missing in action (MIA) cases,'' he said. ``The teams are
investigating loss incidents that occurred and trying to interview
individuals who may possess information surrounding the incidents.''
   He said the two sides may later excavate any warplane crash
sites that are found during the investigation.
   Previously, the only significant joint field activity was in
late 1985, when U.S. soldiers and Vietnamese state workers dug up
the wreckage of a U.S. B-52 bomber just outside Hanoi but found no
remains.
   Boyd said the teams will try to gather evidence such as the
soldiers' personnel effects and local government reports of the
incidents.
   He said the teams will search an area in Bac Thai and Vinh Phu
provinces, 40 miles northwest of Hanoi, and in Lang Son and Ha Bac
provinces 30 miles to the northeast of the capital. They may later
investigate a third area southeast of Hanoi, he said.
   Boyd said the U.S. side brought in eight motorcycles for the
Vietnamese to scout villages before the joint teams arrive.
   The seven cases are among 70 ``discrepancy cases'' the United
States has asked Vietnam to resolve urgently, claiming there is
evidence the men survived and came under Vietnamese control.
   Washington says it has no evidence they remain alive 15 years
after U.S. forces withdrew from Vietnam.
   ``We hope to accomplish many more joint investigation operations
in Vietnam during this initial 90-day period of joint activity and
continue beyond that time until this issue is resolved as fully as
possible,'' said a statement from the U.S. team leader, Lt. Col.
Joe Harvey. ``We are prepared to provide four teams, if Vietnam
agrees.''
   Harvey earlier called the project a significant breakthrough,
and said joint investigations could resolve all 70 cases.
   A total of 2,393 Americans listed as MIA in the war -- 1,757 in
Vietnam, 547 in Laos, 83 in Cambodia and six in China.
   The war, which cost 58,000 American lives, ended when communist
North Vietnam defeated U.S.-backed South Vietnam in April 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-UnemploymentInsurance Bjt   09-26 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unemployment Insurance, Bjt,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says Unemployment Insurance System Endangered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unemployment insurance system has enough
reserves to last only five months in a severe recession and would
have to borrow billions of dollars from the federal government to
keep paying benefits, congressional watchdogs said Monday.
   Because states had to borrow $11.8 billion to keep paying
benefits during the 1981-82 recession, most have tightened
eligibility requirements so much that only one of every four
jobless workers in October of last year received unemployment
checks, the General Accounting Office said in a report.
   ``The average proportion of unemployed receiving benefits during
the 1980s has fallen by about 30 percent since the 1950s,'' the GAO
said. ``In 1952, nearly 55 percent of unemployed civilian workers
were receiving benefits; by 1986, only 32 percent received
benefits.''
   Although demographic changes in the workforce explain part of
the decline, the report said the Reagan administration's emphasis
on states repaying the $11.8 billion they borrowed in 1981-82 has
caused at least 44 of them to tighten eligibility requirements.
   As of 1986, the GAO said, state unemployment insurance trusts
still owed the U.S. Treasury a total of $4.8 billion. The combined
state-federal system still had reserves of about $19.4 billion last
year, enough to last about five months in a severe recessions, the
watchdogs said.
   But, they added, recent recessions have tended to last at least
12 months, and the Labor Department recommends that each state
carry sufficient reserves to pay benefits for 18 months.
   While 39 states had adequate reserves in 1969, no more than two
states have had sufficient funds in any year since 1976 to deal
with a recession without borrowing from the federal Treasury, the
report said.
   The state-federal system was created as part of the New Deal to
help cushion the blow of the Depression on laid off workers. The
program is designed to be self-sufficient, with the federal
government assumes the cost of administration while states pay the
actual benefits with funds raised through a payroll tax on
employers.
   Because states have been trimming benefits and tightening
eligibility, the GAO questioned the system's ability to ``stabilize
the economy and mitigate the effects of income loss suffered by the
unemployed'' in the next recession.
   The report suggested that unless Congress somehow eases the
burden, the country may see ``greater tax increases and larger
benefit reductions in the regions that have experienced the least
favorable economic conditions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Reagan-UN-Text     09-26 1191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan-UN-Text,1200-up</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS, New York (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of remarks by
President Reagan to the 43rd General Asssembly Monday.
   Mr. President, Mr. Secretary-General, distinguished delegates.
Half a world away _ far from this place of peace _ the firing, the
killing, the bloodshed in two merciless conflicts have for the
first time in recent memory diminished. After adding terrible new
names to the roll call of human horror _ names such as Halabja,
Maidan Shahr, and Spin Buldak _ there is today hope of peace in the
Persian Gulf and Afghanistan.
   So, too, in the highlands and coastal cities of southern Africa
_ places of civil war, places of occupation by foreign troops _
talk of peace is heard, peace for the tortured nation of Angola.
Six thousand five hundred miles further east, in the Southeast
Asian country of Cambodia, there is hope now of a settlement, hope
now of the removal of Vietnam's occupying forces. And finally in
this hemisphere, where only 12 years ago one-third of the people of
Latin America lived under democratic rule, some 90 percent do so
today; and especially in Central America, nations such as El
Salvador, once thratened by the anarchy of the death squad and the
specter of totalitarian rule, now know the hope of self-government
and the prospect of eocnomic growth.
   And, another change, Mr. Secretary-General. A change that if it
endures may go down as one of the signal accomplishments of our
history _ a change that is cause for shaking of the head in wonder
_ is also upon us. A change going to the source of post-war
tensions, and to the once seemingly impossible dream of ending the
twin threats of our time _ totalitarianism and thermonuclear world
war.
   For the first, time, the differences between East and West _
fundamental differences over important moral questions dealing with
the worth of the individual and whether governments shall control
people or people control governments _ for the first time, these
differences ahve shown signs of easing. Easing to the point where
there are not just troop withdrawals from places like Afghanistan
but also talk in the East of reform and greater freedom of press,
of assembly, and of religion. Yes, fundamental differences remain.
But should talk of reform become more than that, should it become
reality _ there is the prospect of not only a new era in
Soviet-American relations but a new age of world peace. For such
reform can bring peace; history teaches and my country has always
believed that where the rights of the individual and the people are
enshrined, war is a distant prospect; for it is not people who make
war, governments do that.
   I stand at this podium then in a moment of hope. Hope, not just
for the peoples of the United States or the Soviet Union but for
all the peoples of the world. And hope, too, for the dream of peace
among nations, the dream that began the United Nations.
   Precisely because of these changes, today, the United Nations
has the opportunity to live and breathe and work as never before.
Already, you, Mr. Secretary-General, through your persistence,
patience, and unyielding will, have shown, in working toward peace
in Afghanistan and the Persian Gulf, how valuable the United
Nations can be. We salute you for those accomplishments.
   And in Geneva at this very hour, there are numerous negotiations
underway: multilateral negotiations at the Conference on
Disarmament as well as bilateral negotiations on a range of issues
between the Soviets and ourselves. And these negotiations, some of
them under U.N. auspices, involve a broad arms control agenda;
strategic offensive weapons; strategic defense and space; nuclear
testing; and chemical warfare _ whose urgency we have witnessed
anew in recent days.
   And, Mr. Secretary-General, the negotiators are busy _ and over
the past few years they have been engaged in more than an academic
exercise. There is movement. The logjam is broken. Only recently,
when the United States and the Soviet Union signed the INF
agreement, an entire class of U.S. and Soviet nuclear missiles was
eliminated for the first time in history. Progress continues on
negotiations to reduce, in massive number, strategic weapons with
effective verification. And talks will begin soon on conventional
reductions in Europe.
   Much of the reason for all of this goes back, I believe, to
Geneva itself; to the small chateau along the lake where I and the
General Secretary of the Soviet Union had the first of several
fireside chats _ exchanges characterized by frankness, but
friendliness, too. I said at the first meeting in Geneva that this
was a unique encounter between two people who had the power to
start World War III or to begin a new age of peace among nations.
And I also said peace conferences, arms negotiations, proposals for
treaties could make sense only if they were part of a wider context
_ a context that sought to explore and resolve the deeper,
underlying differences between us. I said to Mr. Gorbachev then, as
I have said to you before: Nations do not mistrust each other
because they are armed, they are armed because they mistrust each
other.
   In that place, by that peaceful lake in neutral Switzerland, Mr.
Grobachev and I did begin a new relationship based not just on
engagement over the single issue of arms control, but on a broader
agenda about our deeper differences; an agenda of human rights,
regional conflicts, and bilateral exchanges between our peoples.
Even on the arms control issue itself, we agree to go beyond the
past. To seek not just treaties that permit building weapons to
higher levels, but revolutionary agreements that actually reduced,
and even eliminated, a whole class of nuclear weapons.
   What was begun that morning in Geneva has shown results. In the
INF treaty. In my recent visit to Moscow. In my opportunity to meet
there with Soviet citizens and dissidents and speak of human
rights. And to speak, too, in the Lenin Hills of Moscow to the
young people of the Soviet Union about the wonder and splendor of
human freedom. The results of that morning in Geneva are seen in
peace conferences now under way around the world on regional
conflicts; and in the work of the U.N. here in New York as well as
in Geneva.
   But Mr. Secretary-General, history teaches caution; indeed, that
very building in Geneva, where important negotiations have taken
place _ the Geneva Accords on Afghanistan, the Iran-Iraq
negotiations, for example _ we see it today as stone-like testimony
to a failed dream of peace in another time. The Palais des Nations
was the headquarters of the League of Nations _ an institution that
was to symbolize an end to all war. And yet that institution and
its noble purpose ended with the Second World War, ended because
the chance for peace was not seized in the 1930s by the nations of
the world, ended because humanity did not find the courage to
isolate the aggressors, to reject schemes of government that serve
the state, not the people.
</TEXT>
