<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomeSales     09-26 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest-Wary Home Buyers Caused Sales Spurt in August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economic Outlook Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes
increased a modest 1.1 percent in August to the second-highest
level of the year as buyers tried to close purchases before
interest rates rose further, a real estate trade group said Monday.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
homes rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.67 million
units last month, following a sharp 5.0 percent decline in July.
Except for the 3.82 million rate in June, the August pace was the
fastest in 15 months.
   John Savacool, an economist with the Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., forecasting firm, said buyers completing sales in August
probably began looking for homes in May and June.
   ``That was just after rates started rising,'' he said. The
increase ``was a mild panic response to rising rates.''
   Fixed-rate mortgages dipped below 10 percent in February and
March and have since risen to about 10.5 percent as the Federal
Reserve Board fought inflation through higher interest rates. Many
economists expect rates to top 11 percent by early next year.
   ``Basically, what we're seeing here is the movement of
households into the market now to avoid what they perceive to be
deteriorating conditions. This has persisted through the summer,''
said John A. Tuccillo, chief economist of the real estate
association.
   He predicted sales will decline the rest of the year, bringing
them for all of 1988 to 3.45 million units, a 2.1 percent decline
from 1987.
   Savacool said stronger-than-expected resales so far this year
are a reflection of a robust economy in general.
   ``We've gone a nice long time with a good strong housing market.
... We've had a few declines, but we're still looking at a pretty
strong market,'' he said.
   After hitting a low of 1.99 million units in the recession year
of 1982, resales climbed to a record high of 3.56 million units in
1986. Savacool said sales likely would decline next year as
interest rates rise in the first half, but then recover in 1990.
   All of the strength in August came in the South, where sales
rose 4.4 percent to an annual rate of 1.42 million units,
rebounding from a 4.2 percent decline in July.
   In the Northeast, sales fell 2.9 percent to a 670,000-unit rate,
following a 6.8 percent decline in July.
   Sales were unchanged in the Midwest and West, at 910,000 units
and 650,000 units, respectively.
   Analysts have attributed the softening of sales in the Northeast
to high prices and to the effects of the October stock market crash
on employment in financial service industries.
   Sales in the Midwest, they say, are beginning to pick up, a
reflection of the strong manufacturing economy.
   The median price of a home rose from July to August by $600 to
$91,300, up 5.5 percent from a year ago when the median sales price
for an existing home was $86,500.
   The Northeast remained the costliest region of the country, with
a median sales price of $144,800 last month, up 6.7 percent from a
year ago. It was followed by a median price of $122,000 in the
West, up 6.0 percent from a year ago; $84,300 in the South, up 4.3
percent; and $70,500 in the Midwest, up 6.0 percent.
</TEXT>
