<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-26 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burmese Government Urges Student Dissidents To End Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials appealed Monday to parents
and teachers to stop dissident students from going underground and
linking up with ethnic insurgents to fight the military-led
government.
   Also Monday, the governing party chose a new name in what one
diplomat described as an attempt to change its tarnished image.
   In recent months, millions of people have engaged in street
demonstrations, strikes and other acts of opposition to the Burma
Socialist Program Party and the 26 years of political repression
and economic decline associated with it.
   State-run Radio Rangoon announced the party was changing its
name to the National Unity Party but did not say why.
   A Western diplomat in Bangkok, Thailand, speaking on condition
of anonymity, described the move as an attempt ``to change their
image (and) make a break with the past.''
   Students were among the leaders of the anti-government
demonstrations. Many have gone underground since Gen. Saw Maung
seized power from a civilian president in a military coup Sept. 18,
and security forces, by government count, have killed more than 250
civilians in the crackdown that followed.
   The government described many of those killed as looters.
   Diplomats believe far more than 250 people died during the
crackdown, including unarmed demonstrators who marched the day
after the coup.
   Rangoon remained quiet Monday, although troops stopped all cars
for security checks in the capital's downtown.
   ``Some students, being misled by unscrupulous people, have gone
underground and several others are preparing to follow suit,''
acting Education Minister Pe Thein said in an appeal broadcast
Monday night on state-run Radio Rangoon.
   ``Parents are asked to prevent their children from being misled
by unscrupulous people,'' he said.
   The army commander, Lt. Gen. Than Shwe, issued a similar radio
address, urging parents and teachers to stop students from going
into hiding or linking up with rebel groups seeking autonomy in
Burma.
   ``The army has no intention to take any action against students,
except those who had committed specific criminal offenses,'' he
said.
   A spokesman for Burma's strongest ethnic rebel group, the Karen
National Union, said Saturday that 90 student protesters fled to
his group's border base camps where they may get military training.
Border security officials in Thailand have reported students
crossing the frontier in recent days.
   The main ongoing anti-government activity is a general strike
that began Aug. 8 and has paralyzed Burma. Authorities have ordered
civil servants to return to work by Monday.
   Saw Maung has pledged to hold multiparty elections once peace is
restored to the impoverished nation, but he has set no timetable.
The last such elections were held in 1960.
   Three key opposition leaders _ Aung Gyi, Tin Oo and Aung San Suu
Kyi _ formed an umbrella group Saturday to unite the millions of
students, Buddhist monks, government workers and others struggling
for democracy. The group have called for a non-partisan interim
government to conduct the elections.
</TEXT>
