<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre-Priests     09-26 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre-Priests,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Priests Ordained By Lefebvre Bishop, First Since Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre's
traditionalist movement ordained seven new priests, the first since
it formally split with the Roman Catholic Church in June, a member
of the movement said Monday.
   The ordination Sunday was performed by one of the new bishops,
Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, with Lefebvre in attendance, said a
member of the St. Pius X Fraternity identifying himself as Brother
Michel.
   Six of the new priests are French and one is Italian, he said.
   Lefebvre, whose movement campaigns against reforms which he says
are spreading the ``cancer of liberalism'' in the church, on June
30 consecrated four bishops without papal approval.
   The Vatican condemned the consecrations as as act of schism, a
formal break with the Holy See. It announced that Lefebvre and the
four bishops were automatically excommunicated, or ejected from the
church, for refusing to submit to papal authority.
   It was the first schism since 1870, when Old Catholics split
with the Vatican over the dogma of papal infallibility.
   Lefebvre, 82, said he consecrated the bishops to ordain priests
in his movement after he died.
   He set up his first seminary in 1970 in the Swiss Alps,
rejecting several changes of the Second Vatican Council in 1962-65.
Lebebvre named it after Pope Pius X, who condemned the modernist
``Le Sillon'' movement in 1910.
   In 1976, Pope Paul VI suspended him from his priestly functions
after Lefebvre continued to celebrate Mass in Latin, rather than in
the vernacular.
   Lefebvre ignored the sanction. He has since ordained more than
220 traditionalist priests, and seminaries of his movement operate
worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NCGovernor Bjt   09-26 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NC Governor, Bjt,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics and Race on the Agenda in N.C. Governor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan has launched an
offensive depicting Republican Gov. Jim Martin's administration as
riddled with ethical shortcomings as polls show Martin pulling
ahead in his re-election bid.
   Martin, in turn, has questioned Jordan's respect for the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. and criticized the Democratic challenger for
telling blacks he could not support their views publicly for fear
of alienating ``the white redneck vote.''
   Martin, a former congressman who rode President Reagan's
coattails to victory in 1984, is the second GOP governor elected
this century in North Carolina and would be the first re-elected in
state history.
   Jordan is a 55-year-old lumber mill executive.
   In North Carolina, the governor and lieutenant governor run
separately. There have been disagreements between Martin and Jordan
throughout their term on issues from highway funding to veto power
for the governor.
   But their longest battle was over the budget, which in North
Carolina must be balanced. Jordan accused Martin of being
irresponsible in turning in an unbalanced budget. Martin responded
that he had no way of knowing when he submitted his budget that
changes in tax collections would make it unbalanced.
   Both are moderates with strong business ties who emphasize
education, highway expansion, economic growth and environmental
protection. They expect to spend $5 million each, a state record
for a two-candidate gubernatorial race.
   Some insiders said the average voter probably cannot see much
difference between the two.
   A Charlotte Observer poll Sept. 11-14 gave Martin 51 percent
support to Jordan's 43 percent among 802 voters surveyed. The
margin of error was plus or minus 3.5 percentage points. The
paper's poll in May saw the race as a dead heat.
   A survey for The News and Observer of Raleigh gave Martin an
even bigger lead. Of 806 likely voters interviewed Sept. 11-13, 47
percent favored Martin, 36.4 percent Jordan and 16.6 percent were
undecided. The margin of error was 3.5 points.
   In mid-September, Jordan went on the attack, accusing Martin of
``cynical manipulation of government for political purposes.''
   During his tenure Martin weakened the state financial disclosure
rule and stacked environmental protection commissions with
developers who had conflicts of interest, Jordan charged.
   He accused Martin of giving jobs to spouses of top aides, buying
a leading Democrat's support with a $329-a-day role as an adviser
and making one department ``a tax-paid campaign headquarters'' and
another ``a graveyard for defeated Republican candidates.''
   ``Part of leadership is who you surround youself with, whether
or not you protect the public trust,'' Jordan said. ``Jim Martin is
a nice fellow. But that doesn't mean he is a good governor.''
   Martin called the attacks ``a smear.''
   ``He (Jordan) is a decent enough guy that he will be ashamed of
himself for trying to impugn my ethics,'' Martin said.
   Merle Black, political science professor at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said Jordan was being more
aggressive because his positive approach had been ineffective.
   ``He's got to poke some holes in Martin's armor,'' Black said.
``He's got to develop reasons for the voters why Martin ought to be
removed from office.''
   Earlier this month, Jordan cried foul over a radio commercial
Martin aired on black-oriented stations.
   The spot consisted of a conversation in a fictitious barbershop.
It said Jordan declined Martin's offer to be chairman of a
commission planning activities for the state Martin Luther King Jr.
holiday. ``I wonder what Bob Jordan has against Martin Luther
King,'' it said.
   The ad did not mention that Jordan supported a 1987 bill
establishing the holiday while Martin opposed it. Jordan aides
called the commercial sleazy and a black commission member resigned
in protest.
   Earlier this year, Jordan told a group of black newspaper
executives he agreed with them on some issues that he could not
discuss publicly for fear of alienating ``the white redneck vote.''
   Martin has needled his opponent by telling audiences he wants
their votes ``regardless of your race, creed or the color of your
neck.''
   ``We're not writing off the black vote and we're not going to
let them (Democrats) take it for granted,'' the governor said.
   About 20 percent of the state's 3.2 million registered voters
are black.
</TEXT>
