<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerCyclist     09-26 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Cyclist,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swope Completes Cross-State Trip In Less Than 24 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former cancer patient says he surprised
even himself when he took less than a day to ride his bicycle
across most of the length of Kentucky to raise money for the
American Cancer Society.
   Brad Swope arrived in this northeastern Kentucky city about 4:30
a.m. EDT Monday, approximately 400 miles from Paducah in western
Kentucky, where he began his trek at 7 a.m. EDT Sunday.
   ``I thought I would take every minute of 24 hours. I think
everybody did,'' Swope said.
   ``There was a lot of energy and poignance attached to this
effort,'' he said. ``I couldn't have done it just to do it. I
needed a mission like the American Cancer Society.''
   Swope believed he reached his goal of raising $20,000 in
individual and corporate pledges for cancer research.
   ``The money hasn't been tallied,'' said crew chief Tim Omer,
``but we're expecting to meet our goal.''
   Swope, 38, of Louisville, experienced no health problems during
his ride but planned to rest for two to three days, Omer said.
   Swope was diagnosed as having malignant melanoma _ a form of
skin cancer _ three years ago. Doctors removed a growth from his
back and told him they felt certain they got it all, he said in a
pre-ride interview.
   The 5-foot-8, 136-pound athlete said he undertook the trip
because he ``wanted others to know that people can recover and be
cured from cancer.''
   Swope said hills and fog that covered much of the state Monday
morning made the last 50 miles of the trip the toughest. ``The
terrain was a nightmare,'' he said.
   Swope added that a 12 mph headwind in the western section of the
state caught him by surprise but, in the end, did not affect the
outcome.
   ``Cyclists are almost like sailors, we always watch the wind ...
especially if you weigh 136 pounds and are riding a 19-pound
bike,'' he said. ``But it wasn't the negative factor I thought it
would be. It just became a matter of time and distance.''
   Swope's wife Ann is glad it's over.
   ``It's been a long three months (of intense training),'' she
said. ``Now we can go on to other things.''
   ``It's going to be kind of strange to go home,'' she added.
``We'll probably sit there and say `Now what to we do?'''
</TEXT>
