<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Housing     09-26 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Housing,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Identifies Neighborhoods That May Be Integrated</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Botha-10 Years, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday
identified a group of ``whites only'' areas that could become South
Africa's first legally integrated neighborhoods.
   Tens of thousands of non-whites already live illegally in the
districts named in Parliament by Constitutional Planning Minister
Chris Heunis.
   Heunis listed districts in and near Johannesburg, Cape Town,
Durban and Port Elizabeth when he reintroduced a package of
legislation dealing with the Group Areas Act, which segregates all
neighborhoods by race.
   Neighborhoods are to become multiracial only where a majority of
residents approve or where integration has occurred on a de facto
basis.
   The package also includes proposals to tighten enforcement of
the act in areas that remain segregated.
   The entire package is opposed by most anti-apartheid
organizations, which say the Group Areas Act should be repealed
rather than modified.
   ``If we don't destroy it, it will destroy us,'' said Miley
Richards, a mixed-race Parliament member, in regard to the act.
   Among the areas mentioned by Heunis is Cape Town's District Six
_ a formerly multiracial area from which tens of thousands of
mixed-race people were evicted after it was declared whites-only in
1966.
   Also mentioned was Hillbrow, an area of high-rise apartment
buildings which is one of Johannesburg's liveliest and most
cosmopolitan neighborhoods.
   Hillbrow, like several of the areas named by Heunis, has become
home to many Asians, blacks and people of mixed-race moving into
inner-city housing vacated by whites who left for the suburbs.
   The proposal to allow multiracial neighborhoods has been
denounced by the extreme-right Conservative Party, which is
expected to makes gains in nationwide municipal elections next
month at the expense of President P.W. Botha's National Party.
   Anti-apartheid groups say the National Party is trying to
appease right-wing voters by proposing tougher enforcement of the
Group Areas Act, including sharply increased penalties for
violators.
   The government also is proposing to crack down on occupants of
substandard urban housing and illegal squatter camps _ moves which
could affect millions of blacks.
   Heunis said the government remained committed to protecting
``group rights'' _ its phrase for policies which allow whites-only
schools, hospitals and residential areas.
   The Group Areas bills created a furor in Parliament when the
government introduced them last month. The white chamber approved
the measures, but the smaller mixed-race and Asian chambers refused
to discuss the bills.
   The government withdrew the bills, but decided to reintroduce
them after the other chambers agreed to end their boycott.
   The nation's 26 million black majority is not represented in
Parliament.
   Under South Africa's constitution, the National Party _ which
controls Parliament's white chamber _ has the ability to enact
bills even if the other two chambers reject them.
   The Group Areas Act has been the most bitterly debated issue in
the municipal election campaign.
   Last week, a National Party city councilor in Johannesburg said
he would lobby for multiracial areas in wards that vote for the
anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party, but would seek to keep
other white neighborhoods segregated.
   The councilor, Danie van Zyl, was accused Monday of ``gutter
politics'' by Tony Leon, the Progressive Federal leader in
Johannesburg. Leon said his party favored intergration nationwide,
not just in selected neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
