<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1524EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     09-26 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Trying To Urge Rebel Restraint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has been trying to
persuade the Afghan rebels not to attack departing Soviet troops,
fearing this tactic could prompt Moscow to back off its promise to
be out of Afghanistan by Feb. 15, U.S. officials said Monday.
   This is among the issues that a newly appointed U.S. envoy to
the rebels, Edmund McWilliams, is expected to discuss with
insurgent leaders operating out of base camps in Pakistan, the
officials said.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley confirmed
McWilliams' appointment Monday. He is a career diplomat who once
served at the U.S. Embassy in Afghanistan.
   The U.S. officials, speaking on condition they not be
identified, said some Afghan rebel factions believe that attacks on
Soviet forces will ensure their prompt withdrawal. But they said
the administration holds the opposite view.
   ``We don't want Soviets to have any excuse to slow their
withdrawal or to attack the Afghans,'' one official said.
   He added that the final decision on this and other operational
matters is up to the rebels themselves.
   ``We don't control their fighting activities, but we do present
them with our views,'' the official said.
   On Friday, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
bitterly criticized the Pakistani role in supplying the Afghan
rebels, even through the Soviets are continuing with their
withdrawal schedule.
   He said Pakistan ``is behaving as though it has no obligations''
under the agreement in Geneva signed last April under which the
Soviets promised to pull out their troops over a nine-month period.
   He proposed a meeting at the United Nations this week involving
the representatives of the signatory countries: the Soviet Union,
the United States, Pakistan and Afghanistan.
   Asked about the proposal, Mrs. Oakley said Monday the
administration ``sees no need'' to have such a meeting.
   A U.S. official noted that the United States does not regard the
Afghan government as legitimate and that American participation at
a meeting with an Afghan official could be seen as a reversal of
that policy.
   The United States has maintained for the past five months that
it will show restraint in arming the Afghan rebels only if Moscow
does the same with its ally in Kabul.
   Since Moscow has been providing substantial support to the Kabul
government, the United States has continued its backing for the
insurgents, the official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PlasticsRecycling     09-26 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plastics Recycling,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies To Recycle Plastic Bottles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spotting a ``fundamental shift in society'' to
recycling, Dow Chemical Corp. and Domtar Inc. of Montreal said
Monday they will form a new company to recycle plastic bottles.
   The as-yet unnamed 50-50 venture will retrieve from the trash of
the two countries polyethylene terephthalate (PET) and high-density
polyethylene (HDPE) plastics, which make up about 90 percent of the
plastics used in bottles for milk, soft drinks and a variety of
other products such as powdered detergents.
   Domtar, a diversified chemical and paper firm based in Montreal,
already operates paper and plastics recycling businesses.
   Don Genson, business director for solid waste solutions for Dow,
said the new company would build a pilot plant and then a
commercial plant as early as 1990 at a location in the United
States or Canada still to be decided.
   Domtar will collect the raw material and use the bulk of the
output in its own industrial packaging and building materials
products. Dow will sell some of the material it retrieves, the two
companies said.
   Dow and Domtar declined to estimate their expected investments
or what the output would be used for or to detail the new
technology developed by Dow that will be used in the plant.
   ``We have about 20 projects being evaluated in the corporation
right now,'' said Warren Arseneau, Domtar new business manager.
   The size of the plant has not been decided, but the two firms
believe it will handle about 50 million pounds a year of PET and
HDPE.
   About 900 million pounds of PET is sold each year, with 150
million pounds recycled currently. About three-quarters of original
annual production goes into bottles; recycled material currently is
not used for food and drink because of the chance of contamination.
   HDPE is one of the most widely used plastics and 7.82 billion
pounds is produced every year, about 465 million pounds made by
Dow. Some 2.1 billion pounds goes into bottles for milk and other
household goods and another 342 million pounds goes into
miscellaneous food packaging. Only about 2 percent is recycled
   One recycler, Eaglebrook Plastics Co., estimates that four HDPE
bottles are thrown out for every PET bottle.
   ``We're entering the business confident that the waste
management issue will make a fundamental shift in society and
recycling systems will become the norm,'' Genson said.
   Domtar will deal with recycling centers in areas with PET bottle
return laws and ``waste recovery facilities expected to be
established by states developing new recylcing programs,'' the
companies said.
   Last week, the Environmental Protection Agency announced plans
to exhort, persuade, push and nudge U.S. residents to recycle 25
percent of their garbage and trash by 1992, up from 10 percent now,
because of the rapid exhaustion of landfill space in a throwaway
society.
   According to EPA, 10 states have passed laws requiring recycling
programs of one kind or another, with households separating
recyclable material from food when they put out their garbage. The
agency estimates that these programs operate in about 600 U.S.
communities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
