<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KidnappingAnniversary     09-26 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnapping Anniversary,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Clues in Mississippi Kidnap Case After Two Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months after the wife of one of
Mississippi's richest men was abducted from her home, authorities
said Monday they have no clues on the woman's welfare or
whereabouts.
   The last contact with Annie Laurie Hearin was a letter dated
Aug. 10 to her husband, Robert, president of Mississippi Valley Gas
Co. Hearin's worth reportedly exceeds $100 million.
   ``We are working just as hard and intensely at the end of two
months as we did at the end of two weeks,'' said Wayne Taylor, the
agent in charge of the FBI in Mississippi. ``We are just hoping it
will be resolved quickly.''
   The FBI said Mrs. Hearin was abducted sometime between 3 p.m.
and 4:30 p.m. July 26. Small spots of blood were found inside and
outside the front door of the two-story house in Jackson.
   A crudely phrased typewritten note left behind instructed Hearin
to pay an unspecified amount of money to people he allegedly had
wronged.
   The people named in the letter are current or former franchisers
with School Pictures of Mississippi Inc., of which Hearin was once
the largest stockholder. The company sued the 12 people in the
early 1980s, claiming the franchisers owed money from operating
loans, materials and film-processing fees.
   On Aug. 23, FBI officials announced that Hearin had followed the
instructions and that a total of about $1 million was mailed to the
12 named in the letter _ or their survivors _ on Aug. 16, the day
after Hearin received a handwritten letter from his wife. The note
had an Atlanta postmark.
   In addition to Mississippi Valley Gas, Hearin and partner Leon
Hess, a New Jersey oil man, own controlling interest in Lamar Life
Corp., which is Trustmark National Bank's largest shareholder.
</TEXT>
