<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-26 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabaret pianist Michael Feinstein performed
with other musicians and artists at a concert to raise money for a
group that helps people with AIDS.
   He also opened his wallet, writing a $7,500 check to the
non-profit Health Education Resources Organization.
   ``Lifesongs '88,'' which raised more than $170,000 for the
group, included performances Sunday night by singer Roberta Flack
and comedians Paula Poundstone and Kevin Rooney.
   The check from Feinstein, who returns to Broadway this fall to
perform classics by Cole Porter and George Gershwin in a five-week
run at the Booth Theater, wasn't the only surprise of the evening.
   Letters of support for the organization from President Reagan,
actress Elizabeth Taylor and singer Dionne Warwick were read during
the 3{-hour event.
   HERO provides an AIDS hot line, counseling and community
outreach and education programs for people with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andris Liepa, principal dancer with the Bolshoi
Ballet, will join American Ballet Theater for the 1988-89 season.
   Mikhail Baryshnikov, artistic director of ABT, welcomed Liepa,
26, to the company on Monday.
   ``The opportunity to invite Mr. Liepa to join ABT is yet another
demonstration of our two countries' determination to accelerate
cultural exchange in every possible way,'' Baryshnikov said.
   The artistic director of the Bolshoi Theater and the Soviet
Ministry of Culture gave permission for Liepa's year of performing
in the United States. ABT will tour this season to Orange County,
Calif., Miami Beach, Chicago, San Francisco, Los Angeles, San
Diego, Washington, D.C., and New York.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norwegian actress Liv Ullmann will visit Boston in
October to present a children's rights award to Kitty Dukakis for
her work with Asian refugees and the homeless.
   Ms. Ullmann is a member of the board of directors of
``Childhope,'' an international organization that defends
children's rights. The award will be presented Oct. 4 to Mrs.
Dukakis, wife of presidential candidate Michael S. Dukakis.
   The award, given for protection, respect and opportunity
extended to children, also will be presented to the Children's
Museum in Boston, which is celebrating its 75th anniversary.
