<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Earl Jones will again perform his Tony
Award-winning role in the play ``Fences.''
   ``The Tony makes more of a difference to my agent, because he
might be able to ask a better salary,'' Jones said recently.
   ``I'm sure it gives some of us a healthy confidence. Others of
us, it doesn't help at all. Actors are very fragile, you know. Shy?
Necessarily, yeah. I pretend a lot that I'm not.''
   Jones, 57, plays a man who could have been a major-league
baseball player, except that he was black. The character, Troy
Maxson, instead drives a garbage truck.
   Jones won the award last year, when the play was on Broadway.
The play opens here Wednesday at the James A. Doolittle Theater.
