<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0658,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Enters School And Starts Shooting; Pupil Killed; </HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with hospital spokesman saying
10 people suffering gunshot wounds; four being admitted; picking up
6th graf pvs, `Janitor Thad...'. SUBS last graf with 2 grafs with
background on May school shooting in Chicago suburb. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman entered an elementary school
today and calmly opened fire, killing one pupil, wounding 10 other
people and sending terrified youngsters fleeing into the woods,
authorities and witnesses said.
   Police have a suspect in custody, said Police Chief James
Coursey.
   Dan Branyon, spokesman at Self Memorial Hospital in Greenwood,
said eight children and two teachers were brought there, all
suffering from gunshot injuries. Six of the 10 were treated and
released and four were being admitted, including a child who was in
critical condition, he said.
   Children ran from the Oakland Elementary School into adjacent
woods when the man opened fire about 11 a.m., the The (Greenwood)
Index-Journal reported. Janitor Thad Barr, a witness to part of the
shooting, said he wasn't sure where it started, but the man was in
the lunchroom shooting then went down the hall shooting into
classrooms.
   Physical education aide Phillip Browning said after the suspect
quit shooting, he threw the pistol down and walked out of the
building as if nothing was wrong.
   Browning said he held the suspect until police arrived. He
described the man as a hefty white male in his mid-20s. ``He
remained calm and offered no resistance,'' Browning said.
   The school was evacuated as state troopers, police officers,
sheriff's deputies and school officials arrived. Officers and
volunteers combed the woods for a time after the shooting, looking
for children who might be hiding.
   Greenwood School District 50 Superintendent Bob Watson said
about noon that all he knew was that an unidentified man came into
the building and started shooting children and teachers. Watson
said it didn't appear the man had any connection with the school.
   Marilyn Amick, a first-grade teacher, said she and her students
fled the cafeteria after she saw a man waving a gun around. They
exited through a back door and ran toward the woods.
   Later, they joined other groups of students on the lawn in front
of the school, and teachers checked rolls to count the students.
Children were allowed to go home after they were accounted for.
Some volunteers called parents to let them know their children were
all right.
   Ms. Amick said she comforted her students by telling them
everyone in their class was OK.
   Greenwood is a town of about 22,000 in western South Carolina,
some 50 miles north of Augusta, Ga.
   Just last week, a man later identified Clem Henderson shot and
killed two people in a store in Chicago, then walked across the
street to a school, killing a school janitor and a policewoman
before he was killed by another police officer.
   In that case, no pupils or teachers were injured, but on May 20,
an 8-year-old boy was killed and six other people were injured when
a woman went on a rampage in and around a school in the affluent
Chicago suburb of Winnetka. The woman, Laurie Dann, killed herself
at the end of the spree.
</TEXT>
