<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Mines     09-26 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Mines,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Mines Found in Persian Gulf; Shipping Fears Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS VANDEGRIFT IN THE GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four mines have been
discovered in the northern Persian Gulf recently, and U.S. naval
officers say shipping will be endangered if rough winter weather
rips more mines from their moorings.
   U.S. Navy officers said Monday that three of the mines were
spotted drifting on the surface after breaking loose from their
seabed anchors.
   ``As winter approaches, the waters in the northern gulf get a
lot rougher, and that's when the anchored mines are more likely to
break away. They're also harder to spot,'' said one officer.
``We're very concerned that the situation is going to get worse in
the immediate future.''
   The warning was issued as this 3,600-ton missile frigate arrived
off Kuwait, escorting what U.S. military sources said could be the
next-to-last convoy of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers to be protected
by American warships.
   The White House announced President Reagan has decided to end
the ``tight escort'' of vessels, opting instead for
``accompanying'' them with warships posted along the way to provide
any assistance needed.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan acted
``after reviewing the cease-fire'' between Iran and Iraq which
began Aug. 20, and ``consulting with allies and friends in the
region.''
   Aboard Air Force One en route to New York, where Reagan later
addressed the U.N. General Assembly, Fitzwater said U.S. ships
would still ``take appropriate action if American-flagged ships are
directly threatened.''
   Administration officials said last week they are considering the
``zone defense'' plan, citing reduced gulf tensions and prospects
for a U.S. force cutback of at least one ship. The United States
has 26 warships in the region, 16 in the gulf.
   The military sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
a convoy scheduled to leave Kuwait on Tuesday would likely be the
last escorted the entire 550-mile voyage through the gulf. The
Vandegrift was designated as escort for the 81,283-ton oil products
carrier Surf City.
   The Navy has been escorting 11 Kuwaiti tankers reflagged with
the Stars and Stripes since July 1987 to protect them from Iranian
attack.
   Monday's convoy, the 67th this year and the 89th since
``Operation Earnest Will'' began, brought the 294,739-ton tanker
Townsend up the gulf to Kuwait. A second tanker, the U.S.-owned
Overseas Valdez, dropped off at Bahrain.
   As they neared Kuwait early Monday, the Vandegrift and its
massive charge sailed through waters where the missile frigate
Taylor, a sister ship of the Vandegrift, spotted a floating mine
Saturday. It was destroyed by Navy divers.
   A Kuwaiti cargo vessel reported a similar discovery Friday near
Hout island, 40 miles northwest of the Taylor sighting.
   The officers said a U.S. minesweeper's sonar located a mine Aug.
19 on the seabed in a ``mine danger area'' near Iran-owned Farsi
Island, where dozens of mines had been cleared earlier.
   A day earlier, the Vandegrift was patrolling near two secret
U.S. Navy barges in the same area when bridge lookouts spotted a
mine bobbing 100 yards off the port side.
   U.S. officers said all the mines were 500-pound M-08 contact
devices that Iran is known to have sown widely, and each was safely
disposed of.
   All were covered with marine growth, indicating they had been in
the water for some time, the officers noted.
   Capt. Jim Miller, ``commodore'' of the U.S. minesweeping force
in the gulf, estimated two months ago that despite the recovery of
scores of mines, ``a couple of hundred'' remain, mostly in northern
waters near Iraq, and mostly laid by the Iranians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
