<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HorseSlaughter     09-26 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Slaughter,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Wild Horses Found Slaughtered in Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six to seven dozen wild horses have
been shot dead in an isolated stretch of central Nevada, the
federal Bureau of Land Management confirmed Monday.
   In addition to the remains of 73 animals found last week, BLM
investigators have turned up a dozen more carcasses of wild horses,
along with spent bullets and other evidence, said bureau
spokeswoman Maxine Shane.
   She said the bureau hasn't determined exactly how many horses
have been killed because a few of the original 73 remains spotted
by helicopter turned out to be cattle that died of natural causes.
   The carcasses and bones are strewn along an area one to two
miles wide and about eight miles long. The BLM has said the horses
apparently were shot over a six-month period starting about a year
ago.
   The remote area includes canyons and rolling benchland about 30
miles north of the tiny central Nevada town of Austin and about 15
miles west of the highway linking Austin with Battle Mountain.
   The BLM was tipped by a person who was questioned about an
earlier rifle slaughter of 41 horses whose remains were discovered
30 miles away in August. The bureau did not identify the person.
   More than 38,000 wild horses now run the open range in 10
western states. Nevada's herds are the largest, with estimates of
up to 28,000 horses roaming the state.
</TEXT>
