<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--LincolnCenter     09-26 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Lincoln Center,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lincoln Center Gets $1.25 Million Grant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts and three
of its constituents will receive $1.25 million from the William
Randolph Heart Foundation, it was announced Monday.
   George Weissman, chairman of the center, and Randolph A. Hearst,
president of the foundation, said the gift will be made Tuesday
evening. The grant is equal to a 1982 Hearst Foundation gift to the
same organizations.
   Lincoln Center will receive a $200,000 endowment gift for
operation of a new building for young artists and students and for
new public facilities.
   The Metropolitan Opera and New York Philharmonic will receive
$400,000 each. The Juilliard School will receive $250,000.
   The Hearst Foundation also will make its customary annual
$100,000 gift to the Lincoln Center Consolidated Corporate Fund,
which benefits all the performing constituents at Lincoln Center.
