<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceFuneral     09-26 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Funeral,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Slain By Gunman Is Eulogized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest told more than 1,000 mourners at the
funeral of a slain police officer Monday to be anguished over cuts
in services for the mentally ill, saying the killer ``needed more
help, more love and more understanding.''
   Amid the wail of bagpipes, scores of police officers saluted the
casket carrying the body of Officer Irma Ruiz.
   Ruiz was one of four people killed by Clem Henderson, 40, during
a shooting rampage Thursday at a store and school. Henderson also
died.
   As police stood at attention under a blue sky, the Emerald
Society, a police drum and bagpipe corps, played a dirge while
pallbearers carried the casket into Christ The King church on the
city's Southwest Side.
   ``If we are to be anguished and upset today, perhaps we should
be anguished and upset at those who are cutting and continue to cut
resources for our mentally ill,'' the Rev. James Maloney told
mourners.
   ``Perhaps that is what killed Irma, because there was a person
who needed more help, more love and more understanding than our
institutions provided him,'' Maloney said.
   Dozens of city officials attended the funeral Mass at the Roman
Catholic church, including Mayor Eugene Sawyer and police
Superintendent LeRoy Martin.
   Sawyer said he hoped the shootings would make the public realize
the need to ban the manufacture and sale of handguns.
   On Thursday, Henderson walked into an auto parts store and
fatally shot owner John Van Dyke, 41, and an employee, Robert
Quinn, 26.
   Henderson then crossed the street to the Montefiore School where
he fatally wounded a custodian, Arthur Baker, 33, and wounded a
garbage collector, Laplose Chestnut Jr., 34.
   At the school's front door, Henderson surprised Mrs. Ruiz and
Officer Greg Jaglowski, who had been called there to remove an
unruly student.
   Mrs. Ruiz, the mother of four, was shot once in the chest.
Jaglowski was shot in both legs, but pursued Henderson into the
school where he killed the gunman.
   Jaglowski was in good condition Monday at Mount Sinai Hospital.
   Three of Henderson's other victims also were buried Monday.
Henderson's funeral was scheduled Thursday.
</TEXT>
