<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     09-26 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Slay Sri Lankan Cabinet Minister Near Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister who had been
helping rebuild a region devastated by the 5-year-old civil war in
Sri Lanka was shot to death Monday near a Buddhist temple.
   The military said three unidentified assailants opened fire on
Lionel Jayatilleke's car, killing him and seriously injuring two
bodyguards. The Joint Operations Command said the shooting occurred
in Kuliyapitiya, 40 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Jayatilleke, 64, served as education minister and as minister of
rehabilitation and reconstruction.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the killing.
   Military officials who requested anonymity said they suspected
the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese extremist group that has
vowed to kill anyone who supports a July 1987 accord aimed at
ending the ethnic dispute that was wracked the island's north and
east.
   Members of the front have been accused of trying to assassinate
President Junius R. Jayewardene in August 1987.
   Jayatilleke, a former teacher, had served as minister of
education since July 1977.
   Last year, he was appointed minister of rehabilitation and
reconstruction and assigned to re-open schools and restore civil
services to the war-torn provinces. He spent the last two months
touring the north and east, talking to ethnic groups left homeless
by the war.
   Tamils, mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of the island's 16
million people. They claim they have been denied jobs and military
appointments by the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up
75 percent of the population and control the government.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most militant group,
briefly accepted the accord, but later reneged, claiming it failed
to meet enough demands.
   Militant Sinhalese also claim the accord makes too many
concessions. They have been blamed for 450 killings, including
government and security personnel.
   India became involved in the conflict because 60 million Tamils
living in southern India are sympathetic to the rebel cause. An
estimated 47,000 Indian troops have been stationed on the island
trying to enforce the accord.
   About 8,500 people have died in the fighting, including at least
575 Indian soldiers.
</TEXT>
