<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0639 09-26 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Leaders Blame System For Yugoslavia's Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with youth union warning of
`fratricidal' war, top official resigning, other details,
background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's official youth union on
Monday blamed the political system of this crisis-ridden communist
country for ethnic clashes and warned the conflict could develop
into a civil war.
   A top Communist Party official resigned to protest the mass
rallies by Serb nationalists against ethnic Albanians in the poor,
southern province of Kosovo. The Socialist Youth Union, in a
statement addressed to the Yugoslav people and carried by the state
Tanjug news agency, blamed the ``almost totally inefficient
political system'' for ``a situation which is closer to fratricidal
war than progressive solution of the problems.''
   The youth union also called on officials to battle Yugoslavia's
``economic and social collapse'' through free elections and a
open-market economy.
   In addition to increasing ethnic tensions, Yugoslavia is
battling a 200 percent annual inflation rate, a $21 billion foreign
debt, a 15 percent unemployment rate and increasing labor unrest.
   ``The current situation in the country is characterized by fears
of violence ... poverty and hopelessness,'' the statement said.
   In Kosovo, the Moslem Albanians form 90 percent of the 2 million
population and are fighting to win a greater voice in governing
their autonomous province, now administered by the republic of
Serbia. The Christian Slavs, formed by Serbs and Montenegrins,
claim they are the victims of Albanian arson and street attacks,
are calling on Serbia to completely absorb the province.
   Franc Setinc, a member of the ruling Communist Party Presidium,
resigned Monday over recent rallies by tens of thousands of Slavs
who have chanted demands for arms to fight the Albanians.
   Serbian party boss Slobodan Milosevic backed the protests and
demanded tough measures against Albanian separatists, who are
demanding their own republic free of the 200,000 Slav minority.
   In a resignation letter sent to Tanjug, Setinc said he ``is
concerned by slogans `We want arms!' and the like that call for a
blaze in Kosovo and all of Yugoslavia.''
   ``We are doing little to stop the insanity that ... is driving
us into catastrophe,'' added Setinc, one of the highest officials
to resign since the communists came to power after World War II.
   Milosevic has denounced Setinc and several other communist
officials at the rallies, and his supporters claim non-Serbian
officials have prevented action to stop ethnic strife in Kosovo.
   ``I am afraid of people who manipulate with hardships and
emotions of Serbs and Montenegrins in Kosovo,'' Setinc said in an
apparent reference to Milosevic and other Serbian leaders.
   Yugoslavia's leaders say the rallies could imperil the fragile
ethnic balance in this nation that stretches from Austria to
Greece, or even lead to civil war.
   The animosity in Kosovo, exacerbated by the rallies, is now so
high that many residents believe a military crackdown will come
within months, or even weeks. Police in armored personnel carriers
have been sent to the province by the federal government in
Belgrade.
   In Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, about 2,000 Slav
schoolchildren continued to boycott their classes Monday to protest
alleged harassment by ethnic Albanian classmates, sources said.
   The elementary and high school students have not attended
classes since Thursday, when they staged a street protest. The
students, who belong to Serb and Montenegrin minorities, also
marched Friday.
   They apparently were kept at home Monday by parents fearing
possible confrontations with ethnic Albanians, according to the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Slav students say they will not return to classes until a
meeting of the Communist Party Central Committee in early October
results in decisive action against the Albanians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
