<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-GiantTurtle     09-26 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Giant Turtle,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1-Ton Turtle Washes Up On Welsh Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARDIFF, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-ton leatherback turtle found washed
up dead on a Welsh beach could be the largest of its species ever
recorded, the National Museum of Wales said Monday.
   ``It appears to be a world record,'' said Peter Morgan, keeper
of zoology at the museum in Cardiff, south Wales.
   ``We had to weigh it on a crane and it scaled 2,000 pounds. It
is 8{ feet long from its head to the end of its tail and nearly 10
feet wide, measured across the flippers. I doubt whether they grow
much bigger,'' Morgan said.
   ``There are earlier reports of leatherbacks approaching this
size but this seems to be the heaviest recorded,'' he said.
   The turtle, found Thursday on Harlech Beach in Cardigan Bay,
northwest Wales, was driven to Cardiff by a nature warden where it
was put in the museum's deep freeze.
   Morgan said reports of leatherbacks in Welsh waters were ``very
rare'' and all were females. This one was a male and was thought to
have come from the Caribbean.
   ``They live in the tropics and feed on jellyfish and as we have
had lots of jellyfish in Welsh waters this year it probably was
pursuing them,'' he said.
   Morgan said that while most stranded turtles are injured in
collisions with ships this turtle had not been injured before it
died at sea from an unknown cause. ``We've done an autopsy and
tests on its parasites, like barnacles, should show where it came
from,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
