<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Reagan     09-26 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Reagan,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Turns Other Cheek To Reagan's Tongue-Lashing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-UN, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan departed from a generally
conciliatory speech Monday to deliver a tongue-lashing to a handful
of nations for abusing human rights, singling out the Soviet Union
and others.
   Reagan declared that ``the regard for human rights as the
foundation of peace is at the heart of the United Nations.
   ``Those who starve in Ethiopia, those who die among the Kurds,
those who face racial injustice in South Africa, those who still
cannot write or speak freely in the Soviet Union, those who cannot
worship in the Ukraine, those who struggle for life and freedom on
boats in the South China Sea, those who cannot publish or assemble
in Managua _ all of this is more than just an agenda item on your
calendar,'' Reagan told the delegates from 159 nations.
   ``It must be a first concern; an issue above others,'' said
Reagan.
   Reagan's farewell address to the General Assembly drew about a
minute of applause but no standing ovation, except among members of
the U.S. delegation.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze sat stony-faced
during Reagan's criticism. He left afterward by a private exit and
offered no comment to reporters.
   Reagan's South China Sea reference was to refugees fleeing
Vietnam, and his mention of Kurds was prompted by allegations Iraq
has used poison gas to crush a rebellion by its Kurdish minority.
   Of Cuba, Reagan said ``for years, Cuba, a blatant violator of
its citizens' human rights, has escaped United Nations censure or
even scrutiny.''
   Reagan said the United States prompted the U.N. Human Rights
Commission to examine Havana's human rights policies.
   ``Fidel Castro has already begun to free some political
prisoners, improve prison conditions, and tolerate the existence of
a small, independent national human rights group,'' he said.
   Few foreign officials had comment on Reagan's attacks. But
Nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, Victor Hugo Tinoco, said
Reagan singled out his country out of frustration because ``he
accepts that his policy is a total failure, ... the policy of
paying mercenaries this policy of eight years of war.''
   Washington supports the rebels, known as Contras, in the civil
war against the leftist Sandinista government.
   Clovis Maksoud, the permanent observer of the League of Arab
States, has said previously there is no evidence Iraq used chemical
weapons against the Kurds. Maksoud also has criticized Washington
for allegedly bowing to ``Zionist'' pressures.
   Maksoud did question Reagan's failure to mention the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and the political standoff between Christians and Moslems in
Lebanon.
   The United Nations itself may have had the keenest interest in
Reagan's speech. In previous years, Reagan has lambasted the
organization for alleged overspending, anti-Western bias and a
bloated bureaucracy.
   Washington began withholding part of its U.N. dues to spur
reform, and by this fall the United States was more than $530
million in arrears.
   On Sept. 13, Reagan announced he was satisfied with the U.N.'s
reforms and the United States began paying its back dues.
   ``That eliminates the threat of insolvency,'' said a U.N.
official, speaking on condition of anonymity. The United Nations
would have run out of funds for its payroll, rents and other fixed
expenses by late October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
