<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Indians-Hostages     09-26 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indians-Hostages,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lets Indian Defendant Represent Self</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled Monday that one of two Indian
activists accused of taking hostages in a newspaper office could
act as his own lawyer after the man refused representation by
anyone other than William Kunstler.
   Eddie Hatcher, 31, and Timothy Jacobs, 20, are charged with
taking hostages and possessing illegal firearms. They have never
denied that they walked into The Robesonian newspaper office Feb. 1
in Lumberton, chained the door and held up to 20 people for 10
hours, saying they were trying to expose local corruption.
   Before jury selection started, Hatcher insisted he would be
represented by no one but Kunstler and that the trial should be
delayed until Kunstler finished a trial in New York.
   But U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle had warned Hatcher when
he granted a third delay in the case Aug. 1 that he did not intend
to continue the case again. He said then another lawyer should be
prepared to begin the trial if Kunstler was not present.
   Boyle denied Hatcher's renewed request for a delay Monday, and
then asked Hatcher if he wanted to fire his local attorney, Barry
Nakell, a law professor at the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill. ``If you want him to stay and try this case, I'll
force him to stay,'' Boyle said.
   Hatcher replied: ``Bill Kunstler is my attorney, and I feel like
I'm being forced to make this decision, and my constitutional
rights are being violated.''
   Nakel withdrew as Hatcher's attorney and Boyle then called
Stephanie Moore, an associate of Kunstler, to the front of the
courtroom and asked Hatcher if he would accept her as his trial
attorney.
   But Hatcher continued to repeat that Kunstler was his attorney.
   ``Well, he's not here,'' Boyle said. ``Will you take Ms. Moore?''
   ``Bill Kunstler is my attorney,'' said Hatcher.
   ``His answer, for the record, is no,'' Boyle said, adding that
Hatcher had chosen to defend himself.
   ``No, your honor, I have had that decision forced on me against
my constitutional rights,'' Hatcher said.
   When Boyle told the attorneys to introduce themselves to 28
prospective jurors, Hatcher stood up and said: ``Your honor, I am
not allowed to have my chosen counsel present, so I do not have
anything to say to the jury.''
   Several prospective jurors said they believed the defendants
were guilty. Four said they'd never heard of the case.
   ``In a country which consistently insists that criminal
defendants are entitled to counsel of their choice, it is a
disgrace for a federal judge, sworn to uphold the Constitution to
deny this right to anyone and particularly, a native American who
faces a potential punishment of life in prison,'' Kunstler said in
a statement issued from his New York office.
   Hatcher and Jacobs claim membership in the Tuscarora tribe, an
Indian faction affiliated with the Lumbee tribe in southeastern
North Carolina.
   Hatcher and Jacobs have said they committed the act to draw
attention to allegations of drug trafficking and corruption in the
county. The 10-hour siege at the newspaper ended after Gov. Jim
Martin agreed to form a state task force to investigate their
corruption charges.
   But Hatcher and Jacobs met only once with the task force, which
issued a preliminary report saying it had found little evidence to
back up their charges. Hatcher, Jacobs and their supporters said
the task force did not do a thorough investigation, and that
potential witnesses would not testify without federal and state
immunity.
   Hatcher disappeared Aug. 31 after a federal appeals court
revoked his bond. Jacobs surrendered to marshals in Asheville the
same day. Hatcher was arrested at Raleigh-Durham Airport one week
ago when he stepped off a plane with a Kunstler associate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
