<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReedTrial     09-26 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reed Trial,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Seated in Federal Extortion Trial of State NAACP Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was seated Monday in the federal
extortion trial of state Rep. Thomas Reed, who is accused of
accepting $10,000 in cash to secure a killer's early release from
prison.
   Sixteen people were seated to hear the case of Reed, who also is
president of the Alabama National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.
   U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina ordered the jury sequestered,
and said the trial probably would last three days.
   Reed, a Democrat and the senior black member of the Alabama
House, is charged with accepting $10,000 in cash and $5,000 to
$10,000 in restaurant equipment from the family of Anthony Dennis
Chesser to secure his early release from prison.
   Reed has denied the allegations and has said they are related to
his efforts to have the Confederate battle flag removed from the
state Capitol.
   ``If the truth prevails, I'll be a free man when I leave here,''
Reed, 60, told reporters when he arrived at the U.S. District Court.
   The trial was moved to Mobile from Montgomery because of
publicity.
   A list of prosecution witnesses includes several state prison
and parole officials as well as the inmate Chesser's family.
Defense witnesses include former Alabama Gov. Fob James, state Rep.
Mary Zoghby, former House Speaker Joe McCorquodale, and several
others.
   Jury selection took four hours.
   Reed is scheduled to go to trial Nov. 7 in Montgomery on related
state charges.
</TEXT>
