<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KraftTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0675 09-26 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kraft Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0675,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins In Mutilation Sex-Slayings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to add death total may be 60, and Inserts 3
grafs after the 7th graf, `The victims...' to update with defense
opening statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors described homosexual
violence, necrophilia and mutilation Monday when opening statements
began in the trial of a man accused of killing 16 young males.
   Prosecutor Bryan Brown portrayed Randy Kraft, a former Long
Beach computer programmer, as one who prowled the highways of
Orange County, picking up young male hitchhikers, plying them with
Valium and beer, strangling, then sodomizing them and sometimes
dumping their bodies from a moving car.
   ``Kraft had a fetish for collecting mementos of victims and
photographs,'' the prosecutor said, describing photos in which
victims apparently were posed while dead.
   If Kraft, 43, is found guilty in the 16 killings, which would
make him eligible for the death penalty, prosecutors plan to
produce evidence at his sentencing that they say links him to 21
other slayings in Southern California, Oregon and Michigan.
Prosecutors say the death total may be as high as 60.
   Opening statements in the trial, expected to last a year, began
five years and four months after Kraft was arrested by a Highway
Patrol officer who pulled him over for a routine traffic stop and
discovered a dying Marine on the seat next to him.
   Brown gave the jury gruesome details of the killings, which took
place over 11 years.
   The victims were bound with shoelaces and strangled, often with
their own belts, Brown said. One victim was beheaded and at least
one was sexually mutilated with a knife, the prosecutor said.
   Defense attorney C. Thomas McDonald responded to the
prosecutor's two-hour speech with 10 minutes of opening statements,
warning jurors against being swayed by vivid descriptions of the
killings.
   ``These are tactics designed to inflame you,'' McDonald said.
``This is a tactical decision made by the prosecutor. He won't be
able to prove it. This case is based on suspicion, innuendo and
prosecutorial rhetoric.
   ``Mr. Kraft killed no one,'' McDonald said.
   Defense attorneys lost two rounds in pretrial motions, when
Orange County Judge Donald A. McCartin denied a request to move the
trial to another community and refused to bar some entries from a
list prosecutors have called a ``scorecard'' of Kraft's alleged
victims.
   Kraft has pleaded innocent to 16 counts of first-degree murder
for slayings that occurred between December 1972 and May 1983.
   When he was arrested, police said, they found 47 color
photographs of young men, many of them nude and apparently dead.
They also found a notebook with more than 60 notations, which
prosecutors have called a ``death list'' for all the murders
allegedly committed by Kraft.
   Last week, McCartin allowed 13 entries on the list to be
admitted as evidence. Prosecutors said the entries pertain to 14
killings in which Kraft is charged.
</TEXT>
