<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Bribes     09-26 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Bribes,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brezhnev Son-In-Law Says He Didn't Know What to Do With Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son-in-law of the late Soviet President Leonid
I. Brezhnev testified at his corruption trial Monday that he kept a
$160,000 bribe because it would have been too awkward to return,
Tass reported.
   Yuri Churbanov, the first deputy interior minister before
Brezhnev died in 1982, took the witness stand for the first time at
his trial before a military tribunal. The proceedings are in their
fourth week.
   Churbanov, 51, is being tried with eight others in a case that
is expected to last another month. He is charged with accepting
hundreds of thousands of rubles in bribes from officials in the
republic of Uzbekistan, and could be sentenced to death by firing
squad.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said Churbanov testified
that an Uzbekistan Communist Party official named Umarov delivered
a briefcase to his hotel room once, telling him it was a present
from Uzbekistan party leader Sharaf Rashidov.
   ``When If opened it I found 100,000 or 130,000 rubles,'' Tass
quoted Churbanov as saying. ``I wanted to return the money, but to
whom? Umarov left and I felt awkward approaching Rashidov.''
   ``I was told that that was a a gift, and looked on it as a
gift,'' Tass quoted Churbanov as saying.
   At the official rate of exchange, 100,000 rubles is about
$160,000.
   Rashidov, who died in 1983, was a close associate of Brezhnev.
Since Rashidov's death, several key Uzbekistan officials have been
charged with corruption that occurred during his rule and two have
been executed.
   Churbanov married Brezhnev's daughter, Galina, and worked in the
Interior Ministry under Brezhnev's close associate, Nikolai
Shchelokov.
   He pleaded guilty to abusing his office, but innocent to
accepting bribes.
   Tass said Churbanov also testified that Interior Ministry
officials misled him into believing it was legal for him to use
ministry resources to build a cellar for his country house.
   ``Naturally, when such explanations came from the former first
deputy minister of internal affairs whose job it was to know the
law, the audience could not help smiling,'' Tass said.
   Churbanov's trial is the centerpiece of a campaign against the
legacy of Brezhnev, whose 18-year rule now is characterized in the
Soviet Union as a time of corruption and stagnation.
</TEXT>
