<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FilmStrike     09-26 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Film Strike,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie Chief Calls for Arbitration Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film industry leader said Monday a committee
with binding arbitration power should be formed to resolve future
labor disputes so Hollywood can avoid a rerun of the crippling
5{-month writers' strike.
   ``It's absolutely absurd and doubly shameful that it took five
and a half months and involved thousands of innocent people to come
up with a solution that reasonable men should have come up with
sooner,'' Lee Rich said.
   Rich spoke at the opening session of Cinetex, a trade show and
film festival for the film industry. The former board chairman of
MGM@UA Communications Co. announced this summer he was moving to
Warner Bros. to set up an independent production company.
   Rich called on the industry's management and unions to establish
a commission that would arbitrate future labor problems before they
deteriorate into strikes.
   ``Call it HELP, or Hollywood Enhancement of Labor Practices,''
Rich said. ``This commission would be in place to forever ensure
better handling of the labor-management situations than have ever
existed before.
   ``This strike avoidance committee would act as the final arbiter
in a dispute, when two sides agree to disagree,'' Rich said. ``Its
ruling would be binding, just like the baseball players and club
owners who take salary disputes to arbitration.''
   Rich said that with an enforceable body in place, cooler and
wiser heads might prevail.
   ``With the potential to have everything to win, but also with
the potential to have everything to lose, perhaps management and
labor will more efficiently and more expediently work toward what's
fair.''
   The movie chief, who helped build Lorimar into a TV programming
powerhouse in the early 1980s, said his idea might not be perfect,
but called it a place to start.
   ``The key is that we've got to do something about this
problem,'' Rich said. ``If not, the goose that laid the golden egg
is going to be gone, chopped up _ and eaten.''
   Under his proposal, studios would agree to bring in skilled
labor relations experts _ either federal labor negotiators or labor
lawyers.
   ``Just as a Jack Valenti heads the MPAA (Motion Picture
Association of America) and represents our interests, perhaps a
labor statesman representing both the industry and the unions and
guilds could serve as chairman of this committee,'' Rich suggested.
   ``We'd bring together representatives from the AMPTP (Alliance
of Motion Picture and Television Producers) with representatives of
all the guilds and unions to devise an anti-strike commission
designed to be the arbiter of labor-management disputes.''
   He called the strike an embarrassment to the industry and said
it was ``time for management and the unions to put collective egos
aside and make sure that there isn't a next time.''
   A final arbiter in labor disputes could render verdicts ``long
before any other bloodbaths occur,'' Rich said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
