<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Reagan-Mideast     09-26 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Mideast,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Assured PLO Trying To Recognize Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan received assurances
Monday from Egypt's foreign minister that the Palestine Liberation
Organization was trying to find a way to acknowledge Israel's right
to exist.
   That would meet a primary U.S. condition for dealing with Yasser
Arafat's organization, which all Arab governments recognize as the
sole representative of Palestinians.
   Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid told Reagan that ``some
elements'' of the PLO would continue to resist.''
   But the Egyptian official assured the president that senior PLO
leaders ``would like to find a way to come to terms with Israel's
right to exist,'' U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Richard W.
Murphy said.
   Reagan met for about half an hour with Meguid and Israeli
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres. Secretary of State George P. Shultz
and Murphy participated.
   For years the PLO has been rumored to be on the brink of
accepting Israel, but Arafat's organization has never taken the
step. Its covenant, meanwhile, is sworn to the destruction of the
Jewish state.
   Shultz plans further meetings with Meguid and Peres while they
are in New York to attend the special session of the United Nations
General Assembly.
   Egypt is the only Arab country officially at peace with Israel.
Reagan hailed their 1979 treaty as ``a monumental achievement.''
   Reagan met with the ministers after delivering his farewell
speech to the General Assembly. In it he made a brief reference to
the Arab-Israeli conflict, simply saying ``we look to a peaceful
solution.''
   Reagan also briefly criticized the United Nations for its
adoption of a resolution in 1975 equating Zionism, the Jewish
aspiration for a national homeland, with racism.
   Unlike other speakers, he did not demand Israel's withdrawal
from the West Bank and Gaza, which the Arabs lost in the 1973
Middle East war, or call for a Palestinian homeland.
   At a picture-taking session with Meguid and Peres, the president
said he wished he could have made more progress toward peace in the
Middle East.
   Murphy said U.S. policy calls both for security for all
countries in the region and that ``the Palestinians must have a
voice in their own future and achieve their legitimate political
rights.''
   The State Department official did not attempt to define the
rights.
</TEXT>
