<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-WhoWon 1stLd-Writethru a0661 09-26 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Who Won, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Picture the Debate Outcome a Draw</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UDPATE with newest polls, INSERT one graf after 6th pvs,
ABC News...a tie, picking up 7th pvs, Lee Miringoff...of them.''
^By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both political camps waved victory flags
Monday in the wake of the Bush vs. Dukakis matchup, but polls
indicated the debate was a draw in the opinion of many voters.
   Several analysts said a tie actually worked in favor of one
runner in this race: Michael Dukakis.
   Their reasoning was that since the Massachusetts governor was
less experienced and less well known on the national stage than
George Bush, he gained credibility simply by holding his own
against the vice president.
   A few polling organizations hit the telephones as soon as the
debate stage went black, seeking voters' opinions uncolored by the
analysis of campaign officials or others.
   The Gallup Organization surveyed 337 voters after the debate for
Newsweek magazine and found 42 percent thought Dukakis came out on
top, while 41 percent picked Bush as the winner. Twelve percent
called it a tie and 5 percent had no opinion. The poll had a 6
point margin of error.
   ABC News canvassed 639 voters immediately after the debate and
found 44 percent felt Dukakis won the encounter, 36 percent picked
Bush and 20 percent called it a tie.
   In a CBS News-New York Times poll of 415 debate watchers, 42
percent thought Bush won and 39 percent thought Dukakis won, within
the margin of error of plus or minues five points. And in a Los
Angeles Times survey, 35 percent of 637 viewers polled though
Dukakis won, 34 percent Bush, and 29 percent called it even.
   Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist College Institute for
Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., said, ``Overall, it was a net
plus for Dukakis in that it leveled the playing field forboth of
them.''
   William Schneider, political analyst with the American
Enterprise Institute, said, ``Close means good for Dukakis because
he started out four to six points behind in most of the polls.''
   ``Dukakis effectively demolished the Bush image of him as some
sort of dangerous, radical left-winger,'' said Schneider. ``Bush
had been painting him in very extreme colors for the last month.
... Just by appearing safe and steady and reasonable, I thought he
scored a big point.''
   The Bush and Dukakis handlers began trumpeting victory the
moment the debate ended, and their supporters were for the most
part true blue, too.
   An exception was Illinois Gov. James Thompson, a Republican, who
said, ``Neither guy won and neither guy lost.''
   David Gergen, editor-at-large of U.S. News & World Report and
former Reagan White House communications director, predicted ``this
will make it a more competitive race.''
   Gergen said Bush ``made good, telling points on traditional
values and the differences between the two candidates,'' while
Dukakis ``showed an understanding of the middle class and those
left behind on health insurance, housing, age and the like.''
   An Associated Press panel of six forensic experts gave Dukakis a
narrow victory on their scorecards, 144-141, although three judges
picked Dukakis and three called Bush the winner.
   James J. Unger, director of the National Forensics Institute at
American University in Washington and chairman of the AP judges'
panel, said neither candidate delivered a knockout punch.
   The AEI's Schneider said the debates loom especially large in
this election year because there is no single issue that has
galvanized the voters' attention. He predicted, ``Both candidates
are going to be looking for a knockout blow at the next debate.''
   That will be held Oct. 13 or 14 in Los Angeles. Their running
mates, Republican Dan Quayle and Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, get their
turn in the debating ring Oct. 5 in Omaha, Neb.
</TEXT>
