<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-26 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most of Nation Enjoys Pleasant Fall Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Florida and parts of the Great Lakes and Pacific
Northwest got scattered rain Monday, but most of the nation enjoyed
pleasant weather thanks to a high-pressure pattern over the Ohio
Valley and southern Plains.
   Warm and humid air just south of a stationary front across
northern Florida triggered scattered thunderstorms in the area in
the early afternoon.
   A low pressure front moving slowly across central Minnesota
brought widely scattered showers there, while warm air tracking
northward across the Plains moved over cooler air above the
northern Great Lakes, producing rain across northern Wisconsin and
Michigan's Upper Peninsula.
   In the Pacific Northwest, rain was spotty in parts of
Washington, with showers increasingly heavy by nightfall.
   Fair skies and temperatures in the 60s and 70s were the rule for
most of the nation, with readings in the 50s over the northern
Rockies and in the 90s in southern Texas, south Florida and the
desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Minn., to 97 at Palm Springs, Calif.
The nation's morning low was 16 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Tuesday's forecast called for rain showers to spread across the
Pacific Northwest, with the heaviest concentration across northwest
Washington state. A low pressure front stretching from Wisconsin to
Quebec should bring scattered showers into northeastern New York.
Rain was also predicted in southern Georgia and much of Florida.
   High temperatures should be in the 70s and 80s across much of
the nation, dipping into the 60s from the Pacific Northwest into
the northern Rockies, from North Dakota through upper Michigan and
across New England. Maine should see highs only in the 50s. Highs
should be in the 90s across parts of western Oklahoma and southern
Texas, warming into the 90s in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
