<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FoodStamps     09-26 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Stamps,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experiment Would Use Cards Instead Of Food Stamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three test projects using plastic magnetic
strip cards instead of food stamps will be conducted in parts of
Arizona, New Mexico and Minnesota, the Agriculture Department said
Monday.
   Assistant Secretary John W. Bode said that nearly 30,000 food
stamp households in the three states will use the cards to see if
the system will be easier for people to use and to help reduce lost
or stolen coupons.
   The projects are scheduled to begin within the next 8 to 12
months and run for at least three years, he said. An evaluation
will be made to see if the electronic system might be used
nationally.
   Bode said the $1.3 million project will operate by running the
plastic cards through a computer terminal at grocery checkout
counters. The cost of the food will be automatically deducted from
the family's todal monthly food stamp allotment.
   In addition, he said, some of the food stamp recipients will be
able to use the same plastic cards for other public benefits, such
as Aid for Families With Dependent Children.
   The department first tested the use of electronic benefits in
Reading, Pa., in 1984, involving 3,400 households. It received high
scores from food stamp recipients, stores and banks, which are
involved in issuing and redeeming food stamps coupons.
   Bode said Arizona will get funding to design its projects, which
will be tested in Mesa, with services to 6,500 households.
   Minnesota will test its system in Ramsey County among 13,000
households, and New Mexico will conduct its test in Albuquerque
among 10,150 households.
   Nationally, nearly 19 million people are getting food stamp
benefits, based on family size and adjusted household incomes. The
program costs about $12.6 billion a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
