<DOCNO> AP880926-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending     09-26 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress, White House Near Agreement on Defense Budget.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional and administration officials
were close to agreement Monday on a Pentagon budget which
eliminates some of the objections raised by President Reagan when
he vetoed a defense spending measure last month, congressional
sources said.
   The agreement was being worked out in a series of closed-door
meetings involving Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and top
Democratic and Republican members of the House and Senate Armed
Services committees, said the sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Under terms of the proposed agreement Reagan's cherished Star
Wars anti-missile program would receive $4.1 billion, a figure far
under his $4.8 billion he requested for the fiscal year starting
Oct. 1, the sources said. The Strategic Defense Initiative, as the
program is formally known, currently receives $3.9 billion.
   But the compromise would drop some restrictions in the SDI
budget to which Reagan had objected in the bill he vetoed Aug. 3,
the sources said.
   Reagan wanted $330 million for SDI work which could be used for
an early-stage deployment system, but the Democratic-controlled
Congress had restricted spending on that program to only $85
million.
   The compromise also drops a restriction which had been added by
Congress on testing of depressed-trajectory missiles, a type of
atomic-tipped weapon being developed by the Pentagon.
   Overall, the bill would provide about $300 billion for the
Pentagon, the same as the earlier bill, but slightly less than the
current $302 billion.
   Agreement on the Pentagon budget would dramatically enhance the
prospects that all 13 appropriations bills needed to finance the
government would be enacted by Saturday, the first day of the 1989
federal fiscal year.
   The last time work on all 13 spending bills was completed by the
start of the new fiscal year was in 1948.
   House and Senate Democratic leaders have been pressing to
complete work on all appropriations bills to avoid Reagan and the
GOP painting the Democrats as inefficient and incapable of adhering
to the budget process.
   Last December the Democratic-controlled Congress sent the
president a 1,400-page, $600 billion catch-all spending bill that
arrived at the White House nearly three months into the new fiscal
year. During his State of the Union address in January, Reagan
threatened to veto any similar giant spending bills this year, and
scores of lawmakers signed letters pledging to support him.
   This year's appropriations work was made easier by the budget
summit agreement reached between Reagan and congressional leaders
in November.
   That pact settled many broad spending questions for 1989, but
disputes over various provisions within several individual bills
have caused delays. Lawmakers have said that the dispute over the
defense bill was the most serious, and that its resolution would
make it likely that all 13 bills would be finished on time.
   So far, Reagan has signed four appropriations bills into law,
and has been sent two others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880926-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Education-Executives     09-26 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Education-Executives,275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Calls For Improved Education, Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of business and academic executives
said Monday that America is wasting its human capital, and the next
president must make improved education and training a top national
priority.
   ``Inattention to our human resource needs and the waste of human
potential are eroding our national strength,'' the Business-Higher
Education Forum warned.
   The panel, chaired by University of California President David
P. Gardner, said the nation must forge a new consensus on how to
improve its schools and the capacity of its workers.
   ``Too much of our human talent is being wasted, and a growing
proportion of the next generation is slipping beyond the reach of
the institutions and values of our society,'' it said in a report
called ``American Potential: The Human Dimension.''
   Donald E. Petersen, chairman of the board of Ford Motor Co. and
a leader of a task force that produced the report, told a news
conference, ``The task must be faced and the price must be paid. We
are out of alternatives. From the cradle on, Americans must have
the best in education and training, and we must provide it.''
   The forum, comprised of 80 corporate and university executives,
urged the next president to appoint Cabinet-level task forces or
convene a White House Conference on Human Resources to address
these problems.
   It said math and science education must be bolstered, especially
for the disadvantaged, and it urged every state to follow the
example of North Carolina, Louisiana, Illinois and others that have
created highly selective public high schools for math and science.
   It also called for expanded preschool opportunities, including
day care, health screening and nutrition services.
</TEXT>
