<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0682 09-26 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Modifies Anti-Abortion Stance After Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Bush remarks on debate, including comment that
he and Dukakis were ``about even,'' INSERT one graf after lede,
picking up 2nd pvs, Several thousand...Michael Dukakis, and SUB
four grafs for 8th pvs, Bush's appearance ... overnight stay,
picking up 9th graf, ``I am ... in Jackson.''
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, amid efforts to clarify who
would be liable for punishment if abortions were outlawed,
campaigned in a Democratic region Monday with running mate Dan
Quayle and was cheered loudly when he asked: ``One debate down.
How'd I do?''
   And the vice president gave what seemed a surprising answer to
that question when talking later to reporters. ``I thought it was
kind of about even,'' Bush said.
   Several thousand people turned out at a railroad amusement park
in this west Tennessee community to applaud Bush on his debate
Sunday night with Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis.
   Dukakis had his supporters, as well. A plane flew over the park
trailing a streamer that read: ``Dukakis 1. Bush 0.''
   Even before Bush left Winston-Salem, N.C., the debate site,
campaign chairman James A. Baker III said the vice president, after
reflecting overnight, decided he would not favor criminal
prosecution of women who have abortions even if abortions are
outlawed.
   In the debate, Bush said he had not ``sorted out the penalties''
that might be imposed under an anti-abortion constitutional
amendment he favors but that ``there's got to be some penalties to
enforce the law, whatever they may be.''
   Dukakis immediately seized on the answer, saying Bush was
``prepared to brand a woman a criminal for making that decision.
It's as simple as that.''
   Bush made no mention of the potential controversy until asked
about it by reporters at Casey Jones Village in Jackson. ``No
change of mine at all,'' he insisted.
   Bush's appearance with Quayle was his first since they were
together on Aug. 21. From Jackson, Bush campaigned separately at a
barbecue near Atlanta before flying to Cincinnati for an overnight
stay.
   At the event near Atlanta, Bush was asked about a news report
that president Reagan had claimed in a conversation with Sen. Rudy
Boschwitz, R-Minn., that the debate was a near draw.
   ``He's probably right,''Bush said. Even though Bush's aides have
claimed the vice president scored a clear victory, Bush had not
made such a claim during his day of camapign appearances in the
South.
   Addressing a crowd of hundreds, Bush said: ``You know you get up
there in these debates, why sometimes things escape you. Barbara
(his wife), I think, was a nervous wreck, and our daughter-in-law,
Margaret Bush, standing next to her, I think they were biting their
fingernails off,'' he joked. ``But we think it turned out pretty
well.''
   ``I am particularly proud to be standing at the side of my
running mate in whom I have not only confidence but pride,'' Bush
told the flag-waving audience in Jackson.
   ``One debate down. How'd I do?'' he asked. When he got the
response he wanted, Bush said: ``All right. Stay tuned'' _
referring to Quayle's debate Oct. 5 with Democratic vice
presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen.
   Bush said, ``I loved it last night, I loved it'' when Dukakis
raised the problem of housing for Americans. He said interest rates
were 21 percent under the last Democratic administration and
``America does not want that anymore.''
   Using a football metaphor, Bush said that when Republicans took
over the White House in 1981, America's economy ``was in punt
formation, deep in our own end zone.
   ``And now we're marching down the field, heading toward the goal
line, and the old Democratic team, that second string, that
punt-on-first down crowd, wants to get back into the game,'' he
said. ``No thank you. No thanks. Let's hold the ball. Let's keep
moving forward. Let's take it into the score.''
   Bush's debate answer on abortion _ one of the most explosive and
divisive issues in politics _ gave Dukakis an easy target to
exploit. Bush's staff moved quickly to remove it.
   ``We went in and discussed it (with Bush) this morning and
concluded it was an issue that should be addressed and we addressed
it,'' Baker said.
   He said Bush ``would not wish to see a woman labeled as a
criminal, notwithstanding his view in favor of right of life.''
   ``Frankly, he thinks that a woman in a situation like that would
be more properly considered an additional victim _ perhaps the
second victim _ that she would need help and love and not
punishment,'' Baker said.
   He said that ``some consideration could be given ... to
punishment as far as the abortionist is concerned.''
   At an early-morning briefing with reporters, Baker said that
Bush was able to project himself as ``warm, as human and as
likeable'' while Dukakis failed to ``come across as likeable, and
less dour and less technocratic.''
   Baker softened Bush's debate proposal to ``permit people to buy
into Medicaid'' in order for the very poor to have medical
coverage. ``All I know is he thinks that would be an appropriate
approach to explore,'' Baker said.
</TEXT>
