<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     09-26 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Party Chooses `Democrats' Title, Rejecting `Liberal'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Britain's new centrist
party, the Social and Liberal Democrats, voted overwhelmingly
Monday to call themselves the Democrats for short.
   The vote by a show of hands at the party's first annual
conference in this north England resort upset some members of the
old Liberal Party who wanted the short title Liberal Democrats, to
include their former party's historic name.
   The Social and Liberal Democratic Party was formed last March
from a merger of the long-established Liberal Party and most of the
7-year-old Social Democratic Party. David Owen, the Social
Democratic leader, refused to join and is a leading a separate
faction.
   Legislator Sir Russell Johnston, a former Liberal, said
excluding Liberal from the short title was ``extraordinary folly.''
   ``For me, the world Democrat simply has no clear political
meaning,'' he said.
   He said the new short title implied that Britain's two major
parties, the governing Conservatives and opposition Labor Party,
``are not democrats.'' ``They are,'' added Johnston.
   The new parties obtained 20 percent of the vote in an electoral
alliance at the last general election in 1987.
   But the acrimonious merger slashed support. A Harris poll
published Sunday in the liberal Observer newspaper showed the
Democrats with eight percent support and Owen's faction with five
percent.
   The Liberal Party dates to the 1840s and was one of Britain's
two major parties until Labor supplanted it in the 1920s.
</TEXT>
