<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken 1stLd-Writethru a0695 09-26 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0695,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Suspect Vigorous Training Felled Trainees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf `Timothy Shepard' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
transplant operation under way. Subs 10th graf pvs `Several local'
with 2 grafs to make it a second reference to the mayor conform and
UPDATE with her comment on meeting with adademy officials.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigations began Monday at a
police academy into whether strenuous exercise contributed to the
hospitalization of 16 cadets for exhaustion and dehydration,
including one who needs a liver transplant.
   Several stricken cadets refused to be interviewed Monday without
clearance from Gary Egan, director of the Edward J. Connelly
Criminal Justice Training Center in Agawam. He was taking part in
the internal investigation and unavailable.
   But one former trainee said the training routine was severe.
   ``I've been through basic training in the Army and it was twice
as bad as that,'' said Mike Purcell of Northampton, who quit the
academy after one day. ``The doctors told me that if I had gone
back for a second day, I could have suffered permanent kidney
damage.''
   Timothy Shepard, 25, a Pittsfield police trainee who collapsed
while running on the track Sept. 19, the first day of classes, was
flown to Presbyterian Hospital in Pittsburgh and on Monday for a
liver transplant.
   The operation, which began Monday evening, was expected to take
up to 12 hours, said Pittsfield Mayor Anne Everest Wojtkowski, who
kept in contact with the Shepard family in Pittsburgh.
   A Springfield hospital spokesman said Shepard also suffered
kidney problems, and that several of the other hospitalized cadets
underwent kidney dialysis treatment. Six remained hospitalized
Monday.
   After Shepard collapsed, instructors allowed the recruits to
drink two small cups of water, Purcell said. ``Before that, they
had lined us up at the bubbler twice during the day and only let us
take one cup of water each,'' he said.
   Dr. George Grady, chief state epidemiologist, said his
examination last week found ``it's very clear the exercise was
stressful,'' although he said further investigation may show other
contributing causes.
   Jeff Grossman, a spokesman for the state executive office of
public safety, said investigators from the Criminal Justice
Training Council, which runs the academy, and state police, whose
troopers are instructors at the academy, interviewed the class of
47 men and women Monday. They planned to present findings Tuesday.
   Several local officials, including Wojkowski and North Adams
Mayor John Barrett III, asked the state attorney general's office
to review the training program.
   Wojkowski met Monday with Egan and state police Capt. Thomas
White, and said afterward, ``I was completely dissatisfied with
their responses. I suspect that the incidents are not isolated.''
   Shepard, 25, was the only cadet hospitalized the first day of
classes, but two more were hospitalized the next day and an
additional two the third day of classes, authorities said. Academy
officials urged cadets Wednesday night to seek medical
examinations, and 21 exhibited some of the symptoms ranging from
fatigue and nausea to kidney failure.
   Shepard was in ``tip-top'' shape and had ``worked out for over
six months at least, running and everything,'' to prepare for the
academy, said his brother, Thomas Jr.
   ``He really wanted to be a policeman,'' the brother said. ``He'd
been trying to be one for a couple of years.''
   Grossman said Shepard's condition may have resulted in part from
a ``self-induced, severe diet.'' But Thomas Shepard said his
brother spent the days before reporting to the academy with his
family and ate normally.
   ``He definitely was not fasting. That's total lies. He
definitely was eating fine,'' the brother said.
   Purcell said recruits were required to exercise vigorously and
were kept moving with pushups and laps if they failed to respond
quickly to orders.
   ``We started at 7:30 a.m. with a formation with our gear _ our
jackets, boots and other stuff in a duffel bag weighing 50 to 60
pounds _ and we had to walk to classes carrying the duffel bag
above our heads with one arm,'' he said.
   ``We also moved metal lockers and heavy wood furniture from the
basement up to either the second or third floor of the building,''
he said. ``Everybody was pushed to the limit before we even got to
the physical training part.''
   In February 1987 a young University of Massachusetts officer
shot herself in the head after the first week of the 13-week course.
</TEXT>
