<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0668 09-26 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede CLEVELAND</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Would `Lead America Nowhere'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP six grafs new with comments from Dukakis on ACLU issue;
EDITS elsewhere to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said Monday
the vice president was wrong in suggesting in the previous night's
debate that he agreed with controversial positions of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   ``That's nonsense and he knows it,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis addressed the ACLU issue at an evening rally in Jersey
City after ignoring the issue earlier in the day even as aides
moved to distance him from positions taken by the civil liberties
organization which he holds a membership in.
   In the debate Sunday night, Bush questioned Dukakis' membership
in the group and noted positions taken by the ACLU, including
opposition to restrictions on child pornography, opposition to
movie ratings and opposition to the tax exemption for the Roman
Catholic Church.
   ``Last night he suggested that I agreed with every position ever
taken by the ACLU, and that is nonsense and he knows it,'' Dukakis
said.
   ``Two months ago, I signed one of the toughest child pornography
laws in the United States,'' he said. ``I've always suggested tax
exemptions for religious institutions. And I certainly don't
support Oliver North, who the ACLU is defending.''
   But ACLU president Norman Dorsen said in New York that Bush had
misstated the organization's positions. And Dukakis aides earlier
had noted that the ACLU had filed lawsuits against Dukakis as
governor of Massachusetts over his plans to use roadblocks to catch
drunken drivers and a policy that effectively bars homosexuals from
becoming foster parents.
   Earlier in Cleveland, Dukakis did not raise the issue, although
Ohio Sen. John Glenn told reporters that Dukakis ``has to respond''
on the ACLU issue. Dukakis made his first campaign stop in
Cleveland, a reliable Democratic stronghold in a major industrial
state, after his first nationally televised confrontation with Bush
in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Sunday.
   Before an estimated crowd of 3,000 people in Cleveland's Public
Square, Dukakis belittled Bush's debate answers on questions such
as Social Security, Medicare and the federal deficit.
   ``I asked George Bush to explain how he'd bring down those
massive federal deficits without raiding the Social Security trust
fund,'' Dukakis said. ``And what did he say? Not one word.''
   On each issue, he asked what Bush's answer had been and elicited
the crowd's response: ``Not one word.''
   ``Mr. Bush offers the easy way,'' Dukakis said. ``He sees no
challenges. He offers no solutions. And he will lead America
nowhere as president of the United States.''
   Dukakis recalled former President Kennedy's crucial debate with
GOP Vice President Richard Nixon in 1960, and said Kennedy also had
chosen Cleveland for his first post-debate appearance.
   ``And all of you know what happened,'' Dukakis said. Kennedy won
the debate and the election that year, although he lost Ohio.
   ``Last night, we got down to the real issues in this campaign,''
Dukakis said. ``We heard a lot of talk last night from Mr. Bush
about the mainstream. But it's clear from what we heard last night
that he's willing to leave American families high and dry.''
   Dukakis' week-long campaign swing will take him to several of
the biggest states he is seeking to win. By week's end, he also
will have visited Illinois, Pennsylvania, New York, Texas and
California.
   Campaign manager Susan Estrich said overnight polls showed
Dukakis was judged as decisive winner of the debate, although she
disclosed no details. She said campaign surveys showed ``a very
strong increase in the governor's favorabilities,'' or people
responding favorably to Dukakis.
   Dukakis aides released a list of 16 Bush statements during the
debate that they contended were errors or distortions.
   They noted Bush's debate statement that he wants ``to be the one
to banish chemical and biological weapons,'' but said he cast three
tie-breaking Senate votes as vice president to renew production of
chemical weapons after a 17-year moratorium.
   The aides said Bush praised the Surgeon General's effort to
educate the public about AIDS, but that the Reagan administration
opposed sending AIDS educational materials to households until
forced by Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
