<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0666 09-26 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Peace Talks Resume In The Congo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Americans meeting both sides. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, The Cubans ... with minor editing to conform</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. negotiators met separately with
Angolan-Cuban and South African delegations Monday as a new round
of Angolan peace talks opened. The Americans were clearly hopeful
of an accord.
   Chester Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, sat down with South Africa's delegation to sound
it on an Angolan proposal for the withdrawal of Cuban troops within
three years, conference sources said.
   Later Monday, Crocker met with the Cuban-Angola delegation to
give them South African proposals on the withdrawal, according to
the sources, who spoke on condition their names not be used.
   President Reagan, speaking at the United Nations in New York on
Monday, said that ``years of patient diplomacy and support for
those in Angola who seek self-determination are having their
effect.''
   ``We look forward to an accord between the governments of
Angola, Cuba, and South Africa that will bring about a complete
withdrawal of all foreign troops _primarily Cuban _ from Angola,''
Reagan said.
   South Africa has insisted the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in
Angola be withdrawn within a year.
   The Cubans are backing Angola's Marxist government, which is
fighting a 13-year-old bush war against guerrillas backed by the
United States and South Africa. The Reagan administration was
optimistic about the talks, but South Africa's
government-controlled radio expressed reservations.
   ``It is now imperative that ... the Angolan and Cuban
governments stop stalling on the agreement to withdraw the Cuban
military contingent from Angola and set a realistic timetable for a
Cuban troop withdrawal,'' the radio said.
   The leader of the South African delegation, Neil Van Heerden,
director-general of foreign affairs, claimed Cubans had moved
beyond a cease-fire line to attack the rebels, the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola. Angola has denied the Cubans
are involved in the attack.
   South African troops already have pulled out of Angola as part
of the Aug. 10 cease-fire.
   Angola has said it will take four years to send the Cubans home.
South Africa has insisted they pull out before it grants
independence to South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, which
borders Angola to the south. Independence is to be granted within
the next year.
   Some African nations have joined the United States in trying to
persuade Angola to begin talks with the rebels, but it has refused
any official contact.
   Angola was represented at the talks Monday by Lt. Gen. Antonio
Franca, chief of staff of the Angolan military. Cuba sent Carlos
Aldana Escalante, Communist Party Central Committee secretary.
   Other observers were from the United Nations, the Soviet Union,
France and the South-West African People's Organization, which has
been fighting to oust South Africa from South-West Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
