<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Floods     09-26 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Floods,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Boats, Helicopters Mobilized as Indian Flood Toll Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H.S. NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army boats and helicopters took
thousands of marooned people to safety in Punjab state Monday after
four days of incessant rain flooded northern India and killed
hundreds of people, authorities said.
   At least 70 people died in Punjab and floodwaters in the
neighboring states of Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Jammu and
Kashmir killed nearly 200 others, officials said.
   Agriculture Minister Mohammad Shafi of Jammu and Kashmir state
said at least 34 people were washed away in swirling floodwaters
there since Sunday.
   The toll was expected to rise because communications were cut
off with many villages after rivers overflowed their embankments.
   Relief officials said at least 200,000 people were stranded in
78 villages across Punjab, which produces more than half of India's
wheat and rice. Punjab Gov. S.S. Ray said many of those crops were
destroyed.
   Officials said 35 power stations in Punjab were ordered shut
because of the danger of electrocution, plunging flood-hit areas of
Jalandhar, Ludhiana, Amritsar, Kapurthala and Hoshiarpur into
darkness. Disrupted road and rail links and continued rains
hampered relief efforts.
   The Yamuna River was flowing ``well above danger levels'' in the
federal capital of New Delhi, according to officials at the Flood
Control Center, and villagers living along the river bank were
being evacuating to higher ground.
   A government spokesman told reporters in New Delhi on Monday
said no threat to the city itself existed, although water levels
were rising.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi appointed a crisis management group
of government officials to handle the flood emergency, the
spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The hardest-hit Pujabi city was Jalandhar, where an estimated
50,000 Indians were isolated.
   ``Our first priority is to evacuate the marooned and to give
them food and shelter,'' Ray told reporters.
   He said 100 boats were pressed into service and another 100 were
requested from the army and the Ministry of Agriculture.
   Helicopters dropped food into stricken areas, but were hampered
by rain.
   Many roads were covered with up to eight feet of water,
officials said. Landslides set off by the rains cut off access to
other roads.
   Rail service among the cities of Ludhiana, Jalandhar and
Amritsar was suspended due to rising rivers.
   Floods caused by summer monsoons are a frequent problem in
India, Bangladesh and Nepal.
   Last month, monsoon-swollen rivers flooded three-fourths of
Bangladesh. The government said at least 1,000 people died.
Newspapers put the toll at more than 2,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
