<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Skull-Bush     09-26 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Skull-Bush,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fort Sill Calls Charges `Complete, Total Rumor'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SILL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official at Fort Sill Army Post said
Monday the claim by an Apache leader that Vice President George
Bush's father stole Geronimo's skull years ago is groundless.
   Towana Spivey, director of the Fort Sill museum, said to his
knowledge, Geronimo's grave was disturbed one time, shortly after
his death in 1909, but the body was not disturbed.
   Geronimo, the famous Apache leader, died at Fort Sill in 1909,
and was buried there.
   But some members of the San Carlos Apache tribe in Arizona
believe Geronimo's skull was stolen years ago by Prescott S. Bush
and put on display at the meeting place of the Skull and Bones, a
secret society that both Prescott S. Bush and his son, the vice
president, belonged to at Yale University.
   Former San Carlos tribal chairman Ned Anderson said his
information comes from a 55-year-old document called ``History of
Our Order'' _ purportedly a chronicle of Skull and Bones activities.
</TEXT>
