<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dornan-AIDS     09-26 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dornan-AIDS,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Brother-In-Law Denies Sister's Claim He's Gay and
Has AIDS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 3rd graf may offend some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in law of Rep. Robert Dornan
denied he is homosexual and is suffering from AIDS, despite an
emotional public description of his alleged ailment by the
conservative congressman's wife.
   Douglas Richard Hansen, 51, a San Diego landscape architect,
angrily denounced comments made Sept. 18 by his sister, Sallie
Dornan.
   Mrs. Dornan told a Garden Grove town hall meeting she lost her
temper and called a gay demonstrator a ``fag'' because she was
distraught over her homosexual brother's battle against AIDS, the
Los Angeles Times reported.
   Hansen denied he is homosexual, saying he is healthy and has
seen his sister only once since their mother's funeral in 1983.
   Hansen, who threatened to file a defamation lawsuit against the
Dornans, said he came forward for two reasons: ``To defend my good
name and to blast that guy (Dornan) out of the water, too. He's a
turkey.''
   Dornan and his wife both declined to comment, said Brian
Bennett, Dornan's chief of staff.
   ``It has no bearing on his responsibility as a U.S.
congressman,'' Bennett said. ``It's a matter between his wife and
her brother.''
   Hansen said that because he had many gay friends and feared even
casual contact with them might expose him to the disease, he had
been tested for the AIDS virus four or five times in the last two
years. All the tests were negative, he added.
   ``Why does she come off the wall and say something like this,''
Hansen said. ``I can't believe it. She's been in politics for
years, and she's got to do this to me? I can't believe it.''
   Dornan, a Republican running for a third term, has been
criticized by gay activists for his stand against
anti-discrimination legislation and his opposition to having any
gay caucus within the GOP.
   The congressman's daughter, Robin, said her parents would not
respond to inquiries about Hansen.
   Responding to questions about how the Dornans learned of
Hansen's alleged illness, Robin Dornan said: ``That's personal.
There's been communication. That's all I'm going to say.
   ``It's something that's very, very sensitive and very personal
and very sad. We just want to communicate with him and we don't
want him to be sick and alone.''
   Mrs. Dornan described her brother's condition to the crowd of
200 at the forum.
   ``He tells me every day; the thinner he gets, the sores covering
his body,'' she said.
   Robin Dornan said her mother was speaking in the future tense
about what she feared would happen to her brother in the advanced
stages of the fatal illness.
   The Times reported that Hansen appeared robust and healthy
during the interview.
   ``I'll take an AIDS test anytime,'' Hansen said. ``I'm a healthy
51.''
   He held out his arms and referring to the purple lesions that
are symptoms of a skin cancer common among AIDS patients, he asked,
``Do you see any spots?'' As for his weight, Hansen grinned and
said, ``I'm getting a little porky.''
</TEXT>
