<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About two dozen demonstrators, protesting the
lack of affordable housing, were arrested Monday when they blocked
a roadway on the grounds of the U.S. Capitol, according to police.
   The demonstrators were part of a larger group which has
scheduled daily protests near the Capitol until the elections in
November.
   Those arrested were 24 members of Justice House in Roanoke, Va.,
and two juveniles.
   A police spokesman said the protesters had broken away from the
main demonstration and had tried to enter the Capitol while
carrying a wooden cross that had been made by two homeless men.
   When they were barred entry ``they broke away (from the main
group of demonstrators) and sat down in the roadway,'' said Daniel
Nichols, a spokesman for the U.S. Capitol police.
   The 26 were charged with obstructing passage on Capitol grounds
and demonstrating without a permit.
   The first charge carries a maximum $500 fine and six months in
jail. The second carries a maximum $300 fine and 90 days in jail.
