<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-US-Gulf 2ndLd-Writethru a0680 09-26 1002</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0680,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Eases Gulf Policing Action</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 4th graf bgng ``Talking to ...'' to
include House debate on sanctions against Iraq; picks up pvs 5th
graf bgng ``After making ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing the Iran-Iraq cease-fire agreement, the
Reagan administration said Monday it will end America's
ship-escorting operation in the Persian Gulf while maintaining a
presence there.
   President Reagan's decision to terminate the close-quarter
convoying of neutral commercial ships came after U.S. officials
reviewed how the Aug. 20 cease-fire was working, said White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The move substantially lowers the U.S. profile in the troubled
waters nearly three months after a U.S. Navy Aegis cruiser shot
down an Iranian civilian airliner with 290 people on board. The
United States said it regretted the accident, and officials have
been weighing a program to compensate relatives of the victims.
   Talking to reporters aboard Air Force One while Reagan flew here
from Washington, Fitzwater said the administration decided to relax
the Persian Gulf sea-lane policing operation only after
``consulting with allies and friends in the region.''
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, the House was urged to pass
legislation imposing economic sanctions against Iraq as ``a
concrete expression of congressional outrage against the use of
chemical weapons.''
   A vote on the resolution, which authorizes even sterner future
sanctions if Iraq persists in its alleged poison gas attacks
against it Kurdish minority, was postponed until Tuesday.
   The Reagan administration opposes the legislation on grounds
that it ``would not bring us closer'' to the goal of ending Iraq's
use of chemical weapons.''
   After making a farewell address to the U.N. General Assembly,
Reagan met with Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, the emir of Kuwait,
and also had a session set for later Monday with leaders of the
Gulf Cooperation Council, which is headed by Saudi Arabia.
   During the meeting with the Kuwaiti official, Reagan was asked
why the change was being made in the U.S. military operation.
   ``It's just a little difference in the way it's being done.
That's a Navy decision because of the new situation ... thus
cease-fire.''
   The president said he thought the emir would recognize that ``we
are not lessening our protection of them at all.''
   Asked if there was any chance of normalization with Iran, he
said, ``You know me, I always hope. We're waiting to see what
develops from this cease-fire.''
   Fitzwater said it would take a few days to revamp the U.S.
military presence in the region. He said there would no formal
announcement when that takes place.
   In effect, the United States will replace its close-quarter
escorting of commercial ships with a sort of arms-length
surveillance operation. The formation was likened by U.S. officials
to a ``zone'' coverage of shipping rather than a ``man-to-man''
coverage.
   The analogy to a kind of coverage used in football means that
U.S. ships will watch selected areas of the gulf for trouble,
rather than focusing the protective operation on individual vessels.
   In his General Assembly speech, Reagan said the world can feel
``the uplift of hope'' in the gulf war, which he called ``one of
the bloodiest conflicts since World War II.''
   ``The resolution and the firmness of the allied nations in
keeping the Persian Gulf open to international shipping not only
upheld the rule of law, it helped prevent further spread of the
conflict and laid the basis for peace,'' he said.
   During a brief exchange with reporters after a private meeting
with U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar, Reagan also
said he hoped the easing of tensions in that part of the world
could lead to the release of nine Americans held hostage by
pro-Iranian elements in Lebanon.
   ``I'm keeping my fingers crossed on that because I have high
hopes,'' the president said. ``I have high hopes.''
   Asked if he thought a hostage-release could be achieved in the
four months remaining in his administration, Reagan replied, ``I
don't know if anything can be done that quickly, but we haven't let
up.''
   Reagan also said, however, that ``I'm superstitious about
calling a no-hitter before the game is over.''
   Fitzwater sought to minimize the significance of Reagan's
off-hand remark. ``What he said was, `I don't want to talk about
hostages because it might be bad luck,' '' the spokesman said,
saying Reagan was alluding to a baseball superstitution that one
never talks about a pitcher who might throw a no-hitter against
opposing batters.
   White House chief of staff Kenneth A. Duberstein, asked whether
something was in the works to advance the cause of the hostages,
said, ``There is nothing new on that.''
   Fitzwater said ``there is no new morsel of information'' to
encourage U.S. officials, and said ``there is no new signal''
indicating a hostage release.
   Reagan told Perez de Cuellar that ``peace between Iran and Iraq
was uncertain,'' Fitzwater told reporters at an afternoon briefing
at the Waldorf Astoria Hotel.
   In announcing the phase-down of the U.S. ship protection
operation, Fitzwater stressed that ``the U.S. intends to maintain
in the gulf the forces required to protect U.S.-flagged shipping
and support our national objectives. These changes in no way alter
our commitment to freedom of navigation in the gulf.''
   The White House said that the modification in the U.S. operation
``entails a change from a tight escort procedure to an `accompany'
regime. In an accompany regime, U.S. forces will be positioned such
that they can take appropriate action if U.S.-flagged ships are
directly threatened.''
   There have been no attacks on neutral shipping in the gulf since
the ceasefire began on Aug. 20.
   The U.S. convoy operation began 14 months ago and involved a
precise Navy formation used to protect against potential Iranian
attacks against Kuwaiti tankers re-registered under the U.S. flag.
   The United States had 26 ships in its Joint Task Force Middle
East, including 17 in the Persian Gulf, as of Sept. 16. The Navy
had conducted 85 convoy operations since the escorts began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
