<DOCNO> AP880926-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Reagan-Soviet     09-26 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Reagan-Soviet,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Reagan's U.N. Speech Overall `Positive,' If `Acerbic'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-UN, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union praised President
Reagan's farewell speech to the U.N. General Assembly on Monday as
``generally positive'' and the kind of speech he should have used
to begin his presidency, not end it.
   But it also found the speech ``acerbic'' at times and
``self-serving.''
   Last year the Soviet Union was the target of harsh criticism by
Reagan in his General Assembly address.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press from Moscow,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov called Reagan's speech
on Monday ``in general, positive ... Overall, it was good and
tomorrow (Tuesday) we will listen to the Soviet side'' when Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze speaks.
   ``I wish he (Reagan) had started his presidency with this kind
of speech, not finish it,'' Gerasimov said of Reagan's seventh and
final address to the General Assembly.
   Reagan lectured the communist world last year, from Moscow to
Managua, on the virtues of democracy and private enterprise and the
perceived inferiority of their own system. He praised the United
States for what he suggested was a unique harmony with ``the human
heart,'' a quality he claimed was lacking in other forms of
government.
   In 1987, Reagan condemned the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan;
this year he welcomed the Soviet withdrawal and encouraged an early
withdrawal. Last year he condemned Soviet dictatatorship; this year
he cited ``a change going to the source of postwar tensions and to
the once seemingly impossible dream of ending the twin threats of
our time _ totalitarianism and thermonuclear world war.''
   This year, citing the Moscow summit, Reagan said he was able to
speak ``to the young people of the Soviet Union about the wonder
and splendor of human freedom.''
   Gerasimov commented, ``The president's upbeat mood, his optimism
about where the world is going are things we completely agree
with.''
   ``We are also very glad to hear from him his appreciation of
U.N. efforts to maintain international peace and security,''
Gerasimov said.
   ``It is certainly a change in position, which we warmly
welcome.''
   Gerasimov said it was positive that Reagan cited the easing of
international relations, which Reagan said began in the Geneva
summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``That sounds pretty good to us,'' Gerasimov said.
   He noted that Reagan said the areas of disagreement on a
50-percent cut in strategic nuclear weapons were decreasing and
that a treaty could be signed within a year.
   ``Both sides wanted this in his administration,'' Gerasimov
said. ``But it proved too difficult. But we agree that the sooner
the better. Within a year is okay with us.''
   The Soviet Union also agrees with Reagan's call for a
renegotiated global ban on the use of chemical weapons.
   Gerasimov said Reagan made some ``acerbic remarks'' and
``self-serving'' comments about the superiority of democracy over
Soviet socialism and restrictions on human rights in the Soviet
Union.
   ``Actually,'' he said, ``the world is really changing.''
   In his speech, Reagan called on Moscow to halt its massive aid
to the Nicaraguan government and Gerasimov remarked: ``In Central
America, we are pragmatic, we are not adding fuel to the conflict.
   ``We say the Guatemala Agreements must be fulfilled, and we are
ready to not give aid to Nicaragua if America stops its own aid to
the Contra rebels,'' Gerasimov said.
   It seemed ``a little bit strange,'' he said, ``that the
president of a big and powerful country raises the danger from
small Nicaragua. It does not sound convincing to us.
   ``The government of Nicaragua is ready to talk to the Contras,
and I think the president exaggerates what really is happening
there.''
   The Guatemala Agreements to which Gerasimov referred was the
signing of a peace plan by five Central American presidents on Aug.
7, 1987. The plan was designed by Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias, who won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts.
   One major goal of the Arias plan was an end to all outside aid
to the region's insurgencies.
</TEXT>
