<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OLY--Newspage-Johnson 1stLd-Writethru a0764 09-26 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OLY--Newspage-Johnson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0764,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Olympic Gold Medal Given To Lewis After Johnson Test Positive for
Steroid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with awarding of gold to American.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Ben Johnson was stripped
Tuesday of his world-record victory in the 100-meter dash after
testing positive for steroids, and the Olympic gold medal awarded
to American Carl Lewis.
   International Olympic Committee spokeswoman Michele Verdier said
the IOC executive board unanimously approved its medical
commission's recommendation that the medal be withdrawn because
traces of Stanozolol, a water-based anabolic steroid, were found in
Johnson's urine sample after Saturday's race.
   Johnson flew to New York, and his manager said he was shocked by
the test result.
   ``The only thing we can say at this stage is that it is a
tragedy, a mistake or a sabotage,'' said Johnson's manager, Larry
Heidebrecht.
   ``Up to five days before the race, Ben was in perfect condition.
Something has happened in those days,'' he said.
   ``We do not know what happened and how it happened, but
apparently somebody has sabotaged Ben and we will find out who it
was and how it was done.''
   The Canadian sprinter is automatically suspended from
international competition for two years.
   Johnson finished first in his long-awaited showdown with Lewis
on Saturday in 9.79 seconds, four-hundredths of a second under his
own world record set at the 1987 world championships in Rome. Lewis
was second in an American-record 9.92 seconds.
   With Johnson disqualified, an International Amateur Athletics
Federation spokesman said Lewis moves up to first, Britain's
Lindford Christie gets the silver and American Calvin Smith the
bronze.
   The decision revived Lewis' bid for an unprecedented win of gold
medals in each of two consecutive Olympics in the 100- and
200-meter dashes, the long jump and the 400-meter relay. He won the
long jump Monday.
   Johnson was the seventh athlete and third gold medalist to test
positive at the Seoul Games. Officials had predicted 15 positive
tests among the almost 10,000 athletes.
</TEXT>
