<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Italy-Slayings     09-26 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Slayings,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underworld Suspected In Slayings Of Judge, Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALTANISETTA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An activist who campaigned against
organized crime was killed by gunmen Monday, one day after a judge
who sentenced two crime bosses to prison was killed, authorities
said.
   Government officials said the judge's slaying is a sign that
organized crime figures are trying to intimidate authorities.
   ``This is a crime with the clear stamp of the Mafia, aimed at
intimidation,'' Interior Minister Antonio Gava said Monday.
   Magistrate Antonio Saetta, 66, and his son Stefano, 35, were
slain Sunday by gunmen who shadowed their car, rammed it with their
vehicle and stopped it on a country road ouside Caltanisetta in
central Sicily. The assailants fired at least 20 shots through the
windows.
   On Monday, meanwhile, attackers fired on Mauro Rostagno in
Trapani as he drove home from an appearance on local television to
discuss drug abuse and organized crime influence, the Italian news
agency ANSA reported.
   Police in the western Sicilian town called the killing
``Mafia-style'' but said it was under investigation.
   Rostagno was a leader of ``Continous Fight,'' a leftist
organization that organized protests during the 1960s and 1970s. He
moved to Trapani a decade ago and founded a drug rehabilitation
center.
   Rostagno, 46, appeared regularly on a local television program,
campaigning against drug use and organized crime.
   Saetta had sentenced two powerful crime bosses, brothers Michele
and Salvatore Greco, to life in prison.
   ``This assassination is a very serious signal as to how deep and
difficult to extract are the roots of the evil plant of organized
crime,'' President Francesco Cossiga said of the Saetta killing.
   Authorities have linked the slayings of eight magistrates since
1968 to organized crime.
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita said the reaction of political forces
``has to be strong and united.''
   Gava flew to the island of Sicily on Monday for a meeting with
authorities there about the killing.
   Besides the Greco trial, Saetta presided over the trial of three
organized crime figures convicted of killing Capt. Emanuele Basile
of the carabinieri, or national police. The Grecos were convicted
of masterminding the killing of Judge Rocco Chinnici, who had been
investigating their activities.
</TEXT>
