<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     09-26 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Soldiers Killed in Peruvian Guerrilla Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist rebels ambushed an army truck in the
highlands Monday and killed five soldiers and wounded six in a
crossfire after crippling the vehicle with land mines, police said.
   Also Monday, the military command in Ayacucho state said an army
patrol killed two rebels in a clash with a column of Shining Path
guerrillas Sept. 20.
   The ambush Monday occurred on a lonely mountain road 27 miles
east of Huancavelica, a state capital 155 miles southeast of Lima.
   Police said rebels had mined a 100-yard stretch of dirt road
with dynamite every 10 yards and that at least nine charges
exploded as the truck passed.
   A lieutenant and four soldiers were killed. Eight soldiers who
escaped harm and some of the six wounded troops managed to repel
the attack and the Shining Path guerrillas withdrew after half an
hour, according to the police report.
   Police said the rebels were believed to have suffered casualties
but took their wounded with them.
   In Ayacucho, a state capital 70 miles southeast of Huancavelica
and 230 miles southeast of Lima, the military command said a patrol
encountered a rebel column on Sept. 20, killing two guerrillas in
the ensuing firefight.
   A military communique said troops captured arms, grenades and
subversive pamphlets in the shootout but that other members of the
guerrilla force escaped. The communique did not say if the patrol
suffered casualties.
   The impoverished countryside around Ayacucho was the birthplace
eight years of the Mao-inspired Shining Path insurgency.
   Since then the violence has spread through much of the country
and more than 12,000 people have been killed.
</TEXT>
