<HEAD>Investigators Link Terrorist Attack To Two Earlier Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSRUHE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorists who fired on the car
of a government finance official have been linked to slayings in
1985 and 1986, authorities said Monday.
   Objects found in a car used by the assailants were ``of a
similar nature'' to evidence from the 1985 slaying of industrialist
Ernst Zimmerman and the 1986 killing of diplomat Gerold von
Braunmuehl, said Alexander Prechtel, a spokesman for the federal
prosecutor's office.
   Prechtel would not elaborate.
   Attackers last week fired on the car of Hans Tietmeyer, the No.
2 official in the Finance Ministry. Neither Tietmeyer nor his
driver were hurt.
   The Red Army Faction, West Germany's most notorious terrorist
gang, claimed responsibility, saying its plans to kill Tietmeyer
were thwarted by a jammed rifle.
   Bonn officials linked the attack to this week's joint World
Bank-International Monetary Fund annual meetings in West Berlin.
   Tietmeyer, a key adviser to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, was actively
involved in planning for the talks.
   On Saturday, Prechtel said investigators identified Red Army
Faction member Birgit Hogefeld as one of the assailants. He said
Hogefeld rented the car under an assumed name before the attack.
   The car was later found in a Bonn suburb a few miles from the
attack site.
</TEXT>
