<2ND_LINE>AM-Eliot Memorial,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>T.S. Eliot Centenary Remembered At Westminster Abbey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admirers of poet T.S. Eliot read his works in
Westminster Abbey and in theaters and meeting places around London
on Monday night to mark the centenary of the poet's birth.
   Actress Jill Balcon read Eliot's ``Four Quartets'' during a
service at the abbey, and Eliot's widow, Valerie, laid a wreath at
his memorial tablet there.
   The Poetry Society, Britain's main poetry organization,
organized readings around the capital in churches, concert halls
and other meeting places.
   Ted Hughes, the poet laureate, introduced a Sunday night reading
of ``The Waste Land,'' Eliot's most famous poem, at London's Palace
Theater.
   Thomas Stearns Eliot, one of the major poets of the 20th
century, won the Nobel Prize in literature in 1948. He was born in
St. Louis on Sept. 26, 1888, became a British citizen and died in
London Jan. 4, 1965.
   Many articles about Eliot and his works have appeared in the
British press for the centenary and Mrs. Eliot has edited a first
volume of his letters, covering the years 1898 to 1922.
   ``Her continuing labor of love is everywhere evident in her
editing. ... It is inevitable and right that Eliot should have a
centenary monument; fitting that his widow's life-work should
provide it,'' wrote poet and critic Alan Jenkins in a review of the
book in the weekly Times Literary Supplement last Friday.
</TEXT>
