<HEAD>Jackson Urges Voter Registration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines a0678, AM-Jackson, and a0797, AM-Jackson</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson urged his supporters to go
door-to-door to sign up new voters who he said could provide a
margin of victory for Democrat Michael Dukakis in November's
general election.
   ``As the Bible tells us, there's power in the word, and the vote
is the word,'' Jackson told more than 1,000 people Sunday at the
founding conference for the state chapter of the Rainbow Coalition,
a multiracial network that Jackson founded.
   He said voters should go ``door-to-door, church-to-church,
synagogue-to-synagogue, school-to-school, and along the highways
and byways of this state'' to register voters.
   In a Sept. 20 letter to Rainbow Coalition board members, Jackson
said the nation's 13 million unregistered blacks and Hispanics
could be the margin of victory for Dukakis, who is running against
Vice President George Bush.
   ``We can't throw away this kind of power by not registering and
not voting,'' he wrote.
   Jackson, who lost the Democratic nomination to Dukakis, has
recently started to make campaign appearances on behalf of the
Massachusetts governor.
   In San Francisco, Jackson told a meeting of 200 labor leaders
and supporters that Bush was running a ``mean-spirited'' campaign.
   ``There's a certain mean-spiritedness in this Bush-Quayle
approach,'' Jackson said of the Republican ticket, which he
criticized for ignoring the needs of many Americans, including
women, minorities, the homeless and the poor.
   Jackson also attended a rally at the University of California at
Berkeley, where he concluded his remarks before a crowd of about
4,000 by urging students to come forward and register to vote.
   A university spokesman called the rally one of the biggest
gatherings in recent years.
   This week Jackson said he planned to visit Tennessee, Georgia
and Maryland this week to urge Rainbow Coalition members to sign up
new voters.
