<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0635,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Stabilizes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-7 UPDATE with latest condition report, stock
activity, eliminates outdated material. Picks up 9th graf pvs,
Doctors found ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mammoth sumo wrestlers joined crowds outside the
Imperial Palace on Monday to pray for 87-year-old Emperor Hirohito,
whose condition stabilized despite continued internal bleeding.
   ``The emperor is in stable condition ... but last night he
discharged a slight amount of blood,'' Kenji Maeda, head of general
affairs for the Imperial Household Agency, told reporters early
Tuesday morning.
   Hirohito had a fever of 98.4 Tuesday, down from around 99 Monday
but still higher than his normal temperature of 95.9. On Saturday
it rose to 102.6, prompting concern about his fate, palace
officials said.
   The stock market was up in early trading Tuesday after
fluctuating Monday, reflecting uncertainty over Hirohito's health.
Majiro Ueda of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage, said
reports the emperor was in stable condition encouraged investors to
trade more actively.
   On Monday, Hirohito watched television dramas and received his
sons, Crown Prince Akihito and Prince Hitachi, and their wives for
brief chats, palace Maeda said.
   The emperor's imperial duties were transferred to Akihito, 54,
last Thursday.
   The sumo wrestlers, dressed in silk robes, added their names
Monday to registries to wish Hirohito well. Palace officials said
more than 450,000 well-wishers have journeyed to the Imperial
Household Agency's 12 registry sites across the country.
   Doctors found traces of blood in the emperor's bowels for the
fourth straight day, indicating an intestinal hemorrhage had not
been contained. They administered another .43 pints in blood
transfusions, bringing the total since Hirohito first vomited blood
Sept. 19 to 5.96 pints.
   The nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun quoted medical experts
Monday as saying cancer was the likely cause of Hirohito's
continuous discharge of blood.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny news reports
that the emperor has cancer and instead have urged the Japanese
media to refrain from speculation. Cancer is rarely acknowledged
publicly in Japan.
   Outside the moats surrounding the forested imperial compound,
NTT, Japan's giant telephone company, installed a row of free
public phones so well-wishers could call home.
   ``We wanted to do something to be helpful to all the people who
have come out of concern for the emperor,'' said Yuji Itoh, a
company official. More than 16,000 people have used the phones, he
added, most to tell their families they had recorded their names.
   Also Monday, Japan's third-largest newspaper apologized for an
editorial inadvertently published in its English-language editions
expressing sadness at the emperor's demise.
   ``We deeply regret the completely erroneous editorial, retract
it in entirety, and apologize deeply,'' the Mainichi Shimbun said.
It did not explain how the slip at the Mainichi Daily News had
occurred.
   The newspaper also apologized to the government and the palace.
</TEXT>
