<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     09-26 0926</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0963</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ George Bush and Michael Dukakis, each
hesitant to declare victory in their first head-on clash, are
awaiting the voters' judgment about a debate marked by sharp words
on patriotism, Iran-Contra and Bush's choice of a running mate.
Neither committed a serious mistake or landed a knockout blow.
   ``It was a good night,'' Dukakis said after the 90-minute,
nationally televised encounter Sunday at Wake Forest University.
Separately, Bush flashed a thumbs-up sign to supporters and said
the debate had given him a chance ``to spell out some of the
differences.''
   In the first of two face-to-face meetings, there was very little
warmth between the candidates other than the traditional handshakes
at the beginning and end. Bush said he had hoped for a ``little
friendlier an evening.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ The debate was over and gridlock
reigned in the press room. It wasn't reporters trying to reach
George Bush and Michael Dukakis, it was the stampede of political
heavyweights shamelessly promoting their candidate's performance
while making the other guy's seem abysmal.
   Senators and governors competed for reporters' attention and
television's cameras to claim that Dukakis came across as
presidential, humane and compassionate and Bush as plastic and
fuzzy _ or vice versa.
   In political parlance, it is known as the spin patrol and a glut
of spin was spun by politicians brought in for just that purpose.
The Democrats had the likes of Sens. Ted Kennedy and Bill Bradley
and the Republicans had Sen. Alan Simpson, former Sen. John Tower
and New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Round One of the presidential candidates'
debates went to Michael Dukakis by a slender margin over George
Bush, according to a panel of veteran debate judges who kept score
for The Associated Press.
   Three judges gave the nod to Dukakis, while the other three
sided with Bush, but the Democrat emerged with the most points on
their ballots, 144-141.
   Several hundred television viewers polled by ABC immediately
after Sunday night's debate also thought the Massachusetts governor
was the winner.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDS: For release 10 a.m. EDT. Time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most state unemployment insurance funds would
have to borrow billions from the federal government to pay benefits
in a future recession because of inadequate reserves, according to
a congressional report released today.
   The General Accounting Office study found the Unemployment
Insurance system's ability to cushion economic hard times for many
Americans has declined as states have tried to manage their
financially troubled programs.
   Created to help working people make it through economic hard
times, the state trusts are tightening eligibility requirements
solely to keep their books in the black, leaving more Americans to
face a bleak future if a recession strikes, the GAO said.
</TEXT>
