<DOCNO> AP880926-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1546EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Chile-Glance ADV02   09-26 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chile-Glance, ADV 02,0430</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Chile-at-a-Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: one of a four-story package</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Chile:
   
   THE LAND _ Chile is a long, narrow territory of 292,000 square
miles extending 2,670 miles along the southwestern coast of South
America. It ranges from the semi-tropical, desert north to the
rainy, windswept south. Wedged between the Andes mountains on the
east and Pacific Ocean on the west, its average width is only 95
miles. Its largest cities are Santiago, the capital, where nearly 5
million of the nation's 12 million people live; Valparaiso, its
largest port, 75 miles north west of Santiago, and Concepcion, an
industrial center 350 miles south. It is bordered by Peru on the
north and Bolivia and Argentina on the east.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ The population is predominantly a mixture of the
local Araucano Indians and descendants of the Spanish conquerors.
In the agricultural southern provinces a large German immigrant
community exists. The official language is Spanish, and literacy
exceeds 90 percent. While Chile has no official religion, more than
90 percent of Chileans call themselves Roman Catholics.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Chile is the world's second biggest producer of
copper, after the United States. In recent years, the economy has
diversified and the country has become the Southern Hemisphere's
largest fruit exporter. Mining, fishing and agriculture, including
a booming timber industry, are the main economic activities. The
annual economic growth rate has averaged 5 percent since the
mid-1980s. Inflation stands at around 10 percent annually, one of
the lowest rates in Latin America. The currency is the peso, and
the present exchange rate is 246 pesos to the U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Chile launched a struggle for independence from Spain
on Sept. 18, 1810, and finally attained it in 1818, becoming a
republic and establishing a reputation as one of Latin America's
most stable democracies. Presidents were freely elected, even in
1881 during a victorious four-year territorial war against
neighboring Bolivia and Peru. Major political disturbances were
historically rare, consisting of a brief civil war in 1891 and a
series of coups in 1925. In 1973, however, the military led by Gen.
Augusto Pinochet ousted the elected leftist government of President
Salvador Allende, an avowed Marxist who died in the takeover.
Pinochet has remained in power since and seeks ratification of a
new period of rule, until 1997, in an Oct. 5 referendum.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
