<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--JohnPaul-Quotes ADV09   09-26 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--John Paul-Quotes, ADV 09,0538</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--John Paul's Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are significant quotations from Pope
John Paul II in his 10-year pontificate:
   ``Even if I cannot express myself well in your ... our Italian
language, if I make a mistake you will correct me,'' to the crowd
in St. Peter's Square in his first public appearance after election
as first non-Italian pontiff in 455 years, Oct. 16, 1978.
   ``(Man) cannot become the slave of things, the slave of economic
systems, the slave of production, the slave of his own products,''
his first encyclical, ``Redemptor Hominis,'' issued March 15, 1979.
   ``Never lose your trust, do not be defeated, do not be
discouraged; do not cut yourselves off from the roots from which we
had our origins,'' farewell Mass in Krakow on first trip to Poland,
June 10, 1979.
   ``I pray for that brother of ours who shot me, and whom I have
sincerely pardoned,'' from his hospital bed, May 17, 1981, four
days after being wounded by a Turkish gunman, Mehmet Ali Agca.
   ``I came here as a herald of peace to proclaim a gospel of peace
and a message of reconciliation,'' Cardiff, Wales, June 2, 1982,
ending historic trip to Britain during Falklands war.
   ``No human law can morally justify induced abortion ... nor can
the behavior of local authorities in trying to limit the
responsible freedom of parents to decide whether to procreate
children be allowed on the moral plane,'' address in San Juan,
Puerto Rico, Oct. 13, 1984.
   ``You yourselves are witnesses of the appreciation and gratitude
of the faithful when you don't get mixed up in interests of an
ideological or political nature, which are foreign to the Bible and
to the demands of your vocation,'' to priests in Medellin,
Colombia, July 5, 1986.
   ``It is sometimes claimed that dissent from the magisterium is
totally compatible with being a `good Catholic' and poses no
obstacle to the reception of the sacraments. This is a grave error
that challenges the teaching office of the bishops of the United
States and elsewhere,'' to the U.S. bishops, Los Angeles, Sept. 16,
1987.
   ``For world peace is inconceivable unless the world's leaders
come to recognize that interdependence in itself demands the
abandonment of the politics of blocs, the sacrifice of all forms of
economic, military or political imperialism and the transformation
of mutual distrust into collaboration,'' from the social encyclical
`Sollicitudo Rei Socialis,'' Feb. 19, 1988.
   ``As I stressed last year before representatives of Jewish
communities in the United States, the Jewish people has a right to
a country of its own, as any other nation has under international
law. The same, however, holds for the Palestinian people, many of
whom have become homeless and are refugees,'' to the Austrian
Jewish community, Vienna, June 24, 1988.
   ``With great distress the church has observed the illegitimate
ordination of bishops performed June 30 by Archbishop Marcel
Lefebvre. ... This act of disobedience _ which constitutes the
outright rejection of the Roman primate _constitutes a schismatic
act,'' letter to bishops, July 2, 1988.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
