<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0570</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods jumped
6 percent in August, the government reported, suggesting to
analysts that recent signs of sluggishness in the economy are
probably temporary.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that orders jumped to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $123.1 billion last month
following a huge 7.4 percent decline in July and an 8.7 percent
increase in June.
   The volatility in the month-to-month total reflects wide swings
in demand for transportation and military goods, but economists
said the underlying trend portrays a vigorous U.S. manufacturing
sector.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically-produced cars rose 6.7
percent in mid-September over the same period last year as the
effects of 1987 incentives began wearing off, automakers reported.
   Domestic automakers said Friday they sold 170,988 cars in the
Sept. 11-20 period this year, compared with 160,235 during the same
time last year.
   For a month or so, comparisons between sales during 10-day
periods this year and last year have been colored by automakers'
incentives in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance leaders of industrialized nations have
expressed satisfaction over prospects for non-inflationary world
economic growth, but Brazil's finance minister contended developing
nations were not sharing in the expansion.
   ``Despite alarms and jitters, the world economy has performed
well over the past year,'' Nigel Lawson, the British chancellor of
the exchequer, told finance chiefs Sunday at the annual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
   But finance officials from poorer nations worried they were
being left out of the gains.
   ``If conditions do not change, no basic improvement is expected
this year for the developing countries,'' said Brazil's finance
minister, Mailson Ferreira da Nobrega.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved and sent President
Reagan tightened curbs on textile, apparel and shoe imports,
inviting a pre-election trade clash with the administration but
falling short of a veto-proof margin.
   The House balked Friday at providing the two-thirds support
needed to override a presidential veto in the House.
   The bill, designed to protect U.S. industry against foreign
competition, would freeze textile and apparel imports at 1987
levels this year and limit growth to 1 percent annually starting in
January.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp stock recovered
after tumbling a day earlier when word leaked out that the company
would post third-quarter loan losses that could top $200 million.
   First Interstate stock closed up 87{ cents Friday at $49.37{ a
share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. On Thursday, it
dropped $2.50 to close at $48.50.
   Analysts had advised clients to pass over First Interstate stock
after getting early reports the company planned to set aside $180
million to cover deteriorating real estate loans at subsidiary
First Interstate Bank of Texas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese government has ordered two
Japanese trawlers confined to port following an investigation into
illegal fishing off Alaska, a U.S. State Department official said.
   ``It appears to be a reasonable punishment,'' Edward Wolfe, the
State Department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries, said Friday
of the Japanese government's action.
   The two trawlers reportedly were confined to port for illegally
entering a foreign fishing zone and for failing to maintain proper
navigation logs.
</TEXT>
