<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. says its 1988
earnings will be ``significantly lower'' than the $60 million, or
$1.50 a share, predicted by analysts.
   Control Data stock fell $1.62{ Friday to $20.62{ in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   A spokeswoman for the computer maker said earnings could be down
more than 20 percent from the estimates because of market
``softness'' in key business sectors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aggressive investment firm Coniston Partners
says it has amassed a 19 percent stake in TW Services Inc. and will
press for a meeting with management to discuss acquiring the food
services giant.
   Depending on the outcome of those discussions, the Coniston
group ``may consider making an offer for TW Services directly to
its board or to its stockholders,'' the partnership said Friday.
   TW Services, with annual revenue of about $3.5 billion, operates
the Denny's and Hardee's fast-food chains.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top policy-makers at the Federal Reserve, one
week after boosting a key interest rate, decided to make no further
efforts to tighten credit in August, according to minutes of the
discussions.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, which sets monetary policy
for the central bank, voted 10-1 at their Aug. 16 meeting to leave
credit conditions unchanged for the time being, the minutes
released Friday showed.
   The committee met again last Tuesday and many analysts believe
the Fed again decided to wait and see whether tightening moves
already undertaken would cool off the economy as desired.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has completed congressional action
on a bill that toughens requirements for the federal government to
pay its bills on time.
   The House-passed measure was approved Friday by the Senate after
senators rejected an amendment aimed at helping the government
collect some of the $83 billion it is owed.
   Sponsors of the bill said accepting the amendment, which has
little support in the House, would have jeopardized chances of
passing the bill this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British will yield an inch, but not a mile _
and don't even think about swapping their venerable pint of beer
for a half-liter.
   As a deadline nears for Britain to adopt the metric system of
the European Economic Community, the nation is preparing to defend
some vestiges of its past.
   Britain probably will be weighing in grams and measuring in
centimeters by the time Europe becomes a single market in 1992. But
officials say they want to retain indefinitely some key exceptions
like the pint and the mile.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted spotty gains in a quiet session Friday. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished up 10.67 at 2,090.68.
   The dollar finished lower against most major currencies. Gold
prices fell.
   Bond prices ended slightly lower.
   Gold futures sank to 19-month lows, cocoa prices fell further,
energy futures dropped sharply, grains and soybeans were mostly
lower, livestock and meat were mixed, and stock-index futures rose.
</TEXT>
