<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Caterpillar-Movies     09-26 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caterpillar-Movies,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earth-Moving Giant Works to Build Positive Image In Movies and
Television</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sigourney Weaver used a futuristic
fork-lift to dispatch an alien beast during a climactic fight in
the movie ``Aliens,'' it was a real-life triumph for Caterpillar
Inc.
   The image of the lifter _ which bore the Caterpillar logo _
being pushed to its limit in triumph over an evil force was
powerful enough. But the positive exposure to Caterpillar from the
box-office success of the film surprised officials of the
Peoria-based company.
   ``We had a number of people calling and writing in wanting to
buy the machine,'' said Ron Pilon, manager of Caterpillar's sales
and promotion division. ``We had to explain to people that the
machine in the movie doesn't exist.''
   The cinematic victory _ and accompanying wide public promotion
of its machines as tough and versatile _ resulted from the work of
Caterpillar's Hollywood agent.
   The company for two years has employed UPP Entertainment
Marketing of North Hollywood, Calif. to help it find scripts that
would give its equipment a high, positive profile in motion
pictures and television, and to protect itself from negative
exposure.
   ``We like to be selective so our machines don't come off as the
heavy in a movie,'' Pilon said. ``We don't want another movie like
`Killdozer.'''
   In that 1974 made-for-television movie, a thinly-disguised
Caterpillar tractor became possessed by aliens and proceeded to
wreak havoc on the residents of a small island.
   ``It was going around wiping out people,'' Pilon said. ``Of
course, we got up in arms about it because they made the machine
look like a killer. We want people to see our machines for their
contributions to society: building roads and homes and removing
piles of snow in the winter.''
   The classic movie ``Grapes of Wrath'' also made Caterpillar
officials cringe as company equipment was used to destroy a home
and came to symbolize the oppressive force that forced Dust Bowl
victims off their land.
   Caterpillar declined an opportunity for its machines to appear
in the recent Steven Spielberg movie, ``Batteries Not Included.''
   ``In that movie, the construction company was the bad guy and
Caterpillar equipment would have been used to tear down a hotel and
cafe where a bunch of old folks lived,'' said Cliff McMullen,
president of UPP Entertainment Marketing. ``They had nowhere else
to go.''
   That's typical of what movie-makers have in mind for heavy
equipment, McMullen said. And Caterpillar is the equipment of
preference, he said.
   ``That's the problem,'' McMullen said. ``We probably keep them
out of more films than we get them into. Caterpillar is a sensitive
company and doesn't want to offend the sensibilities of its target
market.''
   Although Caterpillar can't control the use of its equipment,
McMullen often dissuades negative portrayals, sometimes with
threats of legal action.
   But Caterpillar always is ready for heroic roles, such as
fighting a creature in ``Aliens,'' stopping an oil well fire on
``Dallas'' and constructing a pipeline on ``Dynasty.''
   Later this year, three large tractors will appear in the comedy
``Fugitives'' with Nick Nolte and Martin Short. In the December
television special ``A Brady Christmas,'' a Caterpillar
wheel-loader saves the day, and the Brady Bunch, from disaster at a
construction site.
   ``We have never paid anyone to use Caterpillar equipment in a
movie,'' said Don Axt of Caterpillar's advertising department.
``People think this involves big money but it really only involves
a convenience.
   ``We make it convenient or very easy for filmmakers to use
Caterpillar equipment and we usually share the costs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
