<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Tate&Lyle     09-26 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tate & Lyle,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate And Lyle To Buy U.S. Sugar Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate & Lyle PLC said Monday it has agreed to
acquire the sugar refining operations of Amstar Corp. for about
$305 million, strengthening the British company's position in the
U.S. sweetener market.
   At the same time, Tate & Lyle said it will seek a buyer for its
much-smaller sugar refining operations in Yonkers, N.Y., held by
the British company's Refined Sugars Inc. subsidiary. Tate and Lyle
said it expects proceeds from this sale to exceed $100 million.
   The Amstar sugar business, which markets under the Domino brand
name, will be jointly owned by Tate & Lyle and Redpath Industries
Ltd. through Refined Sugars Inc.
   Redpath is a publicly quoted Canadian concern which is 50.15
percent owned by Tate & Lyle. The two companies each own half of
Refined Sugars.
   ``This ... gives the Tate & Lyle group a significant position in
the U.S. cane sugar refining industry,'' said Tate & Lyle Chairman
Neil Shaw.
   Amstar, which has its headquarters in Stamford, Conn., has sugar
refineries in Brooklyn, N.Y., Baltimore and New Orleans.
   Tate & Lyle acquired U.S.-based Staley Continental, a leading
producer of corn sweeteners, in June. In 1985, it formed Western
Sugar Co. in the United States.
</TEXT>
