<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoeskyPact     09-26 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boesky Pact,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partial Settlement Reported In Boesky Litigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partial settlement will be announced this week
in a group of lawsuits against investors in Ivan F. Boesky & Co.,
the investment vehicle of the imprisoned stock speculator,
according to a report published today.
   The accord will result in a payment of $30 million to $50
million to shareholders in companies who claim they were defrauded
by Boesky, the New York Times said in a report attributed to people
involved in the suits.
   The accord is an agreement between 42 limited partners in
Boesky's defunct firm; a British enterprise once controlled by
Boesky; and shareholders of companies who claim they were
defrauded, the newspaper said.
   The pact does not include the two central defendants, Boesky
himself and his main underwriter, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the
Times said.
   ``The settlement is really a grand alliance that will make it
much easier for us to pursue Ivan Boesky and Drexel Burnham,'' a
lawyer involved in negotiations between shareholders and the Boesky
partners told the Times.
   Two years ago Boesky paid a $100 million fine to settle
government charges that he illegally traded on confidential
information. He is serving a three-year federal prison term after
admitting that he conspired to file a false statement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</TEXT>
