<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved slightly lower today in
lethargic dealings, weakened somewhat by lower bond prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials eased 1.60 to 2,089.08
in the first hour and a half of trading.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
633 down, 463 up and 536 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 33.58 million
shares as of 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts noted that the market continues to be stalled in a
narrow trading range and that activity is dominated by ``deal''
stocks.
   ``People are focusing on (companies') earnings or lack of
earnings, on takeover stocks and takeover rumors,'' said Philip
Puccio, a senior vice president at Dillon, Read & Co.
   ``It is starting to become an individual stock-picking market,''
he said. Institutional investors are content to sit on the
sidelines, which has kept trading volume depressed.
   In addition, analysts said there is some concern among investors
that economic statistics for September, although not due to be
released for several weeks, will show the economy has been
reheating. An expanding economy puts upward pressure on interest
rates.
   Meanwhile, the market ``is stalled on the upside because of
concern about interest rates and buffered on the downside because
of the enormous buying power that's around,'' said Larry Wachtel, a
first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Among actively traded issues, TW Services rose 1~ to 25}; the
investment firm Coniston Partners disclosed it holds a 19 percent
stake in the food services concern.
   Best Products, which said its board is considering the sale of
the company, jumped 4 to 19. Kroger rose \ to 55~; the supermarket
company rejected bids from the Haft family and Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co., saying it plans to proceed with a restructuring.
   Elsewhere, K Mart was off 1[ at 38]; Baxter was down ] at 17},
and Xerox was up } at 56].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off .22 at 152.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index rose .22 to 299.33.
