<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-US     09-26 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-US,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Says U.S. Trade Law Could Lead To More Protectionism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community warned
the United States Monday that a new U.S. trade law could lead to
more protectionism.
   The law ``could lead to greater recourse to unilateral measures
by the United States which would be inconsistent with the Punta del
Este declaration and with our common commitment to the multilateral
trading system,'' the 12 EEC foreign ministers said in a statement.
   The 1986 declaration in Punta del Este, Uruguay, launched a new
round of world trade talks designed to combat protectionism.
   The EEC ministers said they will monitor implementation of the
U.S. law ``very closely'' and will take ``prompt action'' if EEC
interests are threatened.
   EEC External Relations Commissioner Willy de Clercq told the
ministers that the new U.S. trade law, by increasing trade powers
for the U.S. Congress, would ``diminish the scope for discretion by
the administration.''
   He said it would ``open the door'' to lobbyists trying to
influence the U.S. administration to renege on its obligations
under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), the set of
regulations governing world trade.
   The United States and the EEC are locked in several trade
disputes at the moment.
   These include EEC objections to the use of hormones in American
beef and U.S. objections to government subsidies for Airbus, the
European aircraft consortium.
   The ministers also repeated their objections to another U.S.
trade initiative, a bill offering protection to manufacturers of
textiles, clothing and footwear.
   ``Such a development would seriously affect trade in this sector
and jeopardize the Uruguay round negotiations,'' the EEC ministers
said in their statement.
   The bill would limit increases in textile and apparel imports to
1 percent a year over their 1987 levels and freeze non-rubber shoe
imports at their 1987 level.
   Both the U.S. House and the Senate have passed the bill, but by
majorities insufficient to override a promised veto by President
Reagan. He has 10 days to sign it into law or, failing that, veto
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
