<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Open Sharply Lower; Grains Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened sharply lower today
on the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by a number of bearish
factors. Grain futures also opened lower.
   Soybeans for November delivery plunged more than 15 cents a
bushel in early trading. Analysts said prices were driven lower by
follow-through selling from Friday, weekend rains in major South
American soybean regions and harvest pressure in the United States.
   ``The opening was much weaker than anybody expected,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Midwestern corn and soybean growers had ``excellent harvesting
weather over the weekend and real good conditions are expected for
the next three days,'' Lespinasse said.
   Soybean crops in Brazil and Argentina were much improved from a
few weeks ago, although rain was still needed in northern Brazil,
he said.
   Wheat futures retreated on a lack of significant new export
business, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.22{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 2} cents lower with December at $2.83{ a bushel; oats were
2} cents to 5 cents lower with December at $2.50{ a bushel;
soybeans were 10 cents to 16} cents lower with November at $8.17 a
bushel.
   Livestock futures were higher in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange but frozen pork belly futures were mixed.
   Live cattle were .28 cent to .53 cent higher with October at
70.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .55 cent higher
with September at 79.75 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent to .55
cent higher with October at 39.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .33 cent lower to .88 cent higher with February at
51.70 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures closed mostly higher on Friday while pork
bellies declined.
</TEXT>
