<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0025 09-26 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity; closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished almost unchanged Monday on
the London Stock Exchange, as a nervous market awaited Tuesday's
key British trade report for August.
   Some participants worried that another bad trade performance
could leave the British government with no alternative but to push
up interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 0.3
point, or 0.02 percent, higher at 1,792.7, below its best level for
the day of 1,795.3 but stronger than its low of 1,789.4.
   Volume was a light 299.6 million shares, down sharply from the
396.5 million shares that changed hands Friday.
   The market remained lethargic as players awaited the British
trade numbers. The report was considered especially important after
last month's trade figures unhinged British markets with news of a
deficit more than double what private economists had expected.
   For August, market expectations call for a narrowing of
Britain's current- account deficit to between 1.2 billion pounds
and 1.7 billion pounds, or about $2 billion to $2.8 billion, from
July's 2.15 billion pounds, or $3.6 billion.
   Many market watchers said a poor trade number already has been
discounted by the market, while a better-than-expected figure might
send equities prices skyward.
</TEXT>
