<DOCNO> AP880926-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WorldBank-IMF Bjt   09-26 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-IMF, Bjt,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IMF Urges Stronger Steps on Third World Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Monetary Fund said Monday poor
countries have been hurt by the recent rise in world interest rates
and urged stronger steps to ease their staggering foreign debt
burdens.
   The policy-making arm of the IMF also called on indebted
countries to pursue policies that will spur growth and help
``restore domestic and foreign confidence.''
   The panel, made up of the finance leaders of 22 countries, said
banks should be encouraged to offer adequate refinancing to the
debtor countries and not just stretch out their payments over
longer periods.
   ``Many countries continue to face severe financing and
adjustment difficulties, which have become more severe due to the
recent increase in interest rates,'' said a statement from the
group attending the annual meeting of the IMF and its sister
agency, the World Bank. The financial organizations count 151
nations as members.
   ``More forceful actions are needed in the context of the current
cooperative, case-by-case approach to resolve these difficulties,''
the statement said.
   The ministers also said governments should not bail out
commercial banks which have made risky loans to poorer countries.
   ``There should be no official guarantees to private lenders,''
said Dutch Finance Minister H. Onno Ruding, the panel chairman.
   Finance ministers from throughout the world began a round of
talks last week in conjunction with the IMF-World Bank meeting,
which officially opens on Tuesday.
   Some 12,000 financial officials, bankers and journalists were
expected to attend the sessions.
   The officials' talks have centered mostly on prospects for the
world economy and the Third World debt.
   In its statement, the policy-making panel said, ``Growth in the
industrial countries has heen stronger than expected, world trade
has been buoyant, and inflation has been kept moderate.''
   The group offered no new proposals for the debt problem and said
it supported the current debt strategy.
   It took note of an offer from the Japanese Export-Import Bank to
make loans on easy terms to large debtor countries following
IMF-backed economic policies.
   ``Japan,'' it said, ``intends to promote growth in developing
countries and to contribute to the solution of the debt problem.''
   Japan's central bank governor, Satoshi Sumita, was expected
Tuesday to provide details of another debt plan, again to help the
larger debtors, known as the ``middle-income'' countries.
   This proposal, first discussed in June at the Toronto economic
summit of key industrialized nations, calls for the debtors to
deposit some of their international reserves with the IMF.
   The finance leaders of the United States and six other major
industrial nations over the weekend gave their final approval to a
plan to help the very poor countries, mostly in sub-Saharan Africa.
   But the big debtors, like Mexico and Brazil, also would like
some special assistance in reducing the debt burdens that have
slowed their economic development. The two countries, the
developing world's largest debtors, have debts totaling more than
$220 billion.
   In recent years, the industrial nations have followed what they
call a case-by-case approach to the debt, an approach that calls
for dealing individually with the debtors.
   The IMF has been instrumental in fashioning financial rescue
packages for heavily indebted countries. The World Bank provides
assistance to these countries for economic development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
