<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-26 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvest Pressures Soybean Futures To 16-Week Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged Monday to their
lowest close in nearly four months on the Chicago Board of Trade as
the accelerating harvest brought new supplies to the market.
   Grain futures also finished lower with oats for December and
March delivery closing down the allowable limit of 10 cents a
bushel.
   Soybeans for delivery in November plummeted more than 26 cents
to close at the day's low of $8.06 a bushel. That was the lowest
closing price for soybean futures since June 1, when soybeans for
July delivery finished at $8.01} a bushel.
   Fine harvesting weather in the Midwest over the weekend and
rains in major soybean-growing areas of Brazil and Argentina
prompted heavy selling, analysts said.
   ``The market's very much on the defensive with the harvest going
on,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Harvest pressure also weighed on the corn market while wheat
prices fell on a lack of significant new export business, analysts
said.
   The corn market ignored bullish reports that aflatoxin, a
carcinogenic fungus, had been found in some samples of corn from
grain elevators in Iowa and Indiana.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 5\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.21{ a bushel; corn was 3\
cents to 5{ cents lower with December at $2.80} a bushel; oats were
6\ cents to 10 cents lower with December at $2.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were 13 cents to 27\ cents lower with November at $8.06 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
