<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Crash-SIA     09-26 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-SIA,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Securities Industry Group President Offers Dismal Post-Crash
Review</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash-Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's leading securities industry group
offered a bleak assessment Monday of the year since the stock crash
and predicted individual investors will shun the market until they
see major reforms.
   Edward I. O'Brien, president of the Securities Industry
Association, said in a statement that although the worst fears
about the economy never materialized after the Oct. 19 collapse and
market conditions have improved in some areas, ``the overall
current environment is at best gray.''
   He said the SIA, the main trade group of Wall Street, ``believes
the near-term outlook isn't likely to improve substantially until
full investor confidence is restored in both the integrity of the
marketplace and the strength of the economy.''
   In the longer term, he said, ``lackluster equities prices will
make it more difficult for companies to raise equity funds at the
very time capital needs and reconstruction of industry are
necessary to effectively compete in the world market for goods and
services.''
   O'Brien's remarks were part of what the SIA called his overview
of events since the crash, which erased 508 points from the Dow
Jones industrial average and has continued to undermine the health
of the securities industry.
   Quoting what he called currently available data, O'Brien said
the dollar amount of common stock offerings fell 37.5 percent in
the first half of 1988 vs. the same time a year earlier. The drop
would have been sharper without the inclusion of offerings in
special investment companies called closed-end funds.
   Although prices of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues have
partly recovered from post-crash lows, they averaged only $32.80
through August 1988, well below $44 in September 1987, O'Brien said.
   Volume on the NYSE through July remained 8 percent off the 1987
average, and the drop would have been even sharper without
inclusion of volume-inflating strategies in which stocks are traded
to capture quarterly dividends, he said.
   Largely as a result of these conditions, layoffs and furloughs
in the business totaled 16,000 nationwide through the first
quarter, he said.
   O'Brien said there have been a few steps to correct problems
exposed as a result of the crash, ``but major regulatory reform
hasn't taken place.''
   As an example, he said no concerted effort has emerged to place
financial markets under one regulator, a key recommendation of a
presidential commission that examined the crash. He also said the
markets themselves have so far failed to agree on common ways to
stop or slow the impact of another panic.
   ``Failure to have these and other systems in place contributed
to the October 19 freefall; and until they are rectified, the
individual investor is likely to continue to be wary of the
marketplace,'' O'Brien concluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
