<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Block Offer for Interco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has denied Interco Inc.'s
request for a preliminary injunction against a $2.64 billion cash
tender offer for Interco by a Washington, D.C.-based investor
group, it was announced Monday.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph J. Farnan Jr. of Wilmington, Del.,
ruled against St. Louis-based Interco on Friday, according to the
investor group, Cardinal Acquisition Corp., which is headed by the
brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales.
   Interco's brands include Ethan Allen and Broyhill furniture,
London Fog outerwear, and Florsheim and Converse shoes.
   Cardinal's $70-a-share tender offer expires Friday at midnight.
Last week Interco's directors spurned a $72-a-share offer that was
conditioned on Interco's providing certain confidential information
to the bidders.
   The offer of $70 a share places a value on the company of $2.64
billion, based on Interco's 35 million outstanding shares,
currently exercisable options for 1.14 million shares, and
preferred stock convertible into 1.59 million shares.
</TEXT>
