<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market meandered lower in a slow
session Monday, weighed down by rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5.51 to 2,085.17.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
550 up, 845 down and 533 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 116.42 million
shares, down from 145.10 million Friday and the lightest total in
two weeks.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 135.37 million shares.
   Prices of long-term government bonds fell in the credit markets,
putting their yields in the 9.07 percent-9.15 percent range.
   Analysts noted that the market continues to be stalled in a
narrow trading range and that activity is dominated by ``deal''
stocks.
   In addition, brokers said there is some concern among investors
that economic statistics for September, although not due to be
released for several weeks, will show that the economy has been
reheating. An expanding economy puts upward pressure on interest
rates.
   The market ``is stalled on the upside because of concern about
interest rates and buffered on the downside because of the enormous
buying power that's around,'' said Larry Wachtel, a first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Stocks are still suffering from the after-effects of Black
Monday last Oct. 19, said Edward O'Brien, president of the
Securities Industry Association, in a statement issued as the first
anniversary of the crash approaches.
   The SIA, Wall Street's main trade group, ``believes the
near-term outlook isn't likely to improve substantially until full
investor confidence is restored in both the integrity of the
marketplace and the strength of the economy,'' the statement said.
   Among actively traded issues, TW Services rose 1\ to 24}. The
investment firm of Coniston Partners disclosed that it holds a 19
percent stake in the food services concern.
   Best Products, which said its board is considering the sale of
the company, jumped 3~ to 18~.
   Kroger rose | to 56]. The company rejected bids from the Haft
family and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., saying it plans to
proceed with a restructuring.
   Service Merchandise fell 1{ to 12] among the volume leaders in
the over-the-counter market. An investor group which had previously
expressed an interest in the company decided not to make a bid at
this time, Service Merchandise said.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $7.12 billion, or 0.27
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .42 to 151.96.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 1.00 to 308.40, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down .88 at 268.88.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slumped 2.22 to 382.75. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 298.74, down .37.
