<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-26 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains Ground; Gold Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar shook off central bank selling and
closed mostly higher Monday, reflecting traders' optimism that the
U.S. currency would remain strong.
   Gold prices rose in domestic trading after falling overseas.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $395 for a troy
ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $1.25 from late Friday's bid of
$393.75.
   At a weekend meeting in Berlin, finance ministers of the seven
industrial nations known as the Group of Seven reaffirmed their
intention to keep currency rates stable.
   But Jack Barbanel, a vice president with Gruntal & Co. Inc.,
said the meeting did not seem to influence the dollar's direction
Monday.
   Investors were reacting to positive factors including a recent
narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit and the conservative attitude
of the Federal Reserve toward interest rates, Barbanel said.
   ``The pressure is for the dollar to stay at these levels or go
higher,'' he said.
   The central banks of several nations entered foreign-exchange
markets to stem the dollar's rise, but the currency still chalked
up a gain.
   The Federal Reserve and central banks of West Germany, Britain,
France, Switzerland, Italy and Austria all intervened to sell
dollars, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.26 Japanese yen to a closing 134.73
yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 134.70 yen, and the U.S.
currency ended the day by rising to 134.535 yen in New York, up
from late Friday's 134.325.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6668 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6715 late Friday. In New
York, however, the pound edged up against the dollar, closing at
$1.6720, up from $1.6715 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8817 West German marks, up from 1.8735; 1.5910
Swiss francs, up from 1.5827; 6.4035 French francs, up from 6.3870;
1,401.37 Italian lire, up from 1,399.00; and 1.2195 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2223.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.8835 West German marks, up from 1.8750; 1.5935
Swiss francs, up from 1.5850; 6.5000 French francs, up from 6.3888;
2.1230 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1140; 1.403.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,400.50; 1.2211 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2220.
   Gold prices steadied in New York Monday after plunging through
the $400 mark last week. On the Commodity Exchange, a troy ounce of
gold closed at $395.10, up from $394.20 late Friday.
   In overseas trading, gold prices fell, but traders predicted
there would be demand for the metal in coming days.
   ``We've seen the worst, at least for the time being,'' said one
bullion dealer in Zurich, Switzerland.
   Gold fell in earlier London trading to a late bid price of
$394.50 a troy ounce, down from late Friday's $396.50, and also
declined in Zurich to $392, down from $398 late Friday.
   All financial institutions in Hong Kong were closed Monday for
the Chinese Mid-Autumn Festival holiday.
   Silver prices fell. On the Commodity Exchange, a troy ounce of
silver dipped to $6.107 from $6.167. In London trading, the metal
was bid late in the day at $6.16 a troy ounce, down from Friday's
$6.22.
