<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Carter Hawley,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailer Reports Quarterly Loss, Annual Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc. on Monday said
it lost $9 million in the final quarter of its fiscal year but
managed to post a profit for the 12-month period.
   The shortfall still was an improvement over the year-ago
quarter, when the retailer reported a loss of $188.8 million.
   Sales during the quarter ended July 30 totaled $594.5 million,
virtually unchanged from a year earlier.
   For the full year, Carter Hawley reported a profit of $17.7
million, a dramatic turnaround from a $178.7 million loss in the
previous year when the Neiman-Marcus unit was spun off to fight a
takeover attempt.
   The company reported sales in the 1988 fiscal year of $2.6
billion, compared with 1987 sales of $2.9 billion.
   The 1988 results include one-time gains of $30 million on the
sale of a shopping center and $10.1 million from an accounting
change. Those gains were partly offset by one-time charges totaling
$30.3 million for changes to operations and early payment of debt.
   The company's 1987 losses were blamed on a restructuring
undertaken to fight a takeover attempt by rival retailer The
Limited of Columbus, Ohio.
   Carter Hawley spun off its specialty stores, Nieman-Marcus,
Bergdorf Goodman and Contempo Casuals, into a separate public
company whose majority shareholder is General Cinema Corp. of
Chestnut Hill, Mass., a large Carter Hawley stockholder.
   Carter Hawley currently runs 113 department stores, including
the Broadway-Southern California, the Broadway-Southwest, Emporium
Capwell, Thalheimers and Weinstock's.
</TEXT>
