<DOCNO> AP880926-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-26 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0828</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvest Pressures Soybean Futures To Lowest Close In 16 Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged Monday to their lowest close in
nearly four months on the Chicago Board of Trade as the
accelerating harvest brought new supplies to the market.
   Grain futures also finished lower with oats for December and
March delivery closing down the allowable limit of 10 cents a
bushel.
   On other markets, sugar and cocoa futures were sharply lower;
livestock and meat futures were sharply higher; energy futures
rose; precious metals were mixed and stock-index futures weakened.
   Soybeans for delivery in November plummeted more than 26 cents
to settle at $8.06\ a bushel, the lowest settlement price for
soybean futures since June 1, when the July contract finished at
$8.01} a bushel.
   On Aug. 24, soybeans for September delivery fell to $8 a bushel
in intra-day trading but settled that day at $8.31{.
   Fine harvesting weather in the Midwest and rains in major
soybean-growing areas of Brazil and Argentina prompted heavy
selling, analysts said.
   ``The market's very much on the defensive with the harvest going
on,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   In addition to the harvest pressure, a dearth of significant
export orders has limited buying interest in soybean futures, said
Cathy Leow, an analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   ``Demand is eventually going to drive us higher, of course, but
... the longer we wait before we see some demand, the lower we're
going to go,'' she said.
   Harvest pressure also weighed on the corn market while wheat
prices fell on a lack of significant new export business, analysts
said.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 5\ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.22\ a bushel; corn was 3\ cents to 5{
cents lower with December at $2.80} a bushel; oats were 5 cents to
10 cents lower with December at $2.44{ a bushel; soybeans were 12{
cents to 28} cents lower with November at $8.06\ a bushel.
   Sugar futures prices fell dramatically on New York's Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange in a sell-off triggered by the sharp drop in
soybean futures, analysts said.
   Prices for March through October 1989 delivery skidded the
0.5-cent-a-pound daily limit while most contracts for nearer-term
delivery, which are not subject to the limit, fell even further.
   Sugar for delivery this October settled 0.5 cent lower at $9.49
a pound.
   Cocoa futures declined steeply in a continuing reaction to the
International Cocoa Organization's failure earlier this month to
devise a means of supporting prices.
   Prices are at 13-year lows and cocoa ``looks like a terminally
ill market with no cure in sight,'' said John Gambino, a technical
analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. in New York.
   Cocoa for December delivery settled $45 lower at $1,124 a metric
ton.
   Unexpectedly strong packer demand for hogs and fattened cattle
helped push some livestock futures up the 1.50-cents-a-pound daily
limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, analysts said.
   The pork market was especially strong, based on expectations
that Friday's quarterly Agriculture Department hogs-and-pigs report
will show that some producers abandoned expansion plans this year
because of the drought-driven increase in feed-grain costs, said
Chuck Levitt, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Live cattle were .65 cent to 1.50 cents higher with October at
70.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .70 cent to 1.50 cents
higher with September at 80.17 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to
1.50 cents higher with October at 40.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .50 cent higher with February at 52.10
cents a pound.
   Gold futures rose slightly on New York's Commodity Exchange
while silver posted solid declines.
   Gold settled 30 cents to $1 higher with October at $495.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to 7.5 cents lower with September at
$6.107 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures ended slightly higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in a volatile session that calmed on news that OPEC's
pricing committee had adjourned their weekend meeting in Brussels,
Belgium, with plans to meet again with the cartel's long-term
strategy committee.
   The 13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is
seeking a solution to the OPEC overproduction that has been blamed
for persistent weakness of crude oil prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 2 cents to 4 cents higher
with November at $14.20 a barrel; heating oil was unchanged to .20
cent lower with October at 40.23 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .05 cent to .31 cent higher with October at 45.25 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled .30 point lower at 271.95.

</TEXT>
