<HEAD>SmithKline Restructuring Expected At Tuesday Board Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Announcement of a major restructuring at
SmithKline Beckman Corp., whose profits have declined, could come
after a board meeting of the pharmaceutical company expected to
take place Wednesday.
   The firm announced in July it planned to cut costs and become
more efficient by restructuring its corporate staff. The firm has
refused to divulge details of the restructuring.
   Analysts and development officials who have spoken to SmithKline
executives believe the shakeup could lead to layoffs of as many as
3,000 worldwide.
   PaineWebber Inc. analyst Ron Nordmann said as many as 2,000 of
SmithKline's employees could be laid off, but cautioned that ``the
restructuring may be more far-reaching than that.''
   Analysts have said they expect the board meeting Wednesday, but
SmithKline refused to confirm the date.
   ``We just can't comment on anything right at the moment,'' a
spokesman said last week. ``We have announced that we are studying
the restructuring of the pharmaceutical business and corporate
staff, and work is continuing, but we can't say anything fruther at
this time.''
   The company said in July that it would reorganize its business
following a lackluster first-half performance in which earnings
dropped by 25 percent. The company also predicted that earnings for
the full 1988 fiscal year would be off by 25 percent as well.
   SmithKline blamed the drop in its profits on the disappointing
sales of its two top drugs _ Tagamet, an anti-ulcer drug, and
Dyazide, a drug used in the treatment of hypertension.
</TEXT>
