<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WorldBank-IMF-Violence 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-IMF-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0251,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militants Clash With Riot Police</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with demonstrators, police reported
injured, other details. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of leftist militants fought running battles
with truncheon-swinging riot police Monday night during protests
against world financial discussions, witnesses said.
   Several rioters were hauled away in police vans, and paramedics
said some protesters and police officers were injured. No figures
were given on the injuries.
   The incidents were the first serious clashes between
demonstrators and police since World Bank-International Monetary
Fund talks began in West Berlin last Thursday.
   Militants threw stones at the windows of downtown stores, banks
and cars. They dragged a small car from its parking place and used
it to block Kurfuerstendamm, the city's main boulevard.
   Police moved in with truncheons, and smashed camera equipment of
photographers taking pictures of the violence, reporters at the
scene said. The street was cleared.
   Some reports said that at one point Bavarian state police
officers used their truncheons to beat plainclothes West Berlin
police. About 2,700 police from across West Germany have been
transported to West Berlin to help the city's 6,000-strong force
during the financial talks.
   The violence broke out after about 500 radicals blocked streets
leading to the German Opera, where hundreds of people were watching
a production of Mozart's ``Magic Flute'' staged especially for
delegates and guests of the talks, witnesses said.
   Some protesters left after warnings by police but others refused
to budge, said witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Police threw a tear-gas grenade as protesters fled down a
street, they said.
   About 100 of the demonstrators ran to a square near West
Berlin's famed Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial Church where they again
fought police, then fled once more, according to the witnesses.
   Other protesters fought with police on a nearby square and at
other sites downtown, said the reporters.
   On Sunday, tens of thousands of people held a mostly peaceful
march in West Berlin to protest what they called unfair financial
policies by industrialized nations toward heavily indebted Third
World lands.
   Several peaceful demonstrations were held earlier Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
