<HEAD>A&P's Earnings Up 21 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTVALE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co. Inc. said
its second-quarter earnings jumped 21 percent from the year-earlier
quarter.
   The supermarket company reported Monday that its net income rose
to $29.4 million, or 77 cents a share, in the three months ended
Sept. 10 from $24.3 million, or 64 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter sales rose 5.8 percent, to $2.3 billion.
   James Wood, A&P's chairman and chief executive officer, said he
was pleased with the continued positive earnings trend.
   The company, which has had some financial problems in recent
years, opened nine new stores in the first half of 1988, including
several ``upscale'' markets in high-income areas.
   At the same time, Wood said, A&P closed 22 older, money-losing
stores.
   ``We expect to open an additional 20 to 25 new stores and
remodel or expand another 60 units during the last half of the
fiscal year,'' he said.
   In the first half of A&P's fiscal year, net income jumped 23.4
percent _ to $67.5 million, or $1.77 a share, from $54.7 million,
or $1.44 a share.
   First-half sales rose 4.5 percent, to $5.3 billion from $5.1
billion.
   The company now has 1,170 supermarkets in 25 states and Canada
under the trade names of A&P, Super Fresh, Food Emporium, Kohl's,
Dominion and Waldbaum's.
</TEXT>
