<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Coca-ColaTrial     09-26 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Coca-Cola Trial,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins Bottlers' Federal Court Suit Against Coca-Cola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. hurt its independent
bottlers when it changed its syrup formula and did not pass on the
savings, a bottler testified Monday as trial began in a federal
court suit against the soft-drink manufacturer.
   The U.S. District Court trial, which is expected to take five
months, involves 24 independent bottlers seeking to have the court
uphold a 1921 pact tying the price they pay for Coca-Cola syrup to
the cost of sugar.
   If successful, the bottlers could realize up to $35 million in
damages.
   William B. Schmidt of Elizabethtown, Ky., who filed the lawsuit,
testified that Coke began substituting high-fructose corn syrup for
sucrose as a sweetener in 1980 without passing the savings on to
bottlers.
   Schmidt, whose grandfather established the fifth Coke bottling
plant in the United States, said the changes made it difficult for
him to compete with other major brands, such as Pepsi Cola.
   ``The company said they'd go to a 50-50 sugar-fructose syrup,''
Schmidt testified. ``The problem was if Coke went to fructose, the
cost decreases. Unless the decreased cost is passed on to the
bottler then competitors would also add fructose and be able to
charge less.''
   Jane F. Vehko, an attorney who argued for the bottlers, alleged
during opening arguments Monday that Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
``broke its promise'' to use sugar as a sweetener, and when it
changed to a cheaper sweetener refused to pass the savings on the
bottlers.
   Frank C. Jones, Coke's attorney, argued the bottlers are not
entitled to any monetary relief.
   ``The bottlers never contended they had a veto right'' to a
change in ingredients in the syrup under the 1921 pact, Jones said.
   He said in 1971 and 1974, Coke changed the caffeine content in
its product without consulting the bottlers, and there were no
complaints from the bottlers.
   ``It's absurd to think (any bottler) would have the power to
veto a sweetener change,'' Jones said.
</TEXT>
